her friends at home.

236
00:00:22,267 --> 00:00:23,667
These, however, with one
exception, were not portraits.

237
00:00:23,667 --> 00:00:25,667
They were views of scenery and of cattle
roundups, and other scenes

238
00:00:25,667 --> 00:00:27,369
characteristic of ranch life.

239
00:00:27,369 --> 00:00:28,769
Of young men she had in her possession
several photographs,

240
00:00:28,769 --> 00:00:29,660
and all but one of these she
had left behind her.

241
00:00:29,660 --> 00:00:30,561
Her aunt’s penetration had in a way
mesmerized the girl;

242
00:00:30,561 --> 00:00:32,481
she rose obediently and sought that
picture of the Virginian.

243
00:00:32,481 --> 00:00:34,201
It was full length, displaying him in all
his cowboy trappings⁠—the leathern

244
00:00:34,201 --> 00:00:36,701
chaps, the belt and pistol,
and in his hand a coil of rope.

245
00:00:36,701 --> 00:00:37,581
Not one of her family had seen it,
or suspected its existence.

246
00:00:37,581 --> 00:00:38,901
She now brought it downstairs and placed
it in her aunt’s hand.

247
00:00:38,901 --> 00:00:38,901
“Mercy!”

248
00:00:38,901 --> 00:00:39,286
cried the old lady.

249
00:00:39,286 --> 00:00:41,172
Molly was silent, but
her eye grew warlike.

250
00:00:41,172 --> 00:00:44,205
“Is that the way⁠—” began the aunt.

251
00:00:44,205 --> 00:00:44,285
“Mercy!”

252
00:00:44,285 --> 00:00:45,903
she murmured; and she sat
staring at the picture.

253
00:00:45,903 --> 00:00:47,130
Molly remained silent.

254
00:00:47,130 --> 00:00:48,748
Her aunt looked slowly up at her.

255
00:00:48,748 --> 00:00:50,722
“Has a man like that presumed⁠—”

256
00:00:50,722 --> 00:00:52,095
“He’s not a bit like that.

257
00:00:52,095 --> 00:00:55,743
Yes, he’s exactly like that,” said Molly.

258
00:00:55,743 --> 00:00:58,296
And she would have snatched the
photograph away, but

259
00:00:58,296 --> 00:00:59,794
her aunt retained it.

260
00:00:59,794 --> 00:01:04,219
“Well,” she said, “I suppose there are
days when he does not kill people.”

261
00:01:04,219 --> 00:01:05,638
“He never killed anybody!”

262
00:01:05,638 --> 00:01:06,778
And Molly laughed.

263
00:01:06,778 --> 00:01:10,422
“Are you seriously⁠—” said the old lady.

264
00:01:10,422 --> -1:59:59,000
“I almost might⁠—at times

265
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
.

266
00:01:12,978 --> 00:01:14,444
He is perfectly splendid.”

267
00:01:14,444 --> 00:01:18,395
“My dear, you have fallen in
love with his clothes.”

268
00:01:18,395 --> 00:01:21,706
“It’s not his clothes.

269
00:01:21,706 --> 00:01:23,184
And I’m not in love.

270
00:01:23,184 --> 00:01:24,697
He often wears others.

271
00:01:24,697 --> 00:01:26,774
He wears a white collar like anybody.”

272
00:01:26,774 --> 00:01:29,784
“Then that would be a more suitable way
to be photographed, I think.

273
00:01:29,784 --> 00:01:31,829
He couldn’t go round like that here.

274
00:01:31,829 --> 00:01:33,792
I could not receive him myself.”

275
00:01:33,792 --> 00:01:35,595
“He’d never think of such a thing.

276
00:01:35,595 --> 00:01:39,142
Why, you talk as if he were a savage.”

277
00:01:39,142 --> 00:01:42,342
The old lady studied the picture
closely for a minute.

278
00:01:42,342 --> 00:01:46,157
“I think it is a good
face,” she finally remarked.

279
00:01:46,157 --> 00:01:48,445
“Is the fellow as handsome
as that, my dear?”

280
00:01:48,445 --> 00:01:50,673
More so, Molly thought.

281
00:01:50,673 --> 00:01:53,938
And who was he, and what
were his prospects?

282
00:01:53,938 --> 00:01:56,353
were the aunt’s next inquiries.

283
00:01:56,353 --> 00:02:00,320
She shook her head at the answers which
she received; and she also shook her

284
00:02:00,320 --> 00:02:05,405
head over her niece’s emphatic denial
that her heart was lost to this man.

285
00:02:05,405 --> 00:02:09,034
But when their parting came,
the old lady said:⁠—

286
00:02:09,034 --> 00:02:11,514
“God bless you and keep you, my dear.

287
00:02:11,514 --> 00:02:13,140
I’ll not try to manage you.

288
00:02:13,140 --> 00:02:17,111
They managed me⁠—” A sigh spoke the
rest of this sentence.

289
00:02:17,111 --> 00:02:21,265
“But I’m not worried about you⁠—at
least, not very much.

290
00:02:21,265 --> 00:02:24,876
You have never done anything that was not
worthy of the Starks.

291
00:02:24,876 --> 00:02:28,876
And if you’re going to take him,
do it before I die so that I can bid him

292
00:02:28,876 --> 00:02:30,212
welcome for your sake.

293
00:02:30,212 --> -1:59:59,000
God bless you, my dear.

294
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

295
00:02:32,476 --> 00:02:36,408
And after the girl had gone back to
Bennington, the great-aunt had this

296
00:02:36,408 --> 00:02:38,302
thought: “She is like us all.

297
00:02:38,302 --> 00:02:40,109
She wants a man that is a man.”

298
00:02:40,109 --> 00:02:44,946
Nor did the old lady breathe her
knowledge to any member of the family.

299
00:02:44,946 --> 00:02:47,511
For she was a loyal spirit,
and her girl’s confidence

300
00:02:47,511 --> 00:02:48,676
was sacred to her.

301
00:02:48,676 --> 00:02:53,966
“Besides,” she reflected,
“if even I can do nothing with her,

302
00:02:53,966 --> 00:02:55,829
what a mess they’d make of it!

303
00:02:55,829 --> 00:02:58,651
We should hear of her elopement next.”

304
00:02:58,651 --> 00:03:04,798
So Molly’s immediate family never saw
that photograph, and never heard a word

305
00:03:04,798 --> 00:03:06,900
from her upon this subject.

306
00:03:06,900 --> 00:03:11,412
But on the day that she left for Bear
Creek, as they sat missing her and

307
00:03:11,412 --> 00:03:14,658
discussing her visit in the evening,
Mrs. Bell observed: “Mother,

308
00:03:14,658 --> 00:03:17,569
how did you think she was?”⁠—“I never
saw her better, Sarah.

309
00:03:17,569 --> 00:03:23,195
That horrible place seems to agree with
her.”⁠—“Oh, yes, agree.

310
00:03:23,195 --> 00:03:28,253
It seemed to me⁠—”⁠—“Well?”⁠—“Oh,
just somehow that she was thinking.”

311
00:03:28,253 --> 00:03:30,987
⁠—“Thinking?”⁠—“Well,
I believe she has something on her

312
00:03:30,987 --> 00:03:34,158
mind.”⁠—“You mean a man,”
said Andrew Bell.⁠—“A man,

313
00:03:34,158 --> 00:03:38,198
Andrew?”⁠—“Yes, Mrs. Wood,
that’s what Sarah always means.”

314
00:03:38,198 --> 00:03:42,023
It may be mentioned that Sarah’s surmises
did not greatly contribute

315
00:03:42,023 --> 00:03:43,892
to her mother’s happiness.

316
00:03:43,892 --> 00:03:48,811
And rumor is so strange a thing that
presently from the malicious outside air

317
00:03:48,811 --> 00:03:52,776
came a vague and dreadful word⁠—one of
those words that cannot be

318
00:03:52,776 --> 00:03:54,251
traced to its source.

319
00:03:54,251 --> 00:03:58,091
Somebody said to Andrew Bell that they
heard Miss Molly Wood was engaged

320
00:03:58,091 --> 00:03:59,248
to marry a rustler.

321
00:03:59,248 --> 00:04:00,731
“Heavens, Andrew!”

322
00:04:00,731 --> 00:04:02,983
said his wife; “what is a rustler?”

323
00:04:02,983 --> 00:04:06,653
It was not in any dictionary,
and current translations

324
00:04:06,653 --> 00:04:08,515
of it were inconsistent.

325
00:04:08,515 --> 00:04:11,853
A man at Hoosic Falls said that he had
passed through Cheyenne,

326
00:04:11,853 --> 00:04:14,973
and heard the term applied in a
complimentary way to people who

327
00:04:14,973 --> 00:04:16,333
were alive and pushing.

328
00:04:16,333 --> 00:04:19,973
Another man had always supposed it meant
some kind of horse.

329
00:04:19,973 --> 00:04:24,431
But the most alarming version of all was
that a rustler was a cattle thief.

330
00:04:24,431 --> 00:04:27,731
Now the truth is that all
these meanings were right.

331
00:04:27,731 --> 00:04:31,744
The word ran a sort of progress in the
cattle country, gathering many

332
00:04:31,744 --> 00:04:33,042
meanings as it went.

333
00:04:33,042 --> 00:04:37,064
It gathered more, however, in Bennington.

334
00:04:37,064 --> 00:04:43,352
In a very few days, gossip had it that
Molly was engaged to a gambler,

335
00:04:43,352 --> 00:04:50,732
a gold miner, an escaped stage robber,
and a Mexican bandit;

336
00:04:50,732 --> 00:04:53,976
while Mrs. Flynt feared she
had married a Mormon.

337
00:04:53,976 --> 00:04:58,674
Along Bear Creek, however,
Molly and her “rustler” took a ride

338
00:04:58,674 --> 00:05:00,453
soon after her return.

339
00:05:00,453 --> 00:05:05,397
They were neither married nor engaged,
and she was telling him about Vermont.

340
00:05:05,397 --> 00:05:07,921
“I never was there,” said he.

341
00:05:07,921 --> 00:05:10,539
“Never happened to strike
in that direction.”

342
00:05:10,539 --> 00:05:12,377
“What decided your direction?”

343
00:05:12,377 --> 00:05:14,839
“Oh, looking for chances.

344
00:05:14,839 --> 00:05:19,782
I reckon I must have been more ambitious
than my brothers⁠—or more restless.

345
00:05:19,782 --> 00:05:21,476
They stayed around on farms.

346
00:05:21,476 --> 00:05:22,939
But I got out.

347
00:05:22,939 --> 00:05:26,701
When I went back again six years
afterward, I was twenty.

348
00:05:26,701 --> 00:05:29,633
They was talking about
the same old things.

349
00:05:29,633 --> 00:05:34,603
Men of twenty-five and thirty⁠—yet just
sittin’ and talkin’ about

350
00:05:34,603 --> 00:05:36,156
the same old things.

351
00:05:36,156 --> 00:05:40,899
I told my mother about what I’d seen here
and there, and she liked it,

352
00:05:40,899 --> 00:05:42,198
right to her death.

353
00:05:42,198 --> 00:05:46,388
But the others⁠—well,
when I found this whole world was hawgs

354
00:05:46,388 --> 00:05:50,308
and turkeys to them,
with a little gunnin’ afteh small game

355
00:05:50,308 --> 00:05:56,390
throwed in, I put on my hat one mawnin’
and told ’em maybe when I was fifty I’d

356
00:05:56,390 --> 00:06:00,407
look in on ’em again to see if they’d
got any new subjects.

357
00:06:00,407 --> 00:06:01,629
But they’ll never.

358
00:06:01,629 --> 00:06:04,908
My brothers don’t seem to want chances.”

359
00:06:04,908 --> 00:06:07,875
“You have lost a good
many yourself,” said Molly.

360
00:06:07,875 --> 00:06:09,076
“That’s correct.”

361
00:06:09,076 --> 00:06:13,103
“And yet,” said she, “sometimes I think
you know a great deal more

362
00:06:13,103 --> 00:06:15,030
than I ever shall.”

363
00:06:15,030 --> 00:06:19,391
“Why, of course I do,”
said he, quite simply.

364
00:06:19,391 --> 00:06:22,802
“I have earned my living
since I was fourteen.

365
00:06:22,802 --> 00:06:26,316
And that’s from old Mexico
to British Columbia.

366
00:06:26,316 --> 00:06:29,020
I have never stolen or begged a cent.

367
00:06:29,020 --> 00:06:31,125
I’d not want yu’ to know what I know.”

368
00:06:31,125 --> 00:06:34,108
She was looking at him,
half listening and half thinking

369
00:06:34,108 --> 00:06:35,148
of her great-aunt.

370
00:06:35,148 --> 00:06:38,548
“I am not losing chances
any more,” he continued.

371
00:06:38,548 --> 00:06:40,712
“And you are the best I’ve got.”

372
00:06:40,712 --> 00:06:44,428
She was not sorry to have Georgie Taylor
come galloping along at this

373
00:06:44,428 --> 00:06:45,863
moment and join them.

374
00:06:45,863 --> 00:06:49,246
But the Virginian swore
profanely under his breath.

375
00:06:49,246 --> 00:06:52,708
And on this ride nothing more happened.

376
00:06:52,708 --> 00:06:54,151
CHAPTER XXIII

377
00:06:54,151 --> 00:06:55,491
Various Points

378
00:06:55,491 --> 00:06:58,522
Love had been snowbound for many weeks.

379
00:06:58,522 --> 00:07:03,353
Before this imprisonment its course had
run neither smooth nor rough,

380
00:07:03,353 --> 00:07:07,584
so far as eye could see;
it had run either not at all,

381
00:07:07,584 --> 00:07:10,842
or, as an undercurrent,
deep out of sight.

382
00:07:10,842 --> 00:07:16,659
In their rides, in their talks,
love had been dumb, as to spoken words

383
00:07:16,659 --> 00:07:20,040
at least; for the Virginian had set
himself a heavy task of

384
00:07:20,040 --> 00:07:21,733
silence and of patience.

385
00:07:21,733 --> 00:07:27,213
Then, where winter barred his visits to
Bear Creek, and there was for the while

386
00:07:27,213 --> 00:07:33,537
no ranch work or responsibility to fill
his thoughts and blood with action,

387
00:07:33,537 --> 00:07:36,178
he set himself a task much lighter.

388
00:07:36,178 --> 00:07:40,236
Often, instead of Shakespeare and
fiction, school books lay open on his

389
00:07:40,236 --> 00:07:43,999
cabin table; and penmanship and spelling
helped the hours to pass.

390
00:07:43,999 --> 00:07:49,329
Many sheets of paper did he fill with
various exercises, and Mrs. Henry gave

391
00:07:49,329 --> 00:07:53,680
him her assistance in
advice and corrections.

392
00:07:53,680 --> 00:07:57,508
“I shall presently be in love with him
myself,” she told the Judge.

393
00:07:57,508 --> 00:07:59,994
“And it’s time for you to become anxious.”

394
00:07:59,994 --> 00:08:02,835
“I am perfectly safe,” he retorted.

395
00:08:02,835 --> 00:08:05,026
“There’s only one woman for him any more.”

396
00:08:05,026 --> 00:08:08,268
“She is not good enough for
him,” declared Mrs. Henry.

397
00:08:08,268 --> 00:08:09,710
“But he’ll never see that.”

398
00:08:09,710 --> 00:08:13,437
So the snow fell, the world froze,
and the spelling-books

399
00:08:13,437 --> 00:08:15,274
and exercises went on.

400
00:08:15,274 --> 00:08:19,850
But this was not the only case of
education which was progressing at the

401
00:08:19,850 --> 00:08:23,345
Sunk Creek Ranch while
love was snowbound.

402
00:08:23,345 --> 00:08:28,143
One morning Scipio le Moyne entered the
Virginian’s sitting room⁠—that apartment

403
00:08:28,143 --> 00:08:32,104
where Dr. MacBride had wrestled with sin
so courageously all night.

404
00:08:32,104 --> 00:08:34,451
The Virginian sat at his desk.

405
00:08:34,451 --> 00:08:38,243
Open books lay around him;
a half-finished piece of writing was

406
00:08:38,243 --> 00:08:41,403
beneath his fist; his fingers
were coated with ink.

407
00:08:41,403 --> 00:08:45,606
Education enveloped him, it may be said.

408
00:08:45,606 --> 00:08:47,806
But there was none in his eye.

409
00:08:47,806 --> 00:08:52,725
That was upon the window,
looking far across the cold plain.

410
00:08:52,725 --> 00:08:56,296
The foreman did not move when Scipio came
in, and this humorous

411
00:08:56,296 --> 00:09:00,219
spirit smiled to himself.

412
00:09:00,219 --> 00:09:07,147
“It’s Bear Creek he’s havin’ a
vision of,” he concluded.

413
00:09:07,147 --> 00:09:11,492
But he knew instantly that
this was not so.

414
00:09:11,492 --> 00:09:16,030
The Virginian was looking at something
real, and Scipio went to the window

415
00:09:16,030 --> 00:09:17,243
to see for himself.

416
00:09:17,243 --> 00:09:22,710
“Well,” he said, having seen,
“when is he going to leave us?”

417
00:09:22,710 --> 00:09:26,885
The foreman continued looking at
two horsemen riding together.

418
00:09:26,885 --> 00:09:31,355
Their shapes, small in the distance,
showed black against

419
00:09:31,355 --> 00:09:32,976
the universal whiteness.

420
00:09:32,976 --> 00:09:35,959
“When d’ yu’ figure he’ll leave us?”

421
00:09:35,959 --> 00:09:37,439
repeated Scipio.

422
00:09:37,439 --> 00:09:41,572
“He,” murmured the Virginian,
always watching the distant

423
00:09:41,572 --> 00:09:43,372
horsemen; and again, “he.”

424
00:09:43,372 --> 00:09:46,917
Scipio sprawled down,
familiarly, across a chair.

425
00:09:46,917 --> 00:09:50,912
He and the Virginian had come to know
each other very well since that

426
00:09:50,912 --> 00:09:53,000
first meeting at Medora.

427
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:57,352
They were birds many of whose feathers
were the same, and the Virginian often

428
00:09:57,352 --> 00:09:59,823
talked to Scipio without reserve.

429
00:09:59,823 --> 00:10:06,655
Consequently, Scipio now understood those
two syllables that the Virginian had

430
00:10:06,655 --> 00:10:11,021
pronounced precisely as though the
sentences which lay between them

431
00:10:11,021 --> 00:10:12,961
had been fully expressed.

432
00:10:12,961 --> 00:10:14,921
“Hm,” he remarked.

433
00:10:14,921 --> 00:10:18,914
“Well, one will be a gain,
and the other won’t be no loss.”

434
00:10:18,914 --> -1:59:59,000
“Poor Shorty

435
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
!”

436
00:10:20,540 --> 00:10:21,614
said the Virginian.

437
00:10:21,614 --> 00:10:22,964
“Poor fool!”

438
00:10:22,964 --> 00:10:25,402
Scipio was less compassionate.

439
00:10:25,402 --> 00:10:29,177
“No,” he persisted, “I
ain’t sorry for him.

440
00:10:29,177 --> -1:59:59,000
Any man old enough to have hair on his
face ought to see through Trampas.

441
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

442
00:10:34,696 --> 00:10:40,441
The Virginian looked out of the window
again, and watched Shorty and Trampas as

443
00:10:40,441 --> 00:10:42,132
they rode in the distance.

444
00:10:42,132 --> 00:10:46,485
“Shorty is kind to animals,” he said.

445
00:10:46,485 --> 00:10:51,109
“He has gentled that hawss Pedro he
bought with his first money.

446
00:10:51,109 --> 00:10:53,414
Gentled him wonderful.

447
00:10:53,414 --> 00:10:57,261
When a man is kind to dumb animals,
I always say he had got

448
00:10:57,261 --> 00:10:58,562
some good in him.”

449
00:10:58,562 --> 00:11:01,453
“Yes,” Scipio reluctantly admitted.

450
00:11:01,453 --> 00:11:02,213
“Yes.

451
00:11:02,213 --> 00:11:04,292
But I always did hate a fool.”

452
00:11:04,292 --> 00:11:08,405
“This hyeh is a mighty cruel
country,” pursued the Virginian.

453
00:11:08,405 --> 00:11:11,169
“To animals that is.

454
00:11:11,169 --> 00:11:12,655
Think of it!

455
00:11:12,655 --> 00:11:16,157
Think what we do to hundreds an’
thousands of little calves!

456
00:11:16,157 --> 00:11:22,052
Throw ’em down, brand ’em,
cut ’em, ear mark ’em,

457
00:11:22,052 --> 00:11:24,394
turn ’em loose, and on to the next.

458
00:11:24,394 --> 00:11:26,968
It has got to be, of course.

459
00:11:26,968 --> 00:11:28,456
But I say this.

460
00:11:28,456 --> 00:11:34,900
If a man can go jammin’ hot irons on to
little calves and slicin’ pieces off ’em

461
00:11:34,900 --> 00:11:39,592
with his knife, and live along,
keepin’ a kindness for animals in his

462
00:11:39,592 --> 00:11:41,378
heart, he has got some good in him.

463
00:11:41,378 --> 00:11:43,050
And that’s what Shorty has got.

464
00:11:43,050 --> 00:11:47,637
But he is lettin’ Trampas get a hold of
him, and both of them will leave us.”

465
00:11:47,637 --> 00:11:51,423
And the Virginian looked out across the
huge winter whiteness again.

466
00:11:51,423 --> 00:11:55,539
But the riders had now
vanished behind some foothills.

467
00:11:55,539 --> 00:11:58,359
Scipio sat silent.

468
00:11:58,359 --> 00:12:01,887
He had never put these thoughts about men
and animals to himself,

469
00:12:01,887 --> 00:12:05,365
and when they were put to him,
he saw that they were true.

470
00:12:05,365 --> 00:12:08,322
“Queer,” he observed finally.

471
00:12:08,322 --> 00:12:08,708
“What?”

472
00:12:08,708 --> 00:12:10,646
“Everything.”

473
00:12:10,646 --> 00:12:15,487
“Nothing’s queer,” stated the Virginian,
“except marriage and lightning.

474
00:12:15,487 --> -1:59:59,000
Them two occurrences can still give me
a sensation of surprise.

475
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

476
00:12:20,421 --> 00:12:23,894
“All the same it is queer,”
Scipio insisted.

477
00:12:23,894 --> 00:12:26,113
“Well, let her go at me.”

478
00:12:26,113 --> 00:12:27,654
“Why, Trampas.

479
00:12:27,654 --> 00:12:28,960
He done you dirt.

480
00:12:28,960 --> 00:12:30,511
You pass that over.

481
00:12:30,511 --> 00:12:34,387
You could have fired him,
but you let him stay and keep his job.

482
00:12:34,387 --> 00:12:36,296
That’s goodness.

483
00:12:36,296 --> 00:12:39,316
And badness is resultin’
from it, straight.

484
00:12:39,316 --> 00:12:41,978
Badness right from goodness.”

485
00:12:41,978 --> 00:12:45,858
“You’re off the trail a whole
lot,” said the Virginian.

486
00:12:45,858 --> 00:12:47,482
“Which side am I off, then?”

487
00:12:47,482 --> 00:12:51,245
“North, south, east, and west.

488
00:12:51,245 --> 00:12:52,565
First point.

489
00:12:52,565 --> 00:12:56,665
I didn’t expect to do Trampas any good by
not killin’ him, which I came pretty

490
00:12:56,665 --> 00:12:58,256
near doin’ three times.

491
00:12:58,256 --> 00:13:03,328
Nor I didn’t expect to do Trampas any
good by lettin’ him keep his job.

492
00:13:03,328 --> 00:13:06,038
But I am foreman of this ranch.

493
00:13:06,038 --> 00:13:12,136
And I can sit and tell all men to their
face: ‘I was above that meanness.’

494
00:13:12,136 --> 00:13:16,071
Point two: it ain’t any goodness,
it is Trampas that badness

495
00:13:16,071 --> 00:13:16,651
has resulted from.

496
00:13:16,651 --> 00:13:18,451
Put him anywhere and it will be the same.

497
00:13:18,451 --> 00:13:19,771
Put him under my eye,
and I can follow his

498
00:13:19,771 --> 00:13:20,411
moves a little, anyway.

499
00:13:20,411 --> 00:13:22,532
You have noticed, maybe,
that since you and I run on to that dead

500
00:13:22,532 --> 00:13:27,033
Polled Angus cow, that was still warm
when we got to her, we have found no

501
00:13:27,033 --> 00:13:28,633
more cows dead of sudden death.

502
00:13:28,633 --> 00:13:33,634
We came mighty close to catchin’ whoever
it was that killed that cow and ran her

503
00:13:33,634 --> 00:13:35,951
calf off to his own bunch.

504
00:13:35,951 --> 00:13:38,014
He wasn’t ten minutes ahead of us.

505
00:13:38,014 --> 00:13:42,585
We can prove nothin’; and he knows that
just as well as we do.

506
00:13:42,585 --> 00:13:47,158
But our cows have all quit
dyin’ of sudden death.

507
00:13:47,158 --> 00:13:50,490
And Trampas he’s gettin’ ready for
a change of residence.

508
00:13:50,490 --> 00:13:54,038
As soon as all the outfits begin hirin’
new hands in the spring,

509
00:13:54,038 --> 00:13:56,814
Trampas will leave us and take a job
with some of them.

510
00:13:56,814 --> 00:13:59,979
And maybe our cows’ll commence gettin’
killed again, and we’ll have to take

511
00:13:59,979 --> 00:14:02,580
steps that will be more emphatic⁠—
maybe.”

512
00:14:02,580 --> 00:14:03,885
Scipio meditated.

513
00:14:03,885 --> 00:14:07,023
“I wonder what killin’ a man feels like?”

514
00:14:07,023 --> 00:14:08,012
he said.

515
00:14:08,012 --> 00:14:12,744
“Why, nothing to bother yu’⁠—when he’d
ought to have been killed.

516
00:14:12,744 --> 00:14:16,898
Next point: Trampas he’ll take Shorty
with him, which is certainly

517
00:14:16,898 --> 00:14:18,090
bad for Shorty.

518
00:14:18,090 --> 00:14:21,760
But it’s me that has kept Shorty out of
harm’s way this long.

519
00:14:21,760 --> 00:14:25,149
If I had fired Trampas,
he’d have worked Shorty into

520
00:14:25,149 --> 00:14:27,259
dissatisfaction that much sooner.”

521
00:14:27,259 --> 00:14:28,956
Scipio meditated again.

522
00:14:28,956 --> 00:14:32,727
“I knowed Trampas would pull
his freight,” he said.

523
00:14:32,727 --> 00:14:34,429
“But I didn’t think of Shorty.

524
00:14:34,429 --> 00:14:35,819
What makes you think it?”

525
00:14:35,819 --> 00:14:38,107
“He asked me for a raise.”

526
00:14:38,107 --> 00:14:41,064
“He ain’t worth the pay he’s getting now.”

527
00:14:41,064 --> 00:14:43,261
“Trampas has told him different.”

528
00:14:43,261 --> 00:14:47,532
“When a man ain’t got no ideas of his
own,” said Scipio, “he’d ought to be

529
00:14:47,532 --> 00:14:50,252
kind o’ careful who he borrows ’em
from.”

530
00:14:50,252 --> 00:14:51,052
“That’s mighty correct,”
said the Virginian.

531
00:14:51,052 --> 00:14:51,892
“Poor Shorty!

532
00:14:51,892 --> 00:14:52,372
He has told me about his life.

533
00:14:52,372 --> 00:14:52,749
It is sorrowful.

534
00:14:52,749 --> 00:14:54,499
And he will never get wise.

535
00:14:54,499 --> 00:14:59,035
It was too late for him to get wise
when he was born.

536
00:14:59,035 --> 00:15:01,798
D’ yu’ know why he’s after higher wages?

537
00:15:01,798 --> -1:59:59,000
He sends most all his money East.

538
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

539
00:15:04,077 --> 00:15:07,435
“I don’t see what Trampas wants
him for,” said Scipio.

540
00:15:07,435 --> 00:15:10,137
“Oh, a handy tool some day.”

541
00:15:10,137 --> 00:15:12,229
“Not very handy,” said Scipio.

542
00:15:12,229 --> 00:15:15,727
“Well, Trampas is aimin’ to train him.

543
00:15:15,727 --> 00:15:20,049
Yu’ see, supposin’ yu’ were figuring to
turn professional thief⁠—yu’d be lookin’

544
00:15:20,049 --> 00:15:23,769
around for a nice young trustful
accomplice to take all the punishment

545
00:15:23,769 --> -1:59:59,000
and let you take the rest.

546
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

547
00:15:26,089 --> 00:15:27,495
“No such thing!”

548
00:15:27,495 --> 00:15:30,385
cried Scipio, angrily.

549
00:15:30,385 --> 00:15:31,582
“I’m no shirker.”

550
00:15:31,582 --> 00:15:35,382
And then, perceiving the Virginian’s
expression, he broke out laughing.

551
00:15:35,382 --> 00:15:40,769
“Well,” he exclaimed,
“yu’ fooled me that time.”

552
00:15:40,769 --> 00:15:41,945
“Looks that way.

553
00:15:41,945 --> 00:15:45,090
But I do mean it about Trampas.”

554
00:15:45,090 --> 00:15:50,421
Presently Scipio rose,
and noticed the half-finished exercise

555
00:15:50,421 --> 00:15:52,998
upon the Virginian’s desk.

556
00:15:52,998 --> 00:15:56,092
“Trampas is a rolling stone,” he said.

557
00:15:56,092 --> 00:15:59,132
“A rolling piece of mud,”
corrected the Virginian.

558
00:15:59,132 --> 00:15:59,917
“Mud!

559
00:15:59,917 --> 00:16:01,492
That’s right.

560
00:16:01,492 --> 00:16:03,559
I’m a rolling stone.

561
00:16:03,559 --> 00:16:05,582
Sometimes I’d most like to quit being.”

562
00:16:05,582 --> 00:16:07,666
“That’s easy done,” said the Virginian.

563
00:16:07,666 --> 00:16:11,265
“No doubt, when yu’ve found the moss
yu’ want to gather.”

564
00:16:11,265 --> 00:16:15,292
As Scipio glanced at the school books
again, a sparkle lurked in

565
00:16:15,292 --> 00:16:16,666
his bleached blue eye.

566
00:16:16,666 --> 00:16:18,849
“I can cipher some,” he said.

567
00:16:18,849 --> 00:16:21,737
“But I expect I’ve got my
own notions about spelling.”

568
00:16:21,737 --> 00:16:26,265
“I retain a few private ideas that way
myself,” remarked the Virginian,

569
00:16:26,265 --> 00:16:29,564
innocently; and Scipio’s
sparkle gathered light.

570
00:16:29,564 --> 00:16:33,922
“As to my geography,”
he pursued, “that’s away out

571
00:16:33,922 --> 00:16:36,137
loose in the brush.

572
00:16:36,137 --> 00:16:38,777
Is Bennington the capital of Vermont?

573
00:16:38,777 --> 00:16:42,849
And how d’ yu’ spell bridegroom?”

574
00:16:42,849 --> 00:16:44,190
“Last point!”

575
00:16:44,190 --> 00:16:47,402
shouted the Virginian,
letting a book fly after him:

576
00:16:47,402 --> 00:16:51,764
“don’t let badness and goodness worry
yu’, for yu’ll never be a judge of

577
00:16:51,764 --> 00:16:52,111
them.”

578
00:16:52,111 --> 00:16:55,346
But Scipio had dodged the
book, and was gone.

579
00:16:55,346 --> 00:17:00,017
As he went his way, he said to himself,
“All the same, it must pay to

580
00:17:00,017 --> 00:17:01,752
fall regular in love.”

581
00:17:01,752 --> 00:17:08,561
At the bunk house that afternoon it was
observed that he was unusually silent.

582
00:17:08,561 --> 00:17:14,042
His exit from the foreman’s cabin had let
in a breath of winter so chill that the

583
00:17:14,042 --> 00:17:19,438
Virginian went to see his thermometer,
a Christmas present from Mrs. Henry.

584
00:17:19,438 --> 00:17:22,135
It registered twenty below zero.

585
00:17:22,135 --> 00:17:26,836
After reviving the fire to a white blaze,
the foreman sat thinking over the story

586
00:17:26,836 --> 00:17:29,939
of Shorty: what its useless,
feeble past had been;

587
00:17:29,939 --> 00:17:32,752
what would be its useless, feeble
future.

588
00:17:32,752 --> 00:17:35,436
He shook his head over the sombre
question, Was there any

589
00:17:35,436 --> 00:17:36,798
way out for Shorty?

590
00:17:36,798 --> 00:17:41,228
“It may be,” he reflected,
“that them whose pleasure brings yu’

591
00:17:41,228 --> 00:17:44,473
into this world owes yu’ a living.

592
00:17:44,473 --> 00:17:48,652
But that don’t make the world responsible.

593
00:17:48,652 --> 00:17:50,782
The world did not beget you.

594
00:17:50,782 --> 00:17:55,546
I reckon man helps them
that help themselves.

595
00:17:55,546 --> 00:18:00,907
As for the universe, it looks like it did
too wholesale a business to turn out an

596
00:18:00,907 --> 00:18:03,948
article up to standard every clip.

597
00:18:03,948 --> 00:18:06,559
Yes, it is sorrowful.

598
00:18:06,559 --> 00:18:08,857
For Shorty is kind to his hawss.”

599
00:18:08,857 --> 00:18:13,466
In the evening the Virginian brought
Shorty into his room.

600
00:18:13,466 --> 00:18:17,453
He usually knew what he had to say,
usually found it easy to arrange his

601
00:18:17,453 --> 00:18:23,034
thoughts; and after such arranging the
words came of themselves.

602
00:18:23,034 --> 00:18:28,253
But as he looked at Shorty,
this did not happen to him.

603
00:18:28,253 --> 00:18:34,108
There was not a line of badness in the
face; yet also there was not a line of

604
00:18:34,108 --> 00:18:40,188
strength; no promise in eye,
or nose, or chin; the whole thing melted

605
00:18:40,188 --> 00:18:44,405
to a stubby, featureless mediocrity.

606
00:18:44,405 --> 00:18:49,533
It was a countenance like thousands;
and hopelessness filled the Virginian as

607
00:18:49,533 --> 00:18:55,186
he looked at this lost dog,
and his dull, wistful eyes.

608
00:18:55,186 --> 00:18:58,350
But some beginning must be made.

609
00:18:58,350 --> 00:19:02,865
“I wonder what the thermometer has got
to be,” he said.

610
00:19:02,865 --> 00:19:06,903
“Yu’ can see it, if yu’ll hold the lamp
to that right side of the window.”

611
00:19:06,903 --> 00:19:08,263
Shorty held the lamp.

612
00:19:08,263 --> 00:19:12,798
“I never used any,” he said,
looking out at the instrument,

613
00:19:12,798 --> 00:19:13,959
nevertheless.

614
00:19:13,959 --> 00:19:17,154
The Virginian had forgotten that
Shorty could not read.

615
00:19:17,154 --> 00:19:20,000
So he looked out of the window himself,
and found that it was

616
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:21,720
twenty-two below zero.

617
00:19:21,720 --> 00:19:26,170
“This is pretty good tobacco,”
he remarked; and Shorty helped himself,

618
00:19:26,170 --> 00:19:27,251
and filled his pipe.

619
00:19:27,251 --> 00:19:30,419
“I had to rub my left ear with
snow today,” said he.

620
00:19:30,419 --> 00:19:31,863
“I was just in time.”

621
00:19:31,863 --> 00:19:35,922
“I thought it looked pretty freezy out
where yu’ was riding,” said the foreman.

622
00:19:35,922 --> 00:19:39,665
The lost dog’s eyes showed
plain astonishment.

623
00:19:39,665 --> 00:19:42,743
“We didn’t see you out there,” said he.

624
00:19:42,743 --> 00:19:47,991
“Well,” said the foreman,
“it’ll soon not be freezing any more;

625
00:19:47,991 --> 00:19:50,317
and then we’ll all be
warm enough with work.

626
00:19:50,317 --> 00:19:52,962
Everybody will be working
all over the range.

627
00:19:52,962 --> 00:19:57,268
And I wish I knew somebody that had a lot
of stable work to be attended to.

628
00:19:57,268 --> 00:19:59,317
I cert’nly do for your sake.”

629
00:19:59,317 --> 00:19:59,962
“Why?”

630
00:19:59,962 --> 00:20:00,816
said Shorty.

631
00:20:00,816 --> -1:59:59,000
“Because it’s the right kind of
a job for you.

632
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

633
00:20:03,413 --> 00:20:06,798
“I can make more⁠—” began
Shorty, and stopped.

634
00:20:06,798 --> 00:20:10,242
“There is a time coming,”
said the Virginian, “when I’ll want

635
00:20:10,242 --> 00:20:13,672
somebody that knows how to get
the friendship of hawsses.

636
00:20:13,672 --> 00:20:18,061
I’ll want him to handle some special
hawsses the Judge has plans about.

637
00:20:18,061 --> 00:20:20,793
Judge Henry would pay fifty
a month for that.”

638
00:20:20,793 --> 00:20:24,704
“I can make more,” said Shorty,
this time with stubbornness.

639
00:20:24,704 --> 00:20:26,738
“Well, yes.

640
00:20:26,738 --> 00:20:30,145
Sometimes a man can⁠—when he’s not
worth it, I mean.

641
00:20:30,145 --> 00:20:32,162
But it don’t generally last.”

642
00:20:32,162 --> 00:20:33,577
Shorty was silent.

643
00:20:33,577 --> 00:20:36,977
“I used to make more myself,”
said the Virginian.

644
00:20:36,977 --> 00:20:40,563
“You’re making a lot more
now,” said Shorty.

645
00:20:40,563 --> 00:20:41,482
“Oh, yes.

646
00:20:41,482 --> 00:20:47,291
But I mean when I was fooling around the
earth, jumping from job to job,

647
00:20:47,291 --> 00:20:50,381
and helling all over town between
whiles.

648
00:20:50,381 --> 00:20:54,843
I was not worth fifty a month
then, nor twenty-five.

649
00:20:54,843 --> 00:20:58,204
But there was nights I made a
heap more at cyards.”

650
00:20:58,204 --> 00:21:00,585
Shorty’s eyes grew large.

651
00:21:00,585 --> 00:21:02,140
“And then, bang!

652
00:21:02,140 --> 00:21:04,819
it was gone with treatin’ the
men and the girls.”

653
00:21:04,819 --> 00:21:09,450
“I don’t always⁠—” said
Shorty, and stopped again.

654
00:21:09,450 --> 00:21:13,836
The Virginian knew that he was thinking
about the money he sent East.

655
00:21:13,836 --> 00:21:18,408
“After a while,” he continued,
“I noticed a right strange fact.

656
00:21:18,408 --> 00:21:22,473
The money I made easy that I wasn’t
worth, it went like it came.

657
00:21:22,473 --> 00:21:25,954
I strained myself none
gettin’ or spendin’ it.

658
00:21:25,954 --> 00:21:29,004
But the money I made hard that I was
worth, why I began to feel

659
00:21:29,004 --> 00:21:30,724
right careful about that.

660
00:21:30,724 --> 00:21:34,506
And now I have got savings stowed away.

661
00:21:34,506 --> 00:21:36,556
If once yu’ could know
how good that feels⁠—”

662
00:21:36,556 --> 00:21:39,960
“So I would know,” said
Shorty, “with your luck.”

663
00:21:39,960 --> 00:21:41,583
“What’s my luck?”

664
00:21:41,583 --> 00:21:43,002
said the Virginian, sternly.

665
00:21:43,002 --> 00:21:48,762
“Well, if I had took up land along a
creek that never goes dry and proved

666
00:21:48,762 --> 00:21:52,333
upon it like you have,
and if I had saw that land raise its

667
00:21:52,333 --> 00:21:53,877
value on me with me lifting no finger⁠—”

668
00:21:53,877 --> 00:21:57,128
“Why did you lift no finger?”

669
00:21:57,128 --> 00:21:58,735
cut in the Virginian.

670
00:21:58,735 --> 00:22:00,714
“Who stopped yu’ taking up land?

671
00:22:00,714 --> 00:22:06,510
Did it not stretch in front of yu’,
behind yu’, all around yu’, the biggest,

672
00:22:06,510 --> 00:22:08,335
baldest opportunity in sight?

673
00:22:08,335 --> 00:22:11,430
That was the time I lifted my
finger; but yu’ didn’t.”

674
00:22:11,430 --> 00:22:12,902
Shorty stood stubborn.

675
00:22:12,902 --> 00:22:15,544
“But never mind that,” said the Virginian.

676
00:22:15,544 --> 00:22:19,970
“Take my land away tomorrow,
and I’d still have my savings in bank.

677
00:22:19,970 --> 00:22:23,474
Because, you see, I had to work right
hard gathering them in.

678
00:22:23,474 --> 00:22:27,062
I found out what I could do,
and I settled down and did it.

679
00:22:27,062 --> 00:22:29,655
Now you can do that too.

680
00:22:29,655 --> 00:22:33,344
The only tough part is the finding out
what you’re good for.

681
00:22:33,344 --> 00:22:35,442
And for you, that is found.

682
00:22:35,442 --> 00:22:38,962
If you’ll just decide to work at this
thing you can do, and gentle those

683
00:22:38,962 --> 00:22:41,984
hawsses for the Judge,
you’ll be having savings

684
00:22:41,984 --> -1:59:59,000
in a bank yourself.

685
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

686
00:22:43,585 --> 00:22:46,662
“I can make more,” said the lost dog.

687
00:22:46,662 --> 00:22:49,856
The Virginian was on the point of
saying, “Then get out!”

688
00:22:49,856 --> 00:22:53,118
But instead, he spoke kindness to the end.

689
00:22:53,118 --> 00:22:57,696
“The weather is freezing yet,”
he said, “and it will be for

690
00:22:57,696 --> 00:22:59,294
a good long while.

691
00:22:59,294 --> 00:23:02,182
Take your time, and tell me if
yu’ change your mind.”

692
00:23:02,182 --> 00:23:06,258
After that Shorty returned to the bunk
house, and the Virginian knew that the

693
00:23:06,258 --> 00:23:10,339
boy had learned his lesson of discontent
from Trampas with a thoroughness

694
00:23:10,339 --> 00:23:11,782
past all unteaching.

695
00:23:11,782 --> 00:23:15,898
This petty triumph of evil seemed scarce
of the size to count as any

696
00:23:15,898 --> 00:23:17,686
victory over the Virginian.

697
00:23:17,686 --> 00:23:20,058
But all men grasp at straws.

698
00:23:20,058 --> 00:23:24,632
Since that first moment,
when in the Medicine Bow saloon the

699
00:23:24,632 --> 00:23:30,004
Virginian had shut the mouth of Trampas
by a word, the man had been trying to

700
00:23:30,004 --> 00:23:33,804
get even without risk;
and at each successive clash of his

701
00:23:33,804 --> 00:23:37,861
weapon with the Virginian’s,
he had merely met another

702
00:23:37,861 --> 00:23:39,967
public humiliation.

703
00:23:39,967 --> 00:23:45,901
Therefore, now at the Sunk Creek Ranch in
these cold white days,

704
00:23:45,901 --> 00:23:52,544
a certain lurking insolence in his gait
showed plainly his opinion that by

705
00:23:52,544 --> 00:23:57,589
disaffecting Shorty he had made
some sort of reprisal.

706
00:23:57,589 --> 00:24:00,052
Yes, he had poisoned the lost dog.

707
00:24:00,052 --> 00:24:04,335
In the springtime, when the neighboring
ranches needed additional hands,

708
00:24:04,335 --> 00:24:09,307
it happened as the Virginian had
foreseen⁠—Trampas departed to a “better

709
00:24:09,307 --> 00:24:15,700
job,” as he took pains to say,
and with him the docile Shorty rode away

710
00:24:15,700 --> 00:24:17,850
upon his horse Pedro.

711
00:24:17,850 --> 00:24:20,678
Love now was not any longer snowbound.

712
00:24:20,678 --> 00:24:23,933
The mountain trails were open enough for
the sure feet of love’s steed⁠—

713
00:24:23,933 --> 00:24:26,241
that horse called Monte.

714
00:24:26,241 --> 00:24:28,786
But duty blocked the path of love.

715
00:24:28,786 --> 00:24:33,113
Instead of turning his face to Bear
Creek, the foreman had other journeys to

716
00:24:33,113 --> 00:24:36,906
make, full of heavy work,
and watchfulness, and

717
00:24:36,906 --> 00:24:38,582
councils with the Judge.

718
00:24:38,582 --> 00:24:43,797
The cattle thieves were growing bold,
and winter had scattered the cattle

719
00:24:43,797 --> 00:24:45,899
widely over the range.

720
00:24:45,899 --> 00:24:49,111
Therefore the Virginian,
instead of going to see her,

721
00:24:49,111 --> 00:24:51,328
wrote a letter to his sweetheart.

722
00:24:51,328 --> 00:24:53,061
It was his first.

723
00:24:53,061 --> 00:24:54,560
CHAPTER XXIV

724
00:24:54,560 --> 00:24:55,656
A Letter with a Moral

725
00:24:55,656 --> 00:25:00,502
The letter which the Virginian wrote to
Molly Wood was, as has been stated,

726
00:25:00,502 --> 00:25:02,443
the first that he had
ever addressed to her.

727
00:25:02,443 --> 00:25:07,235
I think, perhaps, he may have been a
little shy as to his skill in the

728
00:25:07,235 --> 00:25:13,593
epistolary art, a little anxious lest
any sustained production from his pen

729
00:25:13,593 --> 00:25:18,579
might contain blunders that would too
staringly remind her

730
00:25:18,579 --> 00:25:21,563
of his scant learning.

731
00:25:21,563 --> 00:25:27,263
He could turn off a business
communication about steers or stock

732
00:25:27,263 --> 00:25:32,981
cars, or any other of the subjects
involved in his profession,

733
00:25:32,981 --> 00:25:40,413
with a brevity and a clearness that led
the Judge to confide three-quarters of

734
00:25:40,413 --> 00:25:43,256
such correspondence to his foreman.

735
00:25:43,256 --> 00:25:46,874
“Write to the 76 outfit,”
the Judge would say,

736
00:25:46,874 --> 00:25:50,133
“and tell them that my wagon cannot
start for the roundup until,”

737
00:25:50,133 --> 00:25:55,333
etc.; or “Write to Cheyenne and say that
if they will hold a meeting next Monday

738
00:25:55,333 --> 00:25:57,184
week, I will,” etc.

739
00:25:57,184 --> 00:26:01,368
And then the Virginian would write
such communications with ease.

740
00:26:01,368 --> 00:26:04,412
But his first message to his lady was
scarcely written with ease.

741
00:26:04,412 --> 00:26:07,401
It must be classed, I think,
among those productions which

742
00:26:07,401 --> 00:26:10,725
are styled literary efforts.

743
00:26:10,725 --> 00:26:14,885
It was completed in pencil before it was
copied in ink; and that first draft of

744
00:26:14,885 --> 00:26:19,198
it in pencil was well-nigh illegible
with erasures and amendments.

745
00:26:19,198 --> 00:26:23,358
The state of mind of the writer during
its composition may be gathered without

746
00:26:23,358 --> 00:26:28,522
further description on my part from a
slight interruption which

747
00:26:28,522 --> 00:26:29,727
occurred in the middle.

748
00:26:29,727 --> 00:26:32,322
The door opened, and Scipio
put his head in.

749
00:26:32,322 --> 00:26:33,792
“You coming to dinner?”

750
00:26:33,792 --> 00:26:35,172
he inquired.

751
00:26:35,172 --> 00:26:37,577
“You go to hell,” replied the Virginian.

752
00:26:37,577 --> 00:26:39,496
“My jinks!”

753
00:26:39,496 --> 00:26:42,676
said Scipio, quietly,
and he shut the door

754
00:26:42,676 --> 00:26:45,082
without further observation.

755
00:26:45,082 --> 00:26:50,711
To tell the truth, I doubt if this letter
would ever have been undertaken,

756
00:26:50,711 --> 00:26:54,588
far less completed and despatched,
had not the lover’s heart

757
00:26:54,588 --> 00:26:56,038
been wrung with disappointment.

758
00:26:56,038 --> 00:27:01,241
All winter long he had looked to that day
when he should knock at the girl’s door,

759
00:27:01,241 --> 00:27:03,201
and hear her voice bid him come in.

760
00:27:03,201 --> 00:27:07,417
All winter long he had been choosing the
ride he would take her.

761
00:27:07,417 --> 00:27:11,961
He had imagined a sunny afternoon,
a hidden grove, a sheltering cleft of

762
00:27:11,961 --> 00:27:15,572
rock, a running spring,
and some words of his that should

763
00:27:15,572 --> 00:27:19,404
conquer her at last and leave
his lips upon hers.

764
00:27:19,404 --> 00:27:24,126
And with this controlled fire pent up
within him, he had counted the days,

765
00:27:24,126 --> 00:27:28,129
scratching them off his calendar with a
dig each night that once or

766
00:27:28,129 --> 00:27:29,724
twice snapped the pen.

767
00:27:29,724 --> 00:27:34,601
Then, when the trail stood open,
this meeting was deferred,

768
00:27:34,601 --> 00:27:40,922
put off for indefinite days,
or weeks; he could not tell how long.

769
00:27:40,922 --> 00:27:47,149
So, gripping his pencil and tracing heavy
words, he gave himself what consolation

770
00:27:47,149 --> 00:27:48,886
he could by writing her.

771
00:27:48,886 --> 00:27:55,532
The letter, duly stamped and addressed to
Bear Creek, set forth upon its travels;

772
00:27:55,532 --> 00:27:57,792
and these were devious and long.

773
00:27:57,792 --> 00:28:01,752
When it reached its destination,
it was some twenty days old.

774
00:28:01,752 --> 00:28:06,620
It had gone by private hand at the
outset, taken the stagecoach at a way

775
00:28:06,620 --> 00:28:10,907
point, become late in that stagecoach,
reached a point of transfer,

776
00:28:10,907 --> 00:28:17,619
and waited there for the postmaster to
begin, continue, end,

777
00:28:17,619 --> 00:28:22,696
and recover from a game of
poker, mingled with whiskey.

778
00:28:22,696 --> 00:28:26,767
Then it once more proceeded,
was dropped at the right way point,

779
00:28:26,767 --> 00:28:29,171
and carried by private
hand to Bear Creek.

780
00:28:29,171 --> 00:28:34,063
The experience of this letter,
however, was not at all a remarkable one

781
00:28:34,063 --> 00:28:36,403
at that time in Wyoming.

782
00:28:36,403 --> 00:28:38,389
Molly Wood looked at the envelope.

783
00:28:38,389 --> 00:28:41,735
She had never before seen
the Virginian’s handwriting.

784
00:28:41,735 --> 00:28:43,529
She knew it instantly.

785
00:28:43,529 --> 00:28:47,425
She closed her door and sat down to read
it with a beating heart.

786
00:28:47,425 --> 00:28:48,616
Sunk Creek Ranch,

787
00:28:48,616 --> 00:28:50,994
May 5, 188‒

788
00:28:50,994 --> 00:28:52,939
My Dear Miss Wood:

789
00:28:52,939 --> 00:28:54,498
I am sorry about this.

790
00:28:54,498 --> 00:28:56,430
My plan was different.

791
00:28:56,430 --> 00:29:01,190
It was to get over for a ride with you
about now or sooner.

792
00:29:01,190 --> 00:29:03,069
This year Spring is early.

793
00:29:03,069 --> 00:29:08,424
The snow is off the flats this side the
range and where the sun gets a chance to

794
00:29:08,424 --> 00:29:14,894
hit the earth strong all day it is green
and has flowers too, a good many.

795
00:29:14,894 --> 00:29:18,082
You can see them bob and mix
together in the wind.

796
00:29:18,082 --> 00:29:22,878
The quaking-asps down low on the South
side are in small leaf and will soon be

797
00:29:22,878 --> 00:29:24,988
twinkling like the flowers do now.

798
00:29:24,988 --> 00:29:29,708
I had planned to take a look at this with
you and that was a better plan than what

799
00:29:29,708 --> 00:29:30,694
I have got to do.

800
00:29:30,694 --> 00:29:34,708
The water is high but I could have got
over and as for the snow on top of the

801
00:29:34,708 --> 00:29:38,311
mountain a man told me nobody could
cross it for a week yet,

802
00:29:38,311 --> 00:29:40,113
because he had just done it himself.

803
00:29:40,113 --> 00:29:41,956
Was not he a funny man?

804
00:29:41,956 --> 00:29:45,188
You ought to see how the birds have
streamed across the sky

805
00:29:45,188 --> 00:29:46,761
while Spring was coming.

806
00:29:46,761 --> 00:29:50,320
But you have seen them on your
side of the mountain.

807
00:29:50,320 --> 00:29:55,049
But I can’t come now Miss Wood.

808
00:29:55,049 --> 00:29:58,911
There is a lot for me to do that has to
be done and Judge Henry needs more than

809
00:29:58,911 --> 00:30:00,271
two eyes just now.

810
00:30:00,271 --> 00:30:05,086
I could not think much of myself if I
left him for my own wishes.

811
00:30:05,086 --> 00:30:07,500
But the days will be warmer when I come.

812
00:30:07,500 --> 00:30:11,422
We will not have to quit by five,
and we can get off and sit too.

813
00:30:11,422 --> 00:30:15,302
We could not sit now unless for
a very short while.

814
00:30:15,302 --> 00:30:20,066
If I know when I can come I will try to
let you know, but I think it

815
00:30:20,066 --> 00:30:21,392
will be this way.

816
00:30:21,392 --> 00:30:26,631
I think you will just see me coming for I
have things to do of an unsure nature

817
00:30:26,631 --> 00:30:28,662
and a good number of such.

818
00:30:28,662 --> 00:30:31,219
Do not believe reports about Indians.

819
00:30:31,219 --> 00:30:35,583
They are started by editors to keep the
soldiers in the country.

820
00:30:35,583 --> 00:30:40,238
The friends of the editors get the
hay and beef contracts.

821
00:30:40,238 --> 00:30:44,879
Indians do not come to settled parts
like Bear Creek is.

822
00:30:44,879 --> 00:30:48,542
It is all editors and politicianists.

823
00:30:48,542 --> 00:30:50,756
Nothing has happened worth telling you.

824
00:30:50,756 --> 00:30:53,733
I have read that play Othello.

825
00:30:53,733 --> 00:30:56,673
No man should write down such a thing.

826
00:30:56,673 --> 00:30:58,124
Do you know if it is true?

827
00:30:58,124 --> 00:31:01,026
I have seen one worse
affair down in Arizona.

828
00:31:01,026 --> 00:31:06,204
He killed his little child as well as his
wife but such things should not be put

829
00:31:06,204 --> 00:31:08,924
down in fine language for the public.

830
00:31:08,924 --> 00:31:11,176
I have read Romeo and Juliet.

831
00:31:11,176 --> 00:31:16,089
That is beautiful language but
Romeo is no man.

832
00:31:16,089 --> 00:31:20,268
I like his friend Mercutio
that gets killed.

833
00:31:20,268 --> 00:31:21,380
He is a man.

834
00:31:21,380 --> 00:31:25,752
If he had got Juliet there would have
been no foolishness and trouble.

835
00:31:25,752 --> 00:31:28,530
Well Miss Wood I would like
to see you today.

836
00:31:28,530 --> 00:31:33,770
Do you know what I think Monte would do
if I rode him out and let the rein

837
00:31:33,770 --> 00:31:34,855
slack?

838
00:31:34,855 --> 00:31:39,252
He would come straight to your gate for
he is a horse of great judgement.

839
00:31:39,252 --> 00:31:42,223
(“That’s the first word he
has misspelled,” said Molly.)

840
00:31:42,223 --> 00:31:47,872
I suppose you are sitting with George
Taylor and those children right now.

841
00:31:47,872 --> 00:31:53,625
Then George will get old enough to help
his father but Uncle Hewie’s twins will

842
00:31:53,625 --> 00:31:57,912
be ready for you about then and the
supply will keep coming from all

843
00:31:57,912 --> 00:32:02,818
quarters all sizes for you to say big A
little a to them.

844
00:32:02,818 --> 00:32:04,447
There is no news here.

845
00:32:04,447 --> 00:32:10,132
Only calves and cows and the hens are
laying now which does always seem news

846
00:32:10,132 --> 00:32:12,053
to a hen every time she does it.

847
00:32:12,053 --> 00:32:15,534
Did I ever tell you about a hen
Emily we had here?

848
00:32:15,534 --> 00:32:21,586
She was venturesome to an extent I have
not seen in other hens only she had poor

849
00:32:21,586 --> 00:32:24,910
judgement and would make no family ties.

850
00:32:24,910 --> 00:32:30,513
She would keep trying to get interest in
the ties of others taking charge of

851
00:32:30,513 --> 00:32:35,124
little chicks and bantams and turkeys
and puppies one time,

852
00:32:35,124 --> 00:32:37,711
and she thought most anything was an
egg.

853
00:32:37,711 --> 00:32:40,249
I will tell you about her sometime.

854
00:32:40,249 --> 00:32:45,636
She died without family ties one day
while I was building a house for her

855
00:32:45,636 --> 00:32:46,901
to teach school in.

856
00:32:46,901 --> 00:32:48,875
(“The outrageous wretch!”

857
00:32:48,875 --> 00:32:49,815
cried Molly!

858
00:32:49,815 --> 00:32:55,167
And her cheeks turned deep pink as she
sat alone with her lover’s letter.)

859
00:32:55,167 --> 00:32:57,870
I am coming the first day I am free.

860
00:32:57,870 --> 00:33:02,510
I will be a hundred miles from you most
of the time when I am not more but I

861
00:33:02,510 --> 00:33:07,211
will ride a hundred miles for one hour
and Monte is up to that.

862
00:33:07,211 --> 00:33:12,222
After never seeing you for so long I will
make one hour do if I have to.

863
00:33:12,222 --> 00:33:14,879
Here is a flower I have just
been out and picked.

864
00:33:14,879 --> 00:33:16,253
I have kissed it now.

865
00:33:16,253 --> 00:33:18,233
That is the best I can do yet.

866
00:33:18,233 --> 00:33:21,455
Molly laid the letter in her lap and
looked at the flower.

867
00:33:21,455 --> 00:33:27,096
Then suddenly she jumped up and pressed
it to her lips, and after a long moment

868
00:33:27,096 --> 00:33:28,527
held it away from her.

869
00:33:28,527 --> 00:33:30,008
“No,” she said.

870
00:33:30,008 --> 00:33:30,949
“No, no, no.”

871
00:33:30,949 --> 00:33:32,051
She sat down.

872
00:33:32,051 --> 00:33:35,686
It was some time before
she finished the letter.

873
00:33:35,686 --> 00:33:39,115
Then once more she got up and
put on her hat.

874
00:33:39,115 --> 00:33:39,487
Mrs.

875
00:33:39,487 --> 00:33:43,660
Taylor wondered where the girl could
be walking so fast.

876
00:33:43,660 --> 00:33:47,490
But she was not walking anywhere,
and in half an hour she returned,

877
00:33:47,490 --> 00:33:53,002
rosy with her swift exercise,
but with a spirit as perturbed as when

878
00:33:53,002 --> 00:33:54,242
she had set out.

879
00:33:54,242 --> 00:33:58,333
Next morning at six, when she looked out
of her window, there was Monte tied

880
00:33:58,333 --> 00:33:59,573
to the Taylor’s gate.

881
00:33:59,573 --> 00:34:03,893
Ah, could he have come the day before,
could she have found him when she

882
00:34:03,893 --> 00:34:07,624
returned from that swift walk of hers!

883
00:34:07,624 --> 00:34:11,326
CHAPTER XXV

884
00:34:11,326 --> 00:34:12,866
Progress of the Lost Dog

885
00:34:12,866 --> 00:34:24,146
It was not even an hour’s visit that the
Virginian was able to pay his lady love.

886
00:34:25,295 --> 00:34:35,625
But neither had he come a hundred
miles to see her.

887
00:34:35,625 --> 00:34:41,610
The necessities of his wandering work had
chanced to bring him close enough for a

888
00:34:41,610 --> 00:34:45,985
glimpse of her, and this glimpse he
took, almost on the wing.

889
00:34:45,985 --> 00:34:52,331
For he had to rejoin a company
of men at once.

890
00:34:52,331 --> 00:34:53,610
“Yu’ got my letter?”

891
00:34:53,610 --> 00:34:54,451
he said.

892
00:34:54,451 --> 00:34:55,572
“Yesterday.”

893
00:34:55,572 --> 00:34:56,841
“Yesterday!

894
00:34:56,841 --> 00:34:58,887
I wrote it three weeks ago.

895
00:34:58,887 --> 00:35:01,168
Well, yu’ got it.

896
00:35:01,168 --> 00:35:04,021
This cannot be the hour with
you that I mentioned.

897
00:35:04,021 --> 00:35:06,877
That is coming, and maybe very soon.”

898
00:35:06,877 --> 00:35:07,796
She could say nothing.

899
00:35:07,796 --> 00:35:11,807
Relief she felt, and yet with it
something like a pang.

900
00:35:11,807 --> 00:35:15,949
“Today does not count,”
he told her, “except that every time I

901
00:35:15,949 --> 00:35:17,633
see you counts with me.

902
00:35:17,633 --> 00:35:19,938
But this is not the hour
that I mentioned.”

903
00:35:19,938 --> 00:35:22,880
What little else was said between them
upon this early morning

904
00:35:22,880 --> 00:35:24,560
shall be told duly.

905
00:35:24,560 --> 00:35:30,363
For this visit in its own good time did
count momentously, though both of them

906
00:35:30,363 --> 00:35:33,353
took it lightly while
its fleeting minutes passed.

907
00:35:33,353 --> 00:35:39,118
He returned to her two volumes that she
had lent him long ago and with Taylor he

908
00:35:39,118 --> 00:35:42,405
left a horse which he had brought
for her to ride.

909
00:35:42,405 --> 00:35:46,037
As a goodbye, he put a bunch of
flowers in her hand.

910
00:35:46,037 --> 00:35:49,620
Then he was gone, and she watched him
going by the thick bushes

911
00:35:49,620 --> 00:35:50,699
along the stream.

912
00:35:50,699 --> 00:35:54,822
They were pink with wild roses;
and the meadowlarks,

913
00:35:54,822 --> 00:35:58,296
invisible in the grass,
like hiding choristers,

914
00:35:58,296 --> 00:36:03,438
sent up across the empty miles of
air their unexpected song.

915
00:36:03,438 --> 00:36:07,794
Earth and sky had been propitious,
could he have stayed;

916
00:36:07,794 --> 00:36:12,144
and perhaps one portion of her heart
had been propitious too.

917
00:36:12,144 --> 00:36:16,794
So, as he rode away on Monte,
she watched him, half chilled by reason,

918
00:36:16,794 --> 00:36:21,498
half melted by passion,
self-thwarted, self-accusing,

919
00:36:21,498 --> 00:36:22,530
unresolved.

920
00:36:22,530 --> 00:36:27,339
Therefore the days that came for her now
were all of them unhappy ones,

921
00:36:27,339 --> 00:36:33,546
while for him they were filled with work
well done and with changeless longing.

922
00:36:33,546 --> 00:36:37,162
One day it seemed as if a lull was
coming, a pause in which he could at

923
00:36:37,162 --> 00:36:39,304
last attain that hour with her.

924
00:36:39,304 --> 00:36:43,933
He left the camp and turned his
face toward Bear Creek.

925
00:36:43,933 --> 00:36:45,939
The way led him along Butte Creek.

926
00:36:45,939 --> 00:36:51,681
Across the stream lay Balaam’s large
ranch; and presently on the other bank

927
00:36:51,681 --> 00:36:55,545
he saw Balaam himself,
and reined in Monte for a moment to

928
00:36:55,545 --> 00:36:57,563
watch what Balaam was doing.

929
00:36:57,563 --> 00:37:00,817
“That’s what I’ve heard,”
he muttered to himself.

930
00:37:00,817 --> 00:37:05,257
For Balaam had led some horses to the
water, and was lashing them heavily

931
00:37:05,257 --> 00:37:07,560
because they would not drink.

932
00:37:07,560 --> 00:37:11,900
He looked at this spectacle so intently
that he did not see Shorty

933
00:37:11,900 --> 00:37:14,063
approaching along the trail.

934
00:37:14,063 --> 00:37:17,340
“Morning,” said Shorty to
him, with some constraint.

935
00:37:17,340 --> 00:37:20,939
But the Virginian gave him a pleasant
greeting, “I was afraid I’d not catch

936
00:37:20,939 --> 00:37:23,162
you so quick,” said Shorty.

937
00:37:23,162 --> 00:37:24,397
“This is for you.”

938
00:37:24,397 --> 00:37:29,177
He handed his recent foreman a letter
of much battered appearance.

939
00:37:29,177 --> 00:37:30,711
It was from the Judge.

940
00:37:30,711 --> 00:37:35,953
It had not come straight,
but very gradually, in the pockets

941
00:37:35,953 --> 00:37:38,407
of three successive cowpunchers.

942
00:37:38,407 --> 00:37:44,649
As the Virginian glanced over it and saw
that the enclosure it contained was for

943
00:37:44,649 --> 00:37:47,693
Balaam, his heart fell.

944
00:37:47,693 --> 00:37:50,205
Here were new orders for him,
and he could not go to

945
00:37:50,205 --> 00:37:51,342
see his sweetheart.

946
00:37:51,342 --> 00:37:52,840
“Hello, Shorty!”

947
00:37:52,840 --> 00:37:55,415
said Balaam, from over the creek.

948
00:37:55,415 --> 00:37:59,233
To the Virginian he gave a slight nod.

949
00:37:59,233 --> 00:38:05,005
He did not know him, although he knew
well enough who he was.

950
00:38:05,005 --> 00:38:08,627
“Hyeh’s a letter from Judge Henry for yu’
” said the Virginian,

951
00:38:08,627 --> 00:38:09,986
and he crossed the creek.

952
00:38:09,986 --> 00:38:16,443
Many weeks before, in the early spring,
Balaam had borrowed two horses from the

953
00:38:16,443 --> 00:38:19,998
Judge, promising to return them at once.

954
00:38:19,998 --> 00:38:24,177
But the Judge, of course,
wrote very civilly.

955
00:38:24,177 --> 00:38:27,678
He hoped that “this dunning
reminder” might be excused.

956
00:38:27,678 --> 00:38:30,250
As Balaam read the reminder,
he wished that he had

957
00:38:30,250 --> 00:38:31,907
sent the horses before.

958
00:38:31,907 --> 00:38:35,208
The Judge was a greater man than
he in the Territory.

959
00:38:35,208 --> 00:38:39,832
Balaam could not but excuse the “dunning
reminder,”⁠—but he was ready to be

960
00:38:39,832 --> 00:38:42,597
disagreeable to somebody at once.

961
00:38:42,597 --> 00:38:47,686
“Well,” he said, musing aloud in his
annoyance, “Judge Henry wants

962
00:38:47,686 --> 00:38:48,840
them by the 30th.

963
00:38:48,840 --> 00:38:52,125
Well, this is the 24th,
and time enough yet.”

964
00:38:52,125 --> 00:38:55,845
“This is the 27th,” said
the Virginian, briefly.

965
00:38:55,845 --> 00:38:58,136
That made a difference!

966
00:38:58,136 --> 00:39:02,791
Not so easy to reach Sunk Creek in good
order by the 30th!

967
00:39:02,791 --> 00:39:07,577
Balaam had drifted three sunrises behind
the progress of the month.

968
00:39:07,577 --> 00:39:12,017
Days look alike, and often lose their
very names in the quiet

969
00:39:12,017 --> 00:39:13,480
depths of Cattle Land.

970
00:39:13,480 --> 00:39:16,504
The horses were not even
here at the ranch.

971
00:39:16,504 --> 00:39:19,394
Balaam was ready to be
very disagreeable now.

972
00:39:19,394 --> 00:39:22,483
Suddenly he perceived the date
of the Judge’s letter.

973
00:39:22,483 --> 00:39:25,555
He held it out to the Virginian,
and struck the paper.

974
00:39:25,555 --> 00:39:28,970
“What’s your idea in bringing this
here two weeks late?”

975
00:39:28,970 --> 00:39:29,666
he said.

976
00:39:29,666 --> 00:39:33,782
Now, when he had struck that paper,
Shorty looked at the Virginian.

977
00:39:33,782 --> 00:39:38,106
But nothing happened beyond a certain
change of light in the Southerner’s

978
00:39:38,106 --> 00:39:38,968
eyes.

979
00:39:38,968 --> 00:39:42,458
And when the Southerner spoke,
it was with his usual

980
00:39:42,458 --> 00:39:44,233
gentleness and civility.

981
00:39:44,233 --> 00:39:49,418
He explained that the letter had been put
in his hands just now by Shorty.

982
00:39:49,418 --> 00:39:51,218
“Oh,” said Balaam.

983
00:39:51,218 --> 00:39:52,578
He looked at Shorty.

984
00:39:52,578 --> 00:39:54,679
How had he come to be a messenger?

985
00:39:54,679 --> 00:39:57,808
“You working for the Sunk
Creek outfit again?”

986
00:39:57,808 --> 00:39:58,599
said he.

987
00:39:58,599 --> 00:40:00,399
“No,” said Shorty.

988
00:40:00,399 --> 00:40:04,762
Balaam turned to the Virginian again.

989
00:40:04,762 --> 00:40:08,500
“How do you expect me to get those horses
to Sunk Creek by the 30th?”

990
00:40:08,500 --> 00:40:11,162
The Virginian levelled a
lazy eye on Balaam.

991
00:40:11,162 --> 00:40:13,917
“I ain’ doin’ any expecting,” said he.

992
00:40:13,917 --> 00:40:16,048
His native dialect was on top today.

993
00:40:16,048 --> 00:40:20,478
“The Judge has friends goin’ to arrive
from New Yawk for a trip across

994
00:40:20,478 --> 00:40:22,171
the Basin,” he added.

995
00:40:22,171 --> 00:40:23,569
“The hawsses are for them.”

996
00:40:23,569 --> 00:40:27,699
Balaam grunted with displeasure,
and thought of the sixty or seventy days

997
00:40:27,699 --> 00:40:30,979
since he had told the Judge he would
return the horses at once.

998
00:40:30,979 --> 00:40:35,259
He looked across at Shorty seated in the
shade, and through his uneasy thoughts

999
00:40:35,259 --> 00:40:39,530
his instinct irrelevantly noted what a
good pony the youth rode.

1000
00:40:39,530 --> 00:40:43,451
It was the same animal he had seen
once or twice before.

1001
00:40:43,451 --> 00:40:45,420
But something must be done.

1002
00:40:45,420 --> 00:40:50,950
The Judge’s horses were far out on the
big range, and must be found and driven

1003
00:40:50,950 --> 00:40:55,982
in, which would take certainly the rest
of this day, possibly part of the next.

1004
00:40:55,982 --> 00:41:01,759
Balaam called to one of his men and gave
some sharp orders, emphasizing details,

1005
00:41:01,759 --> 00:41:05,279
and enjoining haste,
while the Virginian leaned slightly

1006
00:41:05,279 --> 00:41:11,273
against his horse, with one arm over the
saddle, hearing and understanding,

1007
00:41:11,273 --> 00:41:12,975
but not smiling outwardly.

1008
00:41:12,975 --> 00:41:16,709
The man departed to saddle up for his
search on the big range,

1009
00:41:16,709 --> 00:41:19,239
and Balaam resumed the
unhitching of his team.

1010
00:41:19,239 --> 00:41:22,636
“So you’re not working for the
Sunk Creek outfit now?”

1011
00:41:22,636 --> 00:41:24,054
he inquired of Shorty.

1012
00:41:24,054 --> 00:41:25,787
He ignored the Virginian.

1013
00:41:25,787 --> 00:41:27,814
“Working for the Goose Egg?”

1014
00:41:27,814 --> 00:41:29,449
“No,” said Shorty.

1015
00:41:29,449 --> 00:41:31,191
“Sand Hill outfit, then?”

1016
00:41:31,191 --> 00:41:33,597
“No,” said Shorty.

1017
00:41:33,597 --> 00:41:36,015
Balaam grinned.

1018
00:41:36,015 --> 00:41:39,818
He noticed how Shorty’s yellow hair stuck
through a hole in his hat,

1019
00:41:39,818 --> 00:41:42,839
and how old and battered
were Shorty’s overalls.

1020
00:41:42,839 --> 00:41:47,130
Shorty had been glad to take a little
accidental pay for becoming the bearer

1021
00:41:47,130 --> 00:41:50,781
of the letter which he had
delivered to the Virginian.

1022
00:41:50,781 --> 00:41:54,256
But even that sum was no
longer in his possession.

1023
00:41:54,256 --> 00:41:58,341
He had passed through Drybone on his way,
and at Drybone there had been

1024
00:41:58,341 --> 00:41:59,686
a game of poker.

1025
00:41:59,686 --> 00:42:02,459
Shorty’s money was now in
the pocket of Trampas.

1026
00:42:02,459 --> 00:42:06,094
But he had one valuable possession in the
world left to him, and that

1027
00:42:06,094 --> 00:42:07,412
was his horse Pedro.

1028
00:42:07,412 --> 00:42:10,800
“Good pony of yours,”
said Balaam to him now,

1029
00:42:10,800 --> 00:42:13,272
from across Butte Creek.

1030
00:42:13,272 --> 00:42:17,576
Then he struck his own horse in the jaw
because he held back from coming to the

1031
00:42:17,576 --> 00:42:19,136
water as the other had done.

1032
00:42:19,136 --> 00:42:25,771
“Your trace ain’t unhitched,”
commented the Virginian, pointing.

1033
00:42:25,771 --> 00:42:29,571
Balaam loosed the strap he had forgotten,
and cut the horse again

1034
00:42:29,571 --> 00:42:31,368
for consistency’s sake.

1035
00:42:31,368 --> 00:42:35,096
The animal, bewildered,
now came down to the water,

1036
00:42:35,096 --> 00:42:38,055
with its head in the air,
and snuffing as it took

1037
00:42:38,055 --> 00:42:39,844
short, nervous steps.

1038
00:42:39,844 --> 00:42:43,844
The Virginian looked on at
this, silent and sombre.

1039
00:42:43,844 --> 00:42:47,740
He could scarcely interfere between
another man and his own beast.

1040
00:42:47,740 --> 00:42:54,201
Neither he nor Balaam was among those
who say their prayers.

1041
00:42:54,201 --> 00:42:56,961
Yet in this omission they were not equal.

1042
00:42:56,961 --> 00:43:03,817
A half-great poet once had a wholly great
day, and in that great day he was able

1043
00:43:03,817 --> 00:43:11,442
to write a poem that has lived and
become, with many, a household word.

1044
00:43:11,442 --> 00:43:15,885
He called it The Rime
of the Ancient Mariner.

1045
00:43:15,885 --> 00:43:19,787
And it is rich with many lines that
possess the memory; but these

1046
00:43:19,787 --> -1:59:59,000
are the golden ones:⁠

1047
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
—

1048
00:43:22,507 --> 00:43:27,331
“He prayeth well who loveth wellBoth man
and bird and beast.

1049
00:43:27,331 --> 00:43:33,357
He prayeth best who loveth bestAll things
both great and small;

1050
00:43:33,357 --> 00:43:41,647
For the dear God who loveth us,
He made and loveth all.”

1051
00:43:41,647 --> 00:43:43,704
These lines are the pure gold.

1052
00:43:43,704 --> 00:43:48,400
They are good to teach children;
because after the children come to be

1053
00:43:48,400 --> 00:43:51,761
men, they may believe at least some
part of them still.

1054
00:43:51,761 --> 00:43:56,352
The Virginian did not know them⁠—but his
heart had taught him many things.

1055
00:43:56,352 --> 00:43:59,341
I doubt if Balaam knew them either.

1056
00:43:59,341 --> 00:44:02,641
But on him they would have been
as pearls to swine.

1057
00:44:02,641 --> 00:44:04,125
“So you’ve quit the roundup?”

1058
00:44:04,125 --> 00:44:05,353
he resumed to Shorty.

1059
00:44:05,353 --> 00:44:08,598
Shorty nodded and looked
sidewise at the Virginian.

1060
00:44:08,598 --> 00:44:11,752
For the Virginian knew that he had been
turned off for going to

1061
00:44:11,752 --> 00:44:14,359
sleep while night-herding.

1062
00:44:14,359 --> 00:44:17,591
Then Balaam threw another glance
on Pedro the horse.

1063
00:44:17,591 --> 00:44:19,425
“Hello, Shorty!”

1064
00:44:19,425 --> 00:44:22,127
he called out, for the boy was departing.

1065
00:44:22,127 --> 00:44:23,838
“Don’t you like dinner any more?

1066
00:44:23,838 --> 00:44:25,801
It’s ready about now.”

1067
00:44:25,801 --> 00:44:30,391
Shorty forded the creek and slung his
saddle off, and on invitation turned

1068
00:44:30,391 --> 00:44:34,819
Pedro, his buckskin pony,
into Balaam’s pasture.

1069
00:44:34,819 --> 00:44:39,333
This was green, the rest of the wide
world being yellow, except only where

1070
00:44:39,333 --> 00:44:44,064
Butte Creek, with its bordering
cottonwoods, coiled away into the desert

1071
00:44:44,064 --> 00:44:47,211
distance like a green snake without end.

1072
00:44:47,211 --> 00:44:50,815
The Virginian also turned his
horse into the pasture.

1073
00:44:50,815 --> 00:44:55,440
He must stay at the ranch till the
Judge’s horses should be found.

1074
00:44:55,440 --> 00:44:56,481
“Mrs.

1075
00:44:56,481 --> 00:45:02,034
Balaam’s East yet,” said her lord,
leading the way to his dining room.

1076
00:45:02,034 --> 00:45:05,996
He wanted Shorty to dine with him,
and could not exclude the Virginian,

1077
00:45:05,996 --> 00:45:07,897
much as he should have enjoyed this.

1078
00:45:07,897 --> 00:45:10,207
“See any Indians?”

1079
00:45:10,207 --> 00:45:11,107
he enquired.

1080
00:45:11,107 --> 00:45:11,959
“Na-a!”

1081
00:45:11,959 --> 00:45:16,229
said Shorty, in disdain of recent rumors.

1082
00:45:16,229 --> 00:45:19,989
“They’re headin’ the other
way,” observed the Virginian.

1083
00:45:19,989 --> 00:45:22,517
“Bow Laig Range is where
they was repawted.”

1084
00:45:22,517 --> 00:45:26,684
“What business have they got off the
reservation, I’d like to know,”

1085
00:45:26,684 --> 00:45:29,391
said the ranchman, “Bow
Leg, or anywhere?”

1086
00:45:29,391 --> 00:45:33,397
“Oh, it’s just a hunt,
and a kind of visitin’ their friends

1087
00:45:33,397 --> 00:45:35,522
on the South Reservation

1088
00:45:35,522 --> 00:45:37,230
,” Shorty explained.

1089
00:45:37,230 --> 00:45:38,627
“Squaws along and all.”

1090
00:45:38,627 --> 00:45:42,960
“Well, if the folks at Washington don’t
keep squaws and all where they belong,”

1091
00:45:42,960 --> 00:45:46,755
said Balaam, in a rage,
“the folks in Wyoming Territory ’ill do

1092
00:45:46,755 --> 00:45:49,121
a little job that way themselves.”

1093
00:45:49,121 --> 00:45:51,259
“There’s a petition out,” said Shorty.

1094
00:45:51,259 --> -1:59:59,000
“Paper’s goin’ East with a lot
of names to it

1095
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
.

1096
00:45:53,777 --> 00:45:56,960
But they ain’t no harm,
them Indians ain’t.”

1097
00:45:56,960 --> 00:45:57,773
“No harm?”

1098
00:45:57,773 --> 00:45:59,244
rasped out Balaam.

1099
00:45:59,244 --> 00:46:03,482
“Was it white men druv
off the O.C. yearlings?”

1100
00:46:03,482 --> 00:46:07,877
Balaam’s Eastern grammar was sometimes at
the mercy of his Western feelings.

1101
00:46:07,877 --> 00:46:11,223
The thought of the perennial
stultification of Indian affairs at

1102
00:46:11,223 --> 00:46:15,747
Washington, whether by politician or
philanthropist, was always

1103
00:46:15,747 --> 00:46:17,042
sure to arouse him.

1104
00:46:17,042 --> 00:46:21,067
He walked impatiently about while he
spoke, and halted impatiently

1105
00:46:21,067 --> 00:46:22,279
at the window.

1106
00:46:22,279 --> 00:46:27,388
Out in the world the unclouded day was
shining, and Balaam’s eye travelled

1107
00:46:27,388 --> 00:46:31,908
across the plains to where a blue line,
faint and pale, lay along the end of

1108
00:46:31,908 --> 00:46:34,087
the vast yellow distance.

1109
00:46:34,087 --> 00:46:37,966
That was the beginning of
the Bow Leg Mountains.

1110
00:46:37,966 --> 00:46:43,509
Somewhere over there were the red men,
ranging in unfrequented depths of rock

1111
00:46:43,509 --> 00:46:46,740
and pine⁠—their forbidden ground.

1112
00:46:46,740 --> 00:46:48,653
Dinner was ready, and they sat down.

1113
00:46:48,653 --> 00:46:52,632
“And I suppose,” Balaam continued,
still hot on the subject,

1114
00:46:52,632 --> 00:47:01,914
“you’d claim Indians object to killing a
white man when they run on to him good

1115
00:47:01,914 --> 00:47:06,399
and far from human help?

1116
00:47:06,399 --> 00:47:11,277
These peaceable Indians are just the
worst in the business.”

1117
00:47:11,277 --> 00:47:15,623
“That’s so,” assented the easy-opinioned
Shorty, exactly as if he had

1118
00:47:15,623 --> 00:47:17,943
always maintained this view.

1119
00:47:17,943 --> 00:47:21,023
“Chap started for Sunk
Creek three weeks ago.

1120
00:47:21,023 --> 00:47:25,814
Trapper he was; old like,
with a red shirt.

1121
00:47:25,814 --> 00:47:28,877
One of his horses come
into the roundup Toosday.

1122
00:47:28,877 --> 00:47:30,371
Man ain’t been heard from.”

1123
00:47:30,371 --> 00:47:34,830
He ate in silence for a while,
evidently brooding in his childlike

1124
00:47:34,830 --> 00:47:35,331
mind.

1125
00:47:35,331 --> 00:47:39,224
Then he said, querulously,
“I’d sooner trust one of them Indians

1126
00:47:39,224 --> 00:47:40,704
than I would Trampas.”

1127
00:47:40,704 --> 00:47:46,544
Balaam slanted his fat bullet head far to
one side, and laying his spoon down (he

1128
00:47:46,544 --> 00:47:50,928
had opened some canned grapes) laughed
steadily at his guest with a

1129
00:47:50,928 --> 00:47:54,658
harsh relish of irony.

1130
00:47:54,658 --> 00:47:59,269
The guest ate a grape,
and perceiving he was seen through,

1131
00:47:59,269 --> 00:48:01,518
smiled back rather miserably.

1132
00:48:01,518 --> 00:48:06,877
“Say, Shorty,” said Balaam,
his head still slanted over,

1133
00:48:06,877 --> 00:48:10,098
“what’s the figures of your
bank balance just now?”

1134
00:48:10,098 --> 00:48:13,664
“I ain’t usin’ banks,” murmured the youth.

1135
00:48:13,664 --> 00:48:17,904
Balaam put some more grapes on Shorty’s
plate, and drawing a cigar from his

1136
00:48:17,904 --> 00:48:21,288
waistcoat, sent it rolling to his guest.

1137
00:48:21,288 --> 00:48:24,251
“Matches are behind you,” he added.

1138
00:48:24,251 --> 00:48:29,568
He gave a cigar to the Virginian as an
afterthought, but to his disgust,

1139
00:48:29,568 --> 00:48:32,168
the Southerner put it in his pocket
and lighted a pipe.

1140
00:48:32,168 --> 00:48:36,640
Balaam accompanied his guest,
Shorty, when he went to the pasture to

1141
00:48:36,640 --> 00:48:38,980
saddle up and depart.

1142
00:48:38,980 --> 00:48:40,503
“Got a rope?”

1143
00:48:40,503 --> 00:48:43,817
he asked the guest, as they
lifted down the bars.

1144
00:48:43,817 --> 00:48:45,217
“Don’t need to rope him.

1145
00:48:45,217 --> 00:48:47,391
I can walk right up to Pedro.

1146
00:48:47,391 --> 00:48:48,353
You stay back.”

1147
00:48:48,353 --> 00:48:51,729
Hiding his bridle behind him,
Shorty walked to the riverbank,

1148
00:48:51,729 --> 00:48:54,929
where the pony was switching his long
tail in the shade; and speaking

1149
00:48:54,929 --> 00:48:59,013
persuasively to him,
he came nearer, till he laid his hand on

1150
00:48:59,013 --> 00:49:03,678
Pedro’s dusky mane, which was many
shades darker than his hide.

1151
00:49:03,678 --> 00:49:06,663
He turned expectantly,
and his master came up to his

1152
00:49:06,663 --> 00:49:09,567
expectations with a piece of bread.

1153
00:49:09,567 --> 00:49:11,027
“Eats that, does he?”

1154
00:49:11,027 --> 00:49:13,818
said Balaam, over the bars.

1155
00:49:13,818 --> 00:49:16,438
“Likes the salt,” said Shorty.

1156
00:49:16,438 --> 00:49:18,869
“Now, n-n-ow, here!

1157
00:49:18,869 --> 00:49:21,296
Yu’ don’t guess yu’ll
be bridled, don’t you?

1158
00:49:21,296 --> 00:49:23,641
Open your teeth!

1159
00:49:23,641 --> 00:49:27,815
Yu’d like to play yu’ was nobody’s
horse and live private?

1160
00:49:27,815 --> 00:49:31,072
Or maybe yu’d prefer ownin’ a saloon?”

1161
00:49:31,072 --> 00:49:36,094
Pedro evidently enjoyed this talk,
and the dodging he made about the bit.

1162
00:49:36,094 --> 00:49:39,807
Once fairly in his mouth,
he accepted the inevitable,

1163
00:49:39,807 --> 00:49:42,746
and followed Shorty to the bars.

1164
00:49:42,746 --> 00:49:46,732
Then Shorty turned and extended his hand.

1165
00:49:46,732 --> 00:49:47,381
“Shake!”

1166
00:49:47,381 --> 00:49:51,697
he said to his pony, who lifted his
forefoot quietly and put it

1167
00:49:51,697 --> 00:49:53,401
in his master’s hand.

1168
00:49:53,401 --> 00:49:58,675
Then the master tickled his nose,
and he wrinkled it and flattened his

1169
00:49:58,675 --> 00:50:01,051
ears, pretending to bite.

1170
00:50:01,051 --> 00:50:06,042
His face wore an expression of knowing
relish over this performance.

1171
00:50:06,042 --> 00:50:09,570
“Now the other hoof,”
said Shorty; and the horse and master

1172
00:50:09,570 --> 00:50:11,046
shook hands with their left.

1173
00:50:11,046 --> 00:50:14,552
“I learned him that,”
said the cowboy, with

1174
00:50:14,552 --> 00:50:16,161
pride and affection.

1175
00:50:16,161 --> 00:50:21,247
“Say, Pede,” he continued,
in Pedro’s ear, “ain’t yu’ the best

1176
00:50:21,247 --> 00:50:23,163
little horse in the country?

1177
00:50:23,163 --> 00:50:24,212
What?

1178
00:50:24,212 --> 00:50:25,428
Here, now!

1179
00:50:25,428 --> 00:50:27,775
Keep out of that, you deadbeat!

1180
00:50:27,775 --> 00:50:29,169
There ain’t no more bread.”

1181
00:50:29,169 --> 00:50:32,229
He pinched the pony’s nose,
one quarter of which was

1182
00:50:32,229 --> 00:50:33,669
wedged into his pocket.

1183
00:50:33,669 --> 00:50:36,151
“Quite a lady’s little pet!”

1184
00:50:36,151 --> 00:50:39,278
said Balaam, with the rasp in his voice.

1185
00:50:39,278 --> 00:50:41,833
“Pity this isn’t New York,
now, where there’s a big

1186
00:50:41,833 --> 00:50:43,944
market for harmless horses.

1187
00:50:43,944 --> 00:50:46,400
Gee-gees, the children call them.”

1188
00:50:46,400 --> 00:50:50,077
“He ain’t no gee-gee,”
said Shorty, offended.

1189
00:50:50,077 --> 00:50:54,189
“He’ll beat any cow-pony
workin’ you’ve got.

1190
00:50:54,189 --> 00:50:58,425
Yu’ can turn him on a half-dollar.

1191
00:50:58,425 --> 00:51:00,759
Don’t need to touch the reins.

1192
00:51:00,759 --> 00:51:04,674
Hang ’em on one finger and swing your
body, and he’ll turn.”

1193
00:51:04,674 --> 00:51:08,709
Balaam knew this, and he knew that the
pony was only a four-year-old.

1194
00:51:08,709 --> 00:51:13,502
“Well,” he said, “Drybone’s had
no circus this season.

1195
00:51:13,502 --> 00:51:15,942
Maybe they’d buy tickets to see Pedro.

1196
00:51:15,942 --> 00:51:17,249
He’s good for that, anyway.”

1197
00:51:17,249 --> 00:51:19,208
Shorty became gloomy.

1198
00:51:19,208 --> 00:51:22,166
The Virginian was grimly smoking.

1199
00:51:22,166 --> 00:51:28,319
Here was something else going on not to
his taste, but none of his business.

1200
00:51:28,319 --> 00:51:31,312
“Try a circus,” persisted Balaam.

1201
00:51:31,312 --> 00:51:35,404
“Alter your plans for spending cash in
town, and make a little money instead.”

1202
00:51:35,404 --> 00:51:40,215
Shorty having no plans to alter and no
cash to spend, grew still more gloomy.

1203
00:51:40,215 --> 00:51:41,978
“What’ll you take for that pony?”

1204
00:51:41,978 --> 00:51:42,989
said Balaam.

1205
00:51:42,989 --> 00:51:45,374
Shorty spoke up instantly.

1206
00:51:45,374 --> 00:51:49,491
“A hundred dollars couldn’t buy that
piece of stale mud off his back,”

1207
00:51:49,491 --> 00:51:54,600
he asserted, looking off
into the sky grandiosely.

1208
00:51:54,600 --> 00:51:58,272
But Balaam looked at Shorty,
“You keep the mud,” he said,

1209
00:51:58,272 --> 00:52:01,213
“and I’ll give you thirty
dollars for the horse.”

1210
00:52:01,213 --> 00:52:04,306
Shorty did a little professional
laughing, and began to

1211
00:52:04,306 --> 00:52:05,542
walk toward his saddle.

1212
00:52:05,542 --> 00:52:09,729
“Give you thirty dollars,”
repeated Balaam, picking a stone up and

1213
00:52:09,729 --> 00:52:11,249
slinging it into the river.

1214
00:52:11,249 --> 00:52:13,100
“How far do yu’ call it to Drybone?”

1215
00:52:13,100 --> 00:52:18,345
Shorty remarked, stooping to investigate
the bucking-strap on his saddle⁠—a

1216
00:52:18,345 --> 00:52:21,879
superfluous performance,
for Pedro never bucked.

1217
00:52:21,879 --> 00:52:24,332
“You won’t have to walk,” said Balaam.

1218
00:52:24,332 --> 00:52:27,790
“Stay all night, and I’ll send you over
comfortably in the morning,

1219
00:52:27,790 --> 00:52:29,475
when the wagon goes for the mail.”

1220
00:52:29,475 --> 00:52:30,745
“Walk?”

1221
00:52:30,745 --> 00:52:31,853
Shorty retorted.

1222
00:52:31,853 --> 00:52:34,531
“Drybone’s twenty-five miles.

1223
00:52:34,531 --> 00:52:37,794
Pedro’ll put me there in three hours and
not know he done it.”

1224
00:52:37,794 --> 00:52:39,865
He lifted the saddle on the horse’s back.

1225
00:52:39,865 --> 00:52:41,572
“Come, Pedro,” said he.

1226
00:52:41,572 --> 00:52:43,086
“Come, Pedro!”

1227
00:52:43,086 --> 00:52:44,557
mocked Balaam.

1228
00:52:44,557 --> 00:52:46,969
There followed a little silence.

1229
00:52:46,969 --> 00:52:51,871
“No, sir,” mumbled Shorty,
with his head under Pedro’s

1230
00:52:51,871 --> 00:52:54,524
belly, busily cinching.

1231
00:52:54,524 --> 00:52:57,925
“A hundred dollars is bottom figures.”

1232
00:52:57,925 --> 00:53:02,866
Balaam, in his turn, now duly performed
some professional laughing,

1233
00:53:02,866 --> 00:53:06,676
which was noted by Shorty
under the horse’s belly.

1234
00:53:06,676 --> 00:53:09,528
He stood up and squared round on Balaam.

1235
00:53:09,528 --> 00:53:13,151
“Well, then,” he said,
“what’ll yu give for him?”

1236
00:53:13,151 --> 00:53:17,805
“Thirty dollars,” said Balaam,
looking far off into the sky,

1237
00:53:17,805 --> 00:53:18,914
as Shorty had looked.

1238
00:53:18,914 --> 00:53:21,945
“Oh, come, now,” expostulated Shorty.

1239
00:53:21,945 --> 00:53:26,065
It was he who now did the feeling for an
offer and this was what

1240
00:53:26,065 --> 00:53:27,322
Balaam liked to see.

1241
00:53:27,322 --> 00:53:30,985
“Why yes,” he said, “thirty,”
and looked surprised that he should have

1242
00:53:30,985 --> 00:53:32,625
to mention the sum so often.

1243
00:53:32,625 --> 00:53:36,336
“I thought yu’d quit them first figures,”
said the cowpuncher,

1244
00:53:36,336 --> 00:53:39,136
“for yu’ can see I ain’t goin’
to look at em.”

1245
00:53:39,136 --> 00:53:43,830
Balaam climbed on the fence and sat there
“I’m not crying for your

1246
00:53:43,830 --> 00:53:46,440
Pedro,” he observed dispassionately.

1247
00:53:46,440 --> 00:53:52,194
“Only it struck me you were dead broke,
and wanted to raise cash and keep

1248
00:53:52,194 --> 00:53:56,871
yourself going till you hunted up a job
and could buy him back.”

1249
00:53:56,871 --> 00:54:00,074
He hooked his right thumb
inside his waistcoat pocket.

1250
00:54:00,074 --> 00:54:03,221
“But I’m not cryin’ for him,” he repeated.

1251
00:54:03,221 --> 00:54:05,778
“He’d stay right here, of course.

1252
00:54:05,778 --> 00:54:10,665
I wouldn’t part with him.

1253
00:54:10,665 --> 00:54:12,679
Why does he stand that way?

1254
00:54:12,679 --> 00:54:13,325
Hello!”

1255
00:54:13,325 --> 00:54:16,976
Balaam suddenly straightened himself,
like a man who has made a discovery.

1256
00:54:16,976 --> 00:54:18,588
“Hello, what?”

1257
00:54:18,588 --> 00:54:20,946
said Shorty, on the defensive.

1258
00:54:20,946 --> 00:54:25,079
Balaam was staring at Pedro
with a judicial frown.

1259
00:54:25,079 --> 00:54:29,622
Then he stuck out a finger at the horse,
keeping the thumb hooked in his pocket.

1260
00:54:29,622 --> 00:54:35,899
So meagre a gesture was felt by the
ruffled Shorty to be no just way

1261
00:54:35,899 --> 00:54:37,012
to point at Pedro.

1262
00:54:37,012 --> 00:54:38,968
“What’s the matter with
that foreleg there?”

1263
00:54:38,968 --> 00:54:39,968
said Balaam.

1264
00:54:39,968 --> 00:54:41,196
“Which?

1265
00:54:41,196 --> 00:54:42,977
Nothin’s the matter with it!”

1266
00:54:42,977 --> 00:54:43,887
snapped Shorty.

1267
00:54:43,887 --> 00:54:49,624
Balaam climbed down from his fence and
came over with elaborate deliberation.

1268
00:54:49,624 --> 00:54:54,820
He passed his hand up and
down the off foreleg.

1269
00:54:54,820 --> 00:54:58,048
Then he spit slenderly.

1270
00:54:58,048 --> 00:54:59,377
“Mm!”

1271
00:54:59,377 --> 00:55:03,427
he said thoughtfully;
and added, with a shade of sadness,

1272
00:55:03,427 --> 00:55:06,871
“that’s always to be expected when
they’re worked too young.”

1273
00:55:06,871 --> 00:55:10,644
Shorty slid his hand slowly
over the disputed leg.

1274
00:55:10,644 --> 00:55:12,326
“What’s to be expected?”

1275
00:55:12,326 --> 00:55:14,613
he inquired⁠—“that they’ll eat hearty?

1276
00:55:14,613 --> -1:59:59,000
Well, he does.

1277
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1278
00:55:15,690 --> 00:55:20,683
At this retort the Virginian permitted
himself to laugh in audible sympathy.

1279
00:55:20,683 --> 00:55:23,910
“Sprung,” continued Balaam, with a sigh.

1280
00:55:23,910 --> 00:55:27,774
“Whirling round short when his bones
were soft did that.

1281
00:55:27,774 --> 00:55:28,616
Yes.”

1282
00:55:28,616 --> 00:55:29,990
“Sprung!”

1283
00:55:29,990 --> 00:55:32,480
Shorty said, with a bark of indignation.

1284
00:55:32,480 --> 00:55:35,479
“Come on, Pede; you and
me’ll spring for town.”

1285
00:55:35,479 --> 00:55:40,044
He caught the horn of the saddle,
and as he swung into place the horse

1286
00:55:40,044 --> 00:55:41,684
rushed away with him.

1287
00:55:41,684 --> 00:55:42,551
“O-ee!

1288
00:55:42,551 --> 00:55:44,358
yoi-yup, yup, yup!”

1289
00:55:44,358 --> 00:55:47,822
sang Shorty, in the shrill cow dialect.

1290
00:55:47,822 --> 00:55:52,690
He made Pedro play an exhibition game of
speed, bringing him round close to

1291
00:55:52,690 --> 00:55:56,050
Balaam in a wide circle,
and then he vanished in dust down

1292
00:55:56,050 --> 00:55:57,290
the left-bank trail.

1293
00:55:57,290 --> 00:55:59,850
Balaam looked after him
and laughed harshly.

1294
00:55:59,850 --> 00:56:03,010
He had seen trout dash about like that
when the hook in their

1295
00:56:03,010 --> 00:56:04,806
jaw first surprised them.

1296
00:56:04,806 --> 00:56:09,330
He knew Shorty would show the pony off,
and he knew Shorty’s love for Pedro was

1297
00:56:09,330 --> 00:56:11,313
not equal to his need of money.

1298
00:56:11,313 --> 00:56:14,570
He called to one of his men,
asked something about the dam at the

1299
00:56:14,570 --> 00:56:19,169
mouth of the canyon,
where the main irrigation ditch began,

1300
00:56:19,169 --> 00:56:23,128
made a remark about the prolonged
drought, and then walked to his dining-

1301
00:56:23,128 --> 00:56:26,960
room door, where, as he
expected, Shorty met him.

1302
00:56:26,960 --> 00:56:29,640
“Say,” said the youth,
“do you consider that’s any way to talk

1303
00:56:29,640 --> 00:56:31,650
about a good horse?”

1304
00:56:31,650 --> 00:56:34,845
“Any dude could see the
leg’s sprung,” said Balaam.

1305
00:56:34,845 --> 00:56:37,645
But he looked at Pedro’s shoulder,
which was well laid back;

1306
00:56:37,645 --> 00:56:42,019
and he admired his points,
dark in contrast with the buckskin,

1307
00:56:42,019 --> 00:56:44,216
and also the width between the eyes.

1308
00:56:44,216 --> 00:56:47,856
“Now you know,” whined Shorty,
“that it ain’t sprung any more

1309
00:56:47,856 --> 00:56:49,376
than your leg’s cork.

1310
00:56:49,376 --> 00:56:53,926
If you mean the right leg ain’t plumb
straight, I can tell you he was born so.

1311
00:56:53,926 --> 00:56:57,148
That don’t make no difference,
for it ain’t weak.

1312
00:56:57,148 --> 00:56:58,559
Try him onced.

1313
00:56:58,559 --> 00:57:02,282
Just as sound and strong as iron.

1314
00:57:02,282 --> 00:57:04,007
Never stumbles.

1315
00:57:04,007 --> 00:57:07,329
And he don’t never go to jumpin’ with yu’.

1316
00:57:07,329 --> 00:57:09,179
He’s kind and he’s smart.”

1317
00:57:09,179 --> 00:57:13,348
And the master petted his pony,
who lifted a hoof for another handshake.

1318
00:57:13,348 --> 00:57:17,427
Of course Balaam had never thought the
leg was sprung, and he now took on an

1319
00:57:17,427 --> 00:57:22,685
unprejudiced air of wanting to believe
Shorty’s statements if he only could.

1320
00:57:22,685 --> 00:57:27,015
“Maybe there’s two years’ work left in
that leg,” he now observed.

1321
00:57:27,015 --> 00:57:29,827
“Better give your hawss away,
Shorty,” said the Virginian.

1322
00:57:29,827 --> 00:57:31,667
“Is this your deal, my friend?”

1323
00:57:31,667 --> 00:57:32,947
inquired Balaam.

1324
00:57:32,947 --> 00:57:35,865
And he slanted his bullet
head at the Virginian.

1325
00:57:35,865 --> 00:57:38,925
“Give him away, Shorty,”
drawled the Southerner.

1326
00:57:38,925 --> 00:57:40,273
“His laig is busted.

1327
00:57:40,273 --> 00:57:40,709
Mr.

1328
00:57:40,709 --> 00:57:42,072
Balaam says so.”

1329
00:57:42,072 --> 00:57:45,015
Balaam’s face grew evil with baffled fury.

1330
00:57:45,015 --> 00:57:48,818
But the Virginian was
gravely considering Pedro.

1331
00:57:48,818 --> 00:57:52,059
He, too, was not pleased.

1332
00:57:52,059 --> 00:57:53,616
But he could not interfere.

1333
00:57:53,616 --> 00:57:57,522
Already he had overstepped the
code in these matters.

1334
00:57:57,522 --> 00:58:03,549
He would have dearly liked⁠—for reasons
good and bad, spite and mercy mingled⁠—

1335
00:58:03,549 --> 00:58:03,586
to

1336
00:58:03,586 --> 00:58:08,568
have spoiled Balaam’s market,
to have offered a reasonable or even an

1337
00:58:08,568 --> 00:58:11,448
unreasonable price for Pedro,
and taken possession

1338
00:58:11,448 --> 00:58:13,601
of the horse himself.

1339
00:58:13,601 --> 00:58:15,613
But this might not be.

1340
00:58:15,613 --> 00:58:21,177
In bets, in card games,
in all horse transactions and other

1341
00:58:21,177 --> 00:58:26,586
matters of similar business,
a man must take care of himself,

1342
00:58:26,586 --> 00:58:32,558
and wiser onlookers must suppress their
wisdom and hold their peace.

1343
00:58:32,558 --> 00:58:34,524
That evening Shorty again had a cigar.

1344
00:58:34,524 --> 00:58:39,180
He had parted with Pedro for forty
dollars, a striped Mexican blanket,

1345
00:58:39,180 --> 00:58:41,229
and a pair of spurs.

1346
00:58:41,229 --> 00:58:45,217
Undressing over in the bunk house,
he said to the Virginian,

1347
00:58:45,217 --> 00:58:50,345
“I’ll sure buy Pedro back off him just
as soon as ever I rustle some cash.”

1348
00:58:50,345 --> 00:58:51,618
The Virginian grunted.

1349
00:58:51,618 --> 00:58:55,145
He was thinking he should have to travel
hard to get the horses to the Judge by

1350
00:58:55,145 --> 00:58:59,305
the 30th; and below that thought lay his
aching disappointment and his

1351
00:58:59,305 --> 00:59:00,945
longing for Bear Creek.

1352
00:59:00,945 --> 00:59:05,865
In the early dawn Shorty sat up among his
blankets on the floor of the bunk house

1353
00:59:05,865 --> 00:59:09,343
and saw the various sleepers coiled or
sprawled in their beds;

1354
00:59:09,343 --> 00:59:12,799
their breathing had not yet grown
restless at the nearing of day.

1355
00:59:12,799 --> 00:59:16,671
He stepped to the door carefully,
and saw the crowding blackbirds begin

1356
00:59:16,671 --> 00:59:20,707
their walk and chatter in the mud of the
littered and trodden corrals.

1357
00:59:20,707 --> 00:59:26,228
From beyond among the cottonwoods,
came continually the smooth unemphatic

1358
00:59:26,228 --> 00:59:30,348
sound of the doves answering each other
invisibly; and against the empty ridge

1359
00:59:30,348 --> 00:59:34,664
of the river-bluff lay the moon,
no longer shining, for there was

1360
00:59:34,664 --> 00:59:38,031
established a new light through the sky.

1361
00:59:38,031 --> 00:59:41,042
Pedro stood in the pasture
close to the bars.

1362
00:59:41,042 --> 00:59:45,297
The cowboy slowly closed the door behind
him, and sitting down on the step,

1363
00:59:45,297 --> 00:59:49,495
drew his money out and idly handled it,
taking no comfort just

1364
00:59:49,495 --> 00:59:50,921
then from its possession.

1365
00:59:50,921 --> 00:59:55,998
Then he put it back, and after dragging
on his boots, crossed to the pasture,

1366
00:59:55,998 --> 01:00:01,777
and held a last talk with his pony,
brushing the cakes of mud from his hide

1367
01:00:01,777 --> 01:00:04,196
where he had rolled,
and passing a lingering

1368
01:00:04,196 --> 01:00:05,648
hand over his mane.

1369
01:00:05,648 --> 01:00:10,041
As the sounds of the morning came
increasingly from tree and plain,

1370
01:00:10,041 --> 01:00:13,714
Shorty glanced back to see that no one
was yet out of the cabin,

1371
01:00:13,714 --> 01:00:17,663
and then put his arms round the horse’s
neck, laying his head against him.

1372
01:00:17,663 --> 01:00:23,956
For a moment the cowboy’s insignificant
face was exalted by the emotion he would

1373
01:00:23,956 --> 01:00:26,155
never have let others see.

1374
01:00:26,155 --> 01:00:30,609
He hugged tight this animal,
who was dearer to his heart than

1375
01:00:30,609 --> 01:00:32,809
anybody in the world.

1376
01:00:32,809 --> -1:59:59,000
“Goodbye, Pedro,” he said⁠—“goodbye.

1377
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1378
01:00:39,672 --> 01:00:41,770
Pedro looked for bread.

1379
01:00:41,770 --> 01:00:46,242
“No,” said his master,
sorrowfully, “not any more.

1380
01:00:46,242 --> 01:00:48,871
Yu’ know well I’d give it yu’ if I had it.

1381
01:00:48,871 --> 01:00:51,963
You and me didn’t figure on
this, did we, Pedro?

1382
01:00:51,963 --> 01:00:52,641
Goodbye!”

1383
01:00:52,641 --> 01:00:55,977
He hugged his pony again,
and got as far as the bars of the

1384
01:00:55,977 --> 01:00:58,057
pasture, but returned once more.

1385
01:00:58,057 --> 01:01:02,080
“Goodbye, my little horse,
my dear horse, my little,

1386
01:01:02,080 --> 01:01:06,345
little Pedro,” he said,
as his tears wet the pony’s neck.

1387
01:01:06,345 --> 01:01:10,321
Then he wiped them with his hand,
and got himself back to the bunk house.

1388
01:01:10,321 --> 01:01:13,730
After breakfast he and his belongings
departed to Drybone,

1389
01:01:13,730 --> 01:01:18,201
and Pedro from his field calmly watched
this departure; for horses must

1390
01:01:18,201 --> 01:01:23,601
recognize even less than men the black
corners that their destinies turn.

1391
01:01:23,601 --> 01:01:27,802
The pony stopped feeding to look at the
mail-wagon pass by; but the master

1392
01:01:27,802 --> 01:01:31,641
sitting in the wagon forebore
to turn his head.

1393
01:01:31,641 --> 01:01:32,760
CHAPTER XXVI

1394
01:01:32,760 --> 01:01:34,416
Balaam and Pedro

1395
01:01:34,416 --> 01:01:39,476
Resigned to wait for the Judge’s horses,
Balaam went into his office this dry,

1396
01:01:39,476 --> 01:01:44,162
bright morning and read nine accumulated
newspapers; for he was behindhand.

1397
01:01:44,162 --> 01:01:49,200
Then he rode out on the ditches,
and met his man returning with the

1398
01:01:49,200 --> 01:01:52,002
troublesome animals at last.

1399
01:01:52,002 --> 01:01:54,642
He hastened home and sent
for the Virginian.

1400
01:01:54,642 --> 01:01:55,951
He had made a decision.

1401
01:01:55,951 --> 01:01:59,553
“See here,” he said; “those
horses are coming.

1402
01:01:59,553 --> 01:02:02,760
What trail would you take
over to the Judge’s?”

1403
01:02:02,760 --> 01:02:08,852
“Shortest trail’s right through the Bow
Laig Mountains,” said the foreman,

1404
01:02:08,852 --> 01:02:11,430
in his gentle voice.

1405
01:02:11,430 --> 01:02:13,349
“Guess you’re right.

1406
01:02:13,349 --> 01:02:15,469
It’s dinnertime.

1407
01:02:15,469 --> 01:02:18,149
We’ll start right afterward.

1408
01:02:18,149 --> 01:02:22,946
We’ll make Little Muddy Crossing by
sundown, and Sunk Creek tomorrow,

1409
01:02:22,946 --> 01:02:25,606
and the next day’ll see us through.

1410
01:02:25,606 --> 01:02:27,649
Can a wagon get through
Sunk Creek Canyon?”

1411
01:02:27,649 --> 01:02:29,051
The Virginian smiled.

1412
01:02:29,051 --> 01:02:32,756
“I reckon it can’t, seh,
and stay resembling a wagon.”

1413
01:02:32,756 --> 01:02:37,996
Balaam told them to saddle Pedro and one
packhorse, and drive the bunch of horses

1414
01:02:37,996 --> 01:02:43,197
into a corral, roping the Judge’s two,
who proved extremely wild.

1415
01:02:43,197 --> 01:02:47,981
He had decided to take this journey
himself on remembering certain politics

1416
01:02:47,981 --> 01:02:50,124
soon to be rife in Cheyenne.

1417
01:02:50,124 --> 01:02:53,843
For Judge Henry was indeed a
greater man than Balaam.

1418
01:02:53,843 --> 01:02:59,404
This personally conducted return of the
horses would temper its tardiness,

1419
01:02:59,404 --> 01:03:05,349
and, moreover, the sight of some New
York visitors would be a good thing

1420
01:03:05,349 --> 01:03:10,944
after seven months of no warmer touch
with that metropolis than the Sunday

1421
01:03:10,944 --> 01:03:16,518
Herald, always eight days old when it
reached the Butte Creek Ranch.

1422
01:03:16,518 --> 01:03:21,233
They forded Butte Creek,
and, crossing the well-travelled trail

1423
01:03:21,233 --> 01:03:24,753
which follows down to Drybone,
turned their faces toward the

1424
01:03:24,753 --> 01:03:28,513
uninhabited country that began
immediately, as the ocean begins

1425
01:03:28,513 --> 01:03:29,993
off a sandy shore.

1426
01:03:29,993 --> 01:03:34,913
And as a single mast on which no sail is
shining stands at the horizon and seems

1427
01:03:34,913 --> 01:03:40,615
to add a loneliness to the surrounding
sea, so the long gray line of fence,

1428
01:03:40,615 --> 01:03:45,249
almost a mile away, that ended Balaam’s
land on this side the creek,

1429
01:03:45,249 --> 01:03:50,381
stretched along the waste ground and
added desolation to the plain.

1430
01:03:50,381 --> 01:03:56,598
No solitary watercourse with margin of
cottonwoods or willow thickets flowed

1431
01:03:56,598 --> 01:04:01,872
here to stripe the dingy,
yellow world with interrupting green,

1432
01:04:01,872 --> 01:04:06,415
nor were cattle to be seen dotting the
distance, nor moving objects at all,

1433
01:04:06,415 --> 01:04:11,311
nor any bird in the soundless air.

1434
01:04:11,311 --> 01:04:15,085
The last gate was shut by the Virginian,
who looked back at the pleasant trees of

1435
01:04:15,085 --> 01:04:19,498
the ranch, and then followed on in
single file across the alkali

1436
01:04:19,498 --> 01:04:20,953
of No Man’s Land.

1437
01:04:20,953 --> 01:04:23,136
No cloud was in the sky.

1438
01:04:23,136 --> 01:04:28,280
The desert’s grim noon shone sombrely
on flat and hill.

1439
01:04:28,280 --> 01:04:31,583
The sagebrush was dull like zinc.

1440
01:04:31,583 --> 01:04:36,165
Thick heat rose near at hand from the
caked alkali, and pale heat

1441
01:04:36,165 --> 01:04:38,044
shrouded the distant peaks.

1442
01:04:38,044 --> 01:04:39,797
There were five horses.

1443
01:04:39,797 --> 01:04:43,676
Balaam led on Pedro, his squat figure
stiff in the saddle,

1444
01:04:43,676 --> 01:04:46,601
but solid as a rock,
and tilted a little forward,

1445
01:04:46,601 --> 01:04:47,888
as his habit was.

1446
01:04:47,888 --> 01:04:52,779
One of the Judge’s horses came next,
a sorrel, dragging back continually on

1447
01:04:52,779 --> 01:04:54,819
the rope by which he was led.

1448
01:04:54,819 --> 01:04:58,859
After him ambled Balaam’s wise pack-
animal, carrying the light burden of two

1449
01:04:58,859 --> 01:05:01,231
days’ food and lodging.

1450
01:05:01,231 --> 01:05:05,511
She was an old mare who could still go
when she chose, but had been schooled by

1451
01:05:05,511 --> 01:05:09,761
the years, and kept the trail,
giving no trouble to the Virginian

1452
01:05:09,761 --> 01:05:10,776
who came behind her.

1453
01:05:10,776 --> 01:05:15,425
He also sat solid as a rock,
yet subtly bending to the struggles of

1454
01:05:15,425 --> 01:05:20,986
the wild horse he led,
as a steel spring bends and balances

1455
01:05:20,986 --> 01:05:22,434
and resumes its poise.

1456
01:05:22,434 --> 01:05:27,299
Thus they made but slow time,
and when they topped the last dull rise

1457
01:05:27,299 --> 01:05:34,046
of ground and looked down on the long
slant of ragged, caked earth to the

1458
01:05:34,046 --> 01:05:38,526
crossing of Little Muddy,
with its single tree and few mean

1459
01:05:38,526 --> 01:05:43,948
bushes, the final distance where
eyesight ends had deepened to violet

1460
01:05:43,948 --> 01:05:47,855
from the thin, steady blue they had
stared at for so many hours,

1461
01:05:47,855 --> 01:05:51,438
and all heat was gone
from the universal dryness.

1462
01:05:51,438 --> 01:05:55,072
The horses drank a long time from the
sluggish yellow water,

1463
01:05:55,072 --> 01:05:59,885
and its alkaline taste and warmth were
equally welcome to the men.

1464
01:05:59,885 --> 01:06:03,220
They built a little fire,
and when supper was ended,

1465
01:06:03,220 --> 01:06:08,295
smoked but a short while and in silence,
before they got in the blankets that

1466
01:06:08,295 --> 01:06:11,352
were spread in a smooth
place beside the water.

1467
01:06:11,352 --> 01:06:15,535
They had picketed the two horses of the
Judge in the best grass they could find,

1468
01:06:15,535 --> 01:06:19,376
letting the rest go free to find
pasture where they could.

1469
01:06:19,376 --> 01:06:23,445
When the first light came,
the Virginian attended to breakfast,

1470
01:06:23,445 --> 01:06:27,576
while Balaam rode away on the sorrel to
bring in the loose horses.

1471
01:06:27,576 --> 01:06:31,199
They had gone far out of sight,
and when he returned with them,

1472
01:06:31,199 --> 01:06:34,073
after some two hours, he was on Pedro.

1473
01:06:34,073 --> 01:06:38,138
Pedro was soaking with sweat,
and red froth creamed from his mouth.

1474
01:06:38,138 --> 01:06:41,267
The Virginian saw the horses must have
been hard to drive in,

1475
01:06:41,267 --> 01:06:45,537
especially after Balaam brought them the
wild sorrel as a leader.

1476
01:06:45,537 --> 01:06:49,170
“If you’d kep’ ridin’ him,
’stead of changin’ off on your hawss,

1477
01:06:49,170 --> 01:06:51,716
they’d have behaved quieter,”
said the foreman.

1478
01:06:51,716 --> 01:06:55,910
“That’s good seasonable
advice,” said Balaam, sarcastically.

1479
01:06:55,910 --> -1:59:59,000
“I could have told you that now.

1480
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1481
01:06:57,600 --> 01:07:01,212
“I could have told you when you started,”
said the Virginian, heating

1482
01:07:01,212 --> 01:07:02,772
the coffee for Balaam.

1483
01:07:02,772 --> 01:07:07,243
Balaam was eloquent on the outrageous
conduct of the horses.

1484
01:07:07,243 --> 01:07:11,526
He had come up with them evidently
striking back for Butte Creek,

1485
01:07:11,526 --> 01:07:13,993
with the old mare in the lead.

1486
01:07:13,993 --> 01:07:19,328
“But I soon showed her the road she was
to go,” he said, as he drove them

1487
01:07:19,328 --> 01:07:20,276
now to the water.

1488
01:07:20,276 --> 01:07:25,531
The Virginian noticed the slight limp of
the mare, and how her pastern was cut as

1489
01:07:25,531 --> 01:07:28,415
if with a stone or the sharp
heel of a boot.

1490
01:07:28,415 --> 01:07:31,610
“I guess she’ll not be in a hurry to
travel except when she’s

1491
01:07:31,610 --> 01:07:33,677
wanted to,” continued Balaam.

1492
01:07:33,677 --> 01:07:37,061
He sat down, and sullenly
poured himself some coffee.

1493
01:07:37,061 --> 01:07:40,349
“We’ll be in luck if we make any
Sunk Creek this night.”

1494
01:07:40,349 --> 01:07:43,621
He went on with his breakfast,
thinking aloud for the benefit of his

1495
01:07:43,621 --> 01:07:48,805
companion, who made no comments,
preferring silence to the discomfort of

1496
01:07:48,805 --> 01:07:54,038
talking with a man whose vindictive
humor was so thoroughly uppermost.

1497
01:07:54,038 --> 01:07:58,360
He did not even listen very attentively,
but continued his preparations for

1498
01:07:58,360 --> 01:08:02,922
departure, washing the dishes,
rolling the blankets,

1499
01:08:02,922 --> 01:08:07,435
and moving about in his usual way of
easy and visible good nature.

1500
01:08:07,435 --> 01:08:13,134
“Six o’clock, already,”
said Balaam, saddling the horses.

1501
01:08:13,134 --> 01:08:16,072
“And we’ll not get started
for ten minutes more.”

1502
01:08:16,072 --> 01:08:18,211
Then he came to Pedro.

1503
01:08:18,211 --> 01:08:21,014
“So you haven’t quit fooling
yet, haven’t you?”

1504
01:08:21,014 --> 01:08:24,779
he exclaimed, for the pony shrank as
he lifted the bridle.

1505
01:08:24,779 --> 01:08:26,884
“Take that for your sore mouth!”

1506
01:08:26,884 --> 01:08:30,941
and he rammed the bit in,
at which Pedro flung back and reared.

1507
01:08:30,941 --> 01:08:35,186
“Well, I never saw Pedro act that way
yet,” said the Virginian.

1508
01:08:35,186 --> 01:08:36,918
“Ah, rubbish!”

1509
01:08:36,918 --> 01:08:37,676
said Balaam.

1510
01:08:37,676 --> 01:08:39,229
“They’re all the same.

1511
01:08:39,229 --> 01:08:42,328
Not a bastard one but’s laying for his
chance to do for you.

1512
01:08:42,328 --> 01:08:45,059
Some’ll buck you off,
and some’ll roll with you,

1513
01:08:45,059 --> 01:08:47,607
and some’ll fight you
with their fore feet.

1514
01:08:47,607 --> 01:08:51,986
They may play good for a year,
but the Western pony’s man’s enemy,

1515
01:08:51,986 --> 01:08:55,124
and when he judges he’s got his chance,
he’s going to do his best.

1516
01:08:55,124 --> 01:08:57,884
And if you come out alive it
won’t be his fault.”

1517
01:08:57,884 --> 01:09:00,987
Balaam paused for a while, packing.

1518
01:09:00,987 --> 01:09:05,027
“You’ve got to keep them afraid of you,”
he said next; “that’s what you’ve got to

1519
01:09:05,027 --> 01:09:07,364
do if you don’t want trouble.

1520
01:09:07,364 --> 01:09:12,601
That Pedro horse there has been fed,
hand-fed, and fooled with like a damn

1521
01:09:12,601 --> 01:09:14,777
pet, and what’s that policy done?

1522
01:09:14,777 --> 01:09:19,349
Why, he goes ugly when he thinks it’s
time, and decides he’ll not drive any

1523
01:09:19,349 --> 01:09:21,213
horses into camp this morning.

1524
01:09:21,213 --> 01:09:23,351
He knows better now.”

1525
01:09:23,351 --> 01:09:24,549
“Mr.

1526
01:09:24,549 --> 01:09:29,324
Balaam,” said the Virginian,
“I’ll buy that hawss off yu’ right now.”

1527
01:09:29,324 --> 01:09:30,707
Balaam shook his head.

1528
01:09:30,707 --> 01:09:34,124
“You’ll not do that right now or any
other time,” said he.

1529
01:09:34,124 --> 01:09:35,572
“I happen to want him.”

1530
01:09:35,572 --> 01:09:37,505
The Virginian could do no more.

1531
01:09:37,505 --> 01:09:43,510
He had heard cowpunchers say to
refractory ponies, “You keep still,

1532
01:09:43,510 --> 01:09:44,868
or I’ll Balaam you!”

1533
01:09:44,868 --> 01:09:48,003
and he now understood the
aptness of the expression.

1534
01:09:48,003 --> 01:09:54,002
Meanwhile Balaam began to lead Pedro to
the creek for a last drink before

1535
01:09:54,002 --> 01:09:56,302
starting across the torrid drought.

1536
01:09:56,302 --> 01:09:59,902
The horse held back on the rein a little,
and Balaam turned and cut the

1537
01:09:59,902 --> 01:10:01,796
whip across his forehead.

1538
01:10:01,796 --> 01:10:06,507
A delay of forcing and backing followed,
while the Virginian,

1539
01:10:06,507 --> 01:10:08,685
already in the saddle, waited.

1540
01:10:08,685 --> 01:10:13,286
The minutes passed, and no immediate
prospect, apparently,

1541
01:10:13,286 --> 01:10:14,844
of getting nearer Sunk Creek.

1542
01:10:14,844 --> 01:10:17,324
“He ain’ goin’ to follow you while you’re
beatin’ his haid,” the

1543
01:10:17,324 --> 01:10:18,737
Southerner at length remarked.

1544
01:10:18,737 --> 01:10:22,519
“Do you think you can teach
me anything about horses?”

1545
01:10:22,519 --> 01:10:23,753
retorted Balaam.

1546
01:10:23,753 --> 01:10:27,701
“Well, it don’t look like I could,”
said the Virginian, lazily.

1547
01:10:27,701 --> 01:10:31,238
“Then don’t try it, so long as it’s not
your horse, my friend.”

1548
01:10:31,238 --> 01:10:34,439
Again the Southerner levelled
his eye on Balaam.

1549
01:10:34,439 --> 01:10:38,001
“All right,” he said,
in the same gentle voice.

1550
01:10:38,001 --> 01:10:40,592
“And don’t you call me your friend.

1551
01:10:40,592 --> 01:10:42,830
You’ve made that mistake twiced.”

1552
01:10:42,830 --> 01:10:46,547
The road was shadeless,
as it had been from the start,

1553
01:10:46,547 --> 01:10:48,604
and they could not travel fast.

1554
01:10:48,604 --> 01:10:53,484
During the first few hours all coolness
was driven out of the glassy morning,

1555
01:10:53,484 --> 01:10:58,977
and another day of illimitable sun
invested the world with its blaze.

1556
01:10:58,977 --> 01:11:04,565
The pale Bow Leg Range was coming nearer,
but its hard hot slants and rifts

1557
01:11:04,565 --> 01:11:09,100
suggested no sort of freshness,
and even the pines that spread for wide

1558
01:11:09,100 --> 01:11:14,387
miles along near the summit counted for
nothing in the distance and the glare,

1559
01:11:14,387 --> 01:11:19,797
but seemed mere patches
of dull dry discoloration.

1560
01:11:19,797 --> 01:11:23,555
No talk was exchanged between the two
travellers, for the cowpuncher had

1561
01:11:23,555 --> 01:11:27,885
nothing to say and Balaam was sulky,
so they moved along in silent endurance

1562
01:11:27,885 --> 01:11:31,135
of each other’s company and the
tedium of the journey.

1563
01:11:31,135 --> 01:11:36,134
But the slow succession of rise and fall
in the plain changed and shortened.

1564
01:11:36,134 --> 01:11:41,696
The earth’s surface became lumpy,
rising into mounds and knotted systems

1565
01:11:41,696 --> 01:11:47,566
of steep small hills cut apart by
staring gashes of sand,

1566
01:11:47,566 --> 01:11:51,545
where water poured in the spring
from the melting snow.

1567
01:11:51,545 --> 01:11:57,399
After a time they ascended through the
foothills till the plain below was for a

1568
01:11:57,399 --> 01:12:01,831
while concealed, but came again into
view in its entirety,

1569
01:12:01,831 --> 01:12:07,857
distant and a thing of the past,
while some magpies sailed down to meet

1570
01:12:07,857 --> 01:12:18,183
them from the new country
they were entering.

1571
01:12:18,183 --> 01:12:22,952
They passed up through a small
transparent forest of dead trees

1572
01:12:22,952 --> 01:12:27,446
standing stark and white,
and a little higher came on a line of

1573
01:12:27,446 --> 01:12:31,506
narrow moisture that crossed the way and
formed a stale pool among

1574
01:12:31,506 --> 01:12:32,898
some willow thickets.

1575
01:12:32,898 --> 01:12:38,289
They turned aside to water their horses,
and found near the pool a circular spot

1576
01:12:38,289 --> 01:12:44,486
of ashes and some poles lying,
and beside these a cage-like edifice of

1577
01:12:44,486 --> 01:12:46,987
willow wands built in the ground.

1578
01:12:46,987 --> 01:12:50,163
“Indian camp,” observed the Virginian.

1579
01:12:50,163 --> 01:12:54,398
There were the tracks of five or six
horses on the farther side of the pool,

1580
01:12:54,398 --> 01:12:58,840
and they did not come into the trail,
but led off among the rocks on some

1581
01:12:58,840 --> 01:13:00,070
system of their own.

1582
01:13:00,070 --> 01:13:02,433
“They’re about a week old,” said Balaam.

1583
01:13:02,433 --> 01:13:04,760
“It’s part of that outfit
that’s been hunting.”

1584
01:13:04,760 --> 01:13:08,656
“They’ve gone on to visit their
friends,” added the cowpuncher.

1585
01:13:08,656 --> 01:13:11,579
“Yes, on the Southern Reservation.

1586
01:13:11,579 --> 01:13:15,132
How far do you call Sunk Creek now?”

1587
01:13:15,132 --> 01:13:19,190
“Well,” said the Virginian,
calculating, “it’s mighty nigh fo’ty

1588
01:13:19,190 --> 01:13:23,312
miles from Muddy Crossin’, an’ I
reckon we’ve come eighteen.”

1589
01:13:23,312 --> 01:13:23,994
“Just about.

1590
01:13:23,994 --> 01:13:25,272
It’s noon.”

1591
01:13:25,272 --> 01:13:27,575
Balaam snapped his watch shut.

1592
01:13:27,575 --> 01:13:30,047
“We’ll rest here till 12:30.”

1593
01:13:30,047 --> 01:13:32,657
When it was time to go,
the Virginian looked

1594
01:13:32,657 --> 01:13:34,777
musingly at the mountains.

1595
01:13:34,777 --> 01:13:38,803
“We’ll need to travel right smart to get
through the canyon tonight,” he said.

1596
01:13:38,803 --> 01:13:42,228
“Tell you what,” said Balaam;
“we’ll rope the Judge’s horses together

1597
01:13:42,228 --> 01:13:43,729
and drive ’em in front of us.

1598
01:13:43,729 --> 01:13:45,051
That’ll make speed.”

1599
01:13:45,051 --> 01:13:46,930
“Mightn’t they get away on us?”

1600
01:13:46,930 --> 01:13:48,228
objected the Virginian.

1601
01:13:48,228 --> 01:13:49,835
“They’re pow’ful wild.”

1602
01:13:49,835 --> 01:13:53,056
“They can’t get away from me,
I guess,” said Balaam,

1603
01:13:53,056 --> 01:13:54,722
and the arrangement was adopted.

