2086
01:42:42,981 --> 01:42:46,716
For I’ve told yu’ you were
going to love me.

2087
01:42:46,716 --> 01:42:50,377
You are goin’ to learn back the thing
you have taught me.

2088
01:42:50,377 --> 01:42:55,122
I’m not askin’ anything now;
I don’t want you to speak a word to me.

2089
01:42:55,122 --> -1:59:59,000
But I’m never goin’ to quit till ‘next
time’ is no more

2090
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
,

2091
01:42:58,257 --> 01:42:58,417
and

2092
01:42:58,417 --> 01:43:00,377
it’s ‘all the time’ for you and me.”

2093
01:43:00,377 --> 01:43:03,953
With that he had ridden away,
not even touching her hand.

2094
01:43:03,953 --> 01:43:08,830
Long after he had gone she was still in
her chair, her eyes lingering upon his

2095
01:43:08,830 --> 01:43:11,871
flowers, those yellow cups
of the prickly pear.

2096
01:43:11,871 --> 01:43:17,031
At length she had risen impatiently,
caught up the flowers,

2097
01:43:17,031 --> 01:43:20,580
gone with them to the open window⁠—and
then, after all, set them

2098
01:43:20,580 --> 01:43:22,620
with pains in water.

2099
01:43:22,620 --> 01:43:25,218
But today Bear Creek was over.

2100
01:43:25,218 --> 01:43:26,614
She was going home now.

2101
01:43:26,614 --> 01:43:29,360
By the week’s end she would be started.

2102
01:43:29,360 --> 01:43:33,946
By the time the mail brought him her
goodbye letter she would be gone.

2103
01:43:33,946 --> 01:43:34,989
She had acted.

2104
01:43:34,989 --> 01:43:39,255
To Bear Creek, the neighborly,
the friendly, the not comprehending,

2105
01:43:39,255 --> 01:43:42,330
this move had come unlooked for,
and had brought regret.

2106
01:43:42,330 --> 01:43:46,625
Only one hard word had been spoken to
Molly, and that by her next-door

2107
01:43:46,625 --> 01:43:48,972
neighbor and kindest friend.

2108
01:43:48,972 --> 01:43:53,319
In Mrs. Taylor’s house the girl had daily
come and gone as a daughter,

2109
01:43:53,319 --> 01:43:56,231
and that lady reached the subject thus:⁠—

2110
01:43:56,231 --> 01:44:00,883
“When I took Taylor,”
said she, sitting by as Robert Browning

2111
01:44:00,883 --> 01:44:04,342
and Jane Austen were going into their
box, “I married for love.”

2112
01:44:04,342 --> 01:44:06,274
“Do you wish it had been money?”

2113
01:44:06,274 --> 01:44:08,877
said Molly, stooping to her industries.

2114
01:44:08,877 --> 01:44:11,533
“You know both of us better
than that, child.”

2115
01:44:11,533 --> 01:44:15,198
“I know I’ve seen people at home who
couldn’t possibly have

2116
01:44:15,198 --> 01:44:16,678
had any other reason.

2117
01:44:16,678 --> 01:44:18,542
They seemed satisfied, too.”

2118
01:44:18,542 --> 01:44:21,086
“Maybe the poor ignorant things were!”

2119
01:44:21,086 --> 01:44:23,958
“And so I have never been sure
how I might choose.”

2120
01:44:23,958 --> 01:44:26,112
“Yes, you are sure, deary.

2121
01:44:26,112 --> 01:44:27,406
Don’t you think I know you?

2122
01:44:27,406 --> 01:44:30,658
And when it comes over Taylor once in a
while, and he tells me I’m the best

2123
01:44:30,658 --> 01:44:34,141
thing in his life, and I tell him he
ain’t merely the best thing but the only

2124
01:44:34,141 --> 01:44:39,520
thing in mine⁠—him and the children⁠—
why, we just agree we’d do it all over

2125
01:44:39,520 --> 01:44:41,802
the same way if we had the chance.”

2126
01:44:41,802 --> 01:44:43,881
Molly continued to be industrious.

2127
01:44:43,881 --> 01:44:47,706
“And that’s why,” said Mrs. Taylor,
“I want every girl that’s anything to me

2128
01:44:47,706 --> 01:44:49,805
to know her luck when it comes.

2129
01:44:49,805 --> 01:44:52,833
For I was that near telling
Taylor I wouldn’t!”

2130
01:44:52,833 --> 01:44:58,498
“If ever my luck comes,”
said Molly, with her back to her friend,

2131
01:44:58,498 --> 01:45:01,196
“I shall say ‘I will’ at once.”

2132
01:45:01,196 --> 01:45:03,405
“Then you’ll say it at
Bennington next week.”

2133
01:45:03,405 --> 01:45:04,641
Molly wheeled round.

2134
01:45:04,641 --> 01:45:07,086
“Why, you surely will.

2135
01:45:07,086 --> 01:45:10,586
Do you expect he’s going to stay here,
and you in Bennington?”

2136
01:45:10,586 --> 01:45:12,734
And the campaigner sat back in her chair.

2137
01:45:12,734 --> 01:45:13,374
“He?

2138
01:45:13,374 --> 01:45:14,414
Goodness!

2139
01:45:14,414 --> 01:45:14,881
Who is he?”

2140
01:45:14,881 --> 01:45:20,549
“Child, child, you’re talking cross today
because you’re at outs with yourself.

2141
01:45:20,549 --> 01:45:26,338
You’ve been at outs ever since you took
this idea of leaving the school and us

2142
01:45:26,338 --> 01:45:28,321
and everything this needless way.

2143
01:45:28,321 --> 01:45:30,241
You have not treated him right.

2144
01:45:30,241 --> 01:45:33,381
And why, I can’t make out to save me.

2145
01:45:33,381 --> 01:45:36,066
What have you found out all of a sudden?

2146
01:45:36,066 --> 01:45:39,701
If he was not good enough for you,
I⁠—But, oh, it’s a prime

2147
01:45:39,701 --> 01:45:41,683
one you’re losing, Molly.

2148
01:45:41,683 --> 01:45:46,722
When a man like that stays faithful to a
girl ’spite all the chances he gets,

2149
01:45:46,722 --> -1:59:59,000
her luck is come.

2150
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2151
01:45:47,749 --> 01:45:49,277
“Oh, my luck!

2152
01:45:49,277 --> -1:59:59,000
People have different notions of luck.

2153
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2154
01:45:52,920 --> 01:45:53,810
“Notions!”

2155
01:45:53,810 --> 01:45:55,931
“He has been very kind.”

2156
01:45:55,931 --> 01:45:56,619
“Kind!”

2157
01:45:56,619 --> 01:46:01,068
And now without further simmering,
Mrs. Taylor’s wrath boiled up and poured

2158
01:46:01,068 --> 01:46:03,298
copiously over Molly Wood.

2159
01:46:03,298 --> 01:46:04,351
“Kind!

2160
01:46:04,351 --> 01:46:07,029
There’s a word you shouldn’t use, my dear.

2161
01:46:07,029 --> 01:46:09,069
No doubt you can spell it.

2162
01:46:09,069 --> 01:46:12,625
But more than its spelling I
guess you don’t know.

2163
01:46:12,625 --> 01:46:17,875
The children can learn what it means from
some of the rest of us folks that don’t

2164
01:46:17,875 --> 01:46:19,430
spell so correct, maybe.”

2165
01:46:19,430 --> 01:46:20,144
“Mrs.

2166
01:46:20,144 --> 01:46:22,185
Taylor, Mrs. Taylor⁠—”

2167
01:46:22,185 --> 01:46:24,101
“I can’t wait, deary.

2168
01:46:24,101 --> 01:46:28,206
Since the roughness looks bigger to you
than the diamond, you had better

2169
01:46:28,206 --> 01:46:30,155
go back to Vermont.

2170
01:46:30,155 --> 01:46:32,967
I expect you’ll find better
grammar there, deary.”

2171
01:46:32,967 --> 01:46:37,117
The good dame stalked out,
and across to her own cabin,

2172
01:46:37,117 --> 01:46:40,332
and left the angry girl among her boxes.

2173
01:46:40,332 --> 01:46:43,931
It was in vain she fell to work upon them.

2174
01:46:43,931 --> 01:46:47,984
Presently something had to be done over
again, and when it was the box held

2175
01:46:47,984 --> 01:46:51,132
several chattels less
than before the readjustment.

2176
01:46:51,132 --> 01:46:56,667
She played a sort of desperate dominos to
fit these objects in the space,

2177
01:46:56,667 --> 01:47:01,292
but here were a paperweight,
a portfolio, with two wretched volumes

2178
01:47:01,292 --> 01:47:06,335
that no chink would harbor;
and letting them fall all at once,

2179
01:47:06,335 --> 01:47:11,103
she straightened herself,
still stormy with revolt,

2180
01:47:11,103 --> 01:47:15,863
eyes and cheeks still hot from the sting
of long-parried truth.

2181
01:47:15,863 --> 01:47:22,527
There, on her wall still,
was the miniature, the little silent

2182
01:47:22,527 --> 01:47:26,679
ancestress; and upon this face
the girl’s glance rested.

2183
01:47:26,679 --> 01:47:31,519
It was as if she appealed to Grandmother
Stark for support and comfort across the

2184
01:47:31,519 --> 01:47:34,412
hundred years which lay between them.

2185
01:47:34,412 --> 01:47:38,550
So the flaxen girl on the wall and she
among the boxes stood a moment face to

2186
01:47:38,550 --> 01:47:43,115
face in seeming communion,
and then the descendant turned

2187
01:47:43,115 --> 01:47:44,197
again to her work.

2188
01:47:44,197 --> 01:47:48,727
But after a desultory touch here and
there she drew a long breath and walked

2189
01:47:48,727 --> 01:47:49,701
to the open door.

2190
01:47:49,701 --> 01:47:52,921
What use was in finishing today,
when she had nearly a week?

2191
01:47:52,921 --> 01:47:57,906
This first spurt of toil had swept the
cabin bare of all indwelling charm,

2192
01:47:57,906 --> 01:47:59,716
and its look was chill.

2193
01:47:59,716 --> 01:48:03,380
Across the lane his horse,
the one he had “gentled” for

2194
01:48:03,380 --> 01:48:05,881
her, was grazing idly.

2195
01:48:05,881 --> 01:48:09,426
She walked there and caught him,
and led him to her gate.

2196
01:48:09,426 --> 01:48:09,804
Mrs.

2197
01:48:09,804 --> 01:48:13,715
Taylor saw her go in,
and soon come out in riding-dress;

2198
01:48:13,715 --> 01:48:17,794
and she watched the girl throw the
saddle on with quick ease⁠—the ease

2199
01:48:17,794 --> 01:48:18,719
he had taught her.

2200
01:48:18,719 --> 01:48:19,074
Mrs.

2201
01:48:19,074 --> 01:48:24,085
Taylor also saw the sharp cut she gave
the horse, and laughed grimly to herself

2202
01:48:24,085 --> 01:48:28,007
in her window as horse and rider
galloped into the beautiful

2203
01:48:28,007 --> 01:48:29,368
sunny loneliness.

