2263
01:52:35,747 --> 01:52:39,956
Next moment she had sprung up and was at
his saddle, searching,

2264
01:52:39,956 --> 01:52:45,388
then swiftly went on to her own and got
her small flask and was back beside him.

2265
01:52:45,388 --> 01:52:50,226
Here was the cold water he had sought,
and she put it against his forehead and

2266
01:52:50,226 --> 01:52:52,031
drenched the wounded shoulder with it.

2267
01:52:52,031 --> 01:52:56,032
Three times she tried to move him,
so he might lie more easy,

2268
01:52:56,032 --> 01:53:01,687
but his dead weight was too much,
and desisting, she sat close and raised

2269
01:53:01,687 --> 01:53:04,918
his head to let it rest against her.

2270
01:53:04,918 --> 01:53:09,000
Thus she saw the blood that was running
from in front of the shoulder also;

2271
01:53:09,000 --> 01:53:11,139
but she said no more about fainting.

2272
01:53:11,139 --> 01:53:15,419
She tore strips from her dress and soaked
them, keeping them cold and wet upon

2273
01:53:15,419 --> 01:53:21,316
both openings of his wound,
and she drew her pocketknife out and cut

2274
01:53:21,316 --> 01:53:23,237
his shirt away from the place.

2275
01:53:23,237 --> 01:53:28,774
As she continually rinsed and cleaned it,
she watched his eyelashes,

2276
01:53:28,774 --> 01:53:33,049
long and soft and thick,
but they did not stir.

2277
01:53:33,049 --> 01:53:37,168
Again she tried the flask,
but failed from being still too gentle,

2278
01:53:37,168 --> 01:53:41,145
and her searching eyes fell upon
ashes near the pool.

2279
01:53:41,145 --> 01:53:47,855
Still undispersed by the weather lay the
small charred ends of a fire he and she

2280
01:53:47,855 --> 01:53:52,120
had made once here together,
to boil coffee and fry trout.

2281
01:53:52,120 --> 01:53:55,545
She built another fire now,
and when the flames were going well,

2282
01:53:55,545 --> 01:54:00,113
filled her flask-cup from the spring and
set it to heat.

2283
01:54:00,113 --> 01:54:04,515
Meanwhile, she returned to nurse
his head and wound.

2284
01:54:04,515 --> 01:54:07,678
Her cold water had stopped the bleeding.

2285
01:54:07,678 --> 01:54:12,983
Then she poured her brandy in the
steaming cup, and, made rough by her

2286
01:54:12,983 --> 01:54:17,084
desperate helplessness,
forced some between his lips and teeth.

2287
01:54:17,084 --> 01:54:22,411
Instantly, almost, she felt the tremble
of life creeping back,

2288
01:54:22,411 --> 01:54:26,763
and as his deep eyes opened upon her she
sat still and mute.

2289
01:54:26,763 --> 01:54:31,817
But the gaze seemed luminous with an
unnoting calm, and she wondered if

2290
01:54:31,817 --> 01:54:36,012
perhaps he could not recognize her;
she watched this internal clearness of

2291
01:54:36,012 --> 01:54:40,766
his vision, scarcely daring to breathe,
until presently he began to speak,

2292
01:54:40,766 --> 01:54:44,955
with the same profound and clear
impersonality sounding in

2293
01:54:44,955 --> 01:54:47,786
his slowly uttered words.

2294
01:54:47,786 --> 01:54:51,693
“I thought they had found me.

2295
01:54:51,693 --> 01:54:56,796
I expected they were going to kill me.”

2296
01:54:56,796 --> 01:55:01,177
He stopped, and she gave him more of the
hot drink, which he took,

2297
01:55:01,177 --> 01:55:05,227
still lying and looking at her as if the
present did not reach his senses.

2298
01:55:05,227 --> 01:55:07,344
“I knew hands were touching me.

2299
01:55:07,344 --> 01:55:09,497
I reckon I was not dead.

2300
01:55:09,497 --> 01:55:14,087
I knew about them soon as they began,
only I could not interfere.”

2301
01:55:14,087 --> 01:55:15,005
He waited again.

2302
01:55:15,005 --> 01:55:18,166
“It is mighty strange where I have been.

2303
01:55:18,166 --> 01:55:19,600
No.

2304
01:55:19,600 --> 01:55:21,641
Mighty natural.”

2305
01:55:21,641 --> 01:55:26,996
Then he went back into his revery,
and lay with his eyes still full open

2306
01:55:26,996 --> 01:55:29,395
upon her where she sat motionless.

2307
01:55:29,395 --> 01:55:33,539
She began to feel a greater awe in this
living presence than when it had been

2308
01:55:33,539 --> 01:55:37,879
his body with an ice-cold hand;
and she quietly spoke his name,

2309
01:55:37,879 --> 01:55:40,439
venturing scarcely more than a whisper.

2310
01:55:40,439 --> 01:55:44,854
At this, some nearer thing
wakened in his look.

2311
01:55:44,854 --> 01:55:47,533
“But it was you all along,” he resumed.

2312
01:55:47,533 --> 01:55:49,197
“It is you now.

2313
01:55:49,197 --> 01:55:50,533
You must not stay⁠—”

2314
01:55:50,533 --> 01:55:54,392
Weakness overcame him,
and his eyes closed.

2315
01:55:54,392 --> 01:55:58,507
She sat ministering to him,
and when he roused again,

2316
01:55:58,507 --> 01:56:01,831
he began anxiously at once:
“You must not stay.

2317
01:56:01,831 --> 01:56:03,117
They would get you, too.”

2318
01:56:03,117 --> 01:56:07,835
She glanced at him with a sort of
fierceness, then reached for his pistol,

2319
01:56:07,835 --> 01:56:11,186
in which was nothing
but blackened empty cartridges.

2320
01:56:11,186 --> 01:56:15,699
She threw these out and drew six from his
belt, loaded the weapon,

2321
01:56:15,699 --> 01:56:17,400
and snapped shut its hinge.

2322
01:56:17,400 --> 01:56:22,146
“Please take it,” he said,
more anxious and more himself.

2323
01:56:22,146 --> 01:56:23,566
“I ain’t worth tryin’ to keep.

2324
01:56:23,566 --> 01:56:24,459
Look at me!”

2325
01:56:24,459 --> 01:56:25,405
“Are you giving up?”

2326
01:56:25,405 --> 01:56:29,275
she inquired, trying to put
scorn in her tone.

2327
01:56:29,275 --> 01:56:30,867
Then she seated herself.

2328
01:56:30,867 --> 01:56:33,608
“Where is the sense in both of us⁠—”

2329
01:56:33,608 --> 01:56:36,378
“You had better save your
strength,” she interrupted.

2330
01:56:36,378 --> 01:56:37,483
He tried to sit up.

2331
01:56:37,483 --> 01:56:38,608
“Lie down!”

2332
01:56:38,608 --> 01:56:39,598
she ordered.

2333
01:56:39,598 --> 01:56:42,573
He sank obediently, and began to smile.

2334
01:56:42,573 --> 01:56:46,670
When she saw that, she smiled too,
and unexpectedly took his hand.

2335
01:56:46,670 --> 01:56:48,667
“Listen, friend,” said she.

2336
01:56:48,667 --> 01:56:51,190
“Nobody shall get you,
and nobody shall get me.

2337
01:56:51,190 --> 01:56:52,905
Now take some more brandy.”

2338
01:56:52,905 --> 01:56:56,180
“It must be noon,” said the cowpuncher,
when she had drawn her

2339
01:56:56,180 --> 01:56:57,300
hand away from him.

2340
01:56:57,300 --> 01:57:03,294
“I remember it was dark when⁠—when⁠—
when I can remember.

2341
01:57:03,294 --> 01:57:06,625
I reckon they were scared to follow me in
so close to settlers.

2342
01:57:06,625 --> -1:59:59,000
Else they would have been here.

2343
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2344
01:57:09,275 --> 01:57:11,885
“You must rest,” she observed.

2345
01:57:11,885 --> 01:57:15,297
She broke the soft ends of some
evergreen, and putting them beneath his

2346
01:57:15,297 --> 01:57:19,671
head, went to the horses,
loosened the cinches,

2347
01:57:19,671 --> 01:57:23,002
took off the bridles,
led them to drink, and

2348
01:57:23,002 --> 01:57:24,173
picketed them to feed.

2349
01:57:24,173 --> 01:57:28,689
Further still, to leave nothing undone
which she could herself manage,

2350
01:57:28,689 --> 01:57:31,865
she took the horses’ saddles off to
refold the blankets when the time should

2351
01:57:31,865 --> 01:57:34,023
come, and meanwhile brought them for
him.

2352
01:57:34,023 --> 01:57:36,376
But he put them away from him.

2353
01:57:36,376 --> 01:57:39,506
He was sitting up against a rock,
stronger evidently, and

2354
01:57:39,506 --> 01:57:41,003
asking for cold water.

2355
01:57:41,003 --> 01:57:44,666
His head was fire-hot,
and the paleness beneath his swarthy

2356
01:57:44,666 --> 01:57:47,555
skin had changed to a deepening flush.

2357
01:57:47,555 --> 01:57:49,564
“Only five miles!”

2358
01:57:49,564 --> 01:57:51,618
she said to him, bathing his head.

2359
01:57:51,618 --> 01:57:52,583
“Yes.

2360
01:57:52,583 --> 01:57:55,219
I must hold it steady,”
he answered, waving his

2361
01:57:55,219 --> 01:57:56,290
hand at the cliff.

2362
01:57:56,290 --> 01:57:59,774
She told him to try and keep it steady
until they got home.

2363
01:57:59,774 --> 01:58:01,224
“Yes,” he repeated.

2364
01:58:01,224 --> 01:58:02,978
“Only five miles.

2365
01:58:02,978 --> 01:58:04,851
But it’s fightin’ to turn around.”

2366
01:58:04,851 --> 01:58:08,251
Half aware that he was becoming
lightheaded, he looked from the rock to

2367
01:58:08,251 --> 01:58:11,938
her and from her to the
rock with dilating eyes.

2368
01:58:11,938 --> 01:58:14,296
“We can hold it together,” she said.

2369
01:58:14,296 --> 01:58:16,234
“You must get on your horse.”

2370
01:58:16,234 --> 01:58:20,765
She took his handkerchief from round his
neck, knotting it with her own,

2371
01:58:20,765 --> 01:58:25,781
and to make more bandage she ran to the
roll of clothes behind his saddle and

2372
01:58:25,781 --> 01:58:27,621
tore in halves a clean shirt.

2373
01:58:27,621 --> 01:58:30,581
A handkerchief fell from it,
which she seized also,

2374
01:58:30,581 --> 01:58:34,626
and opening, saw her own
initials by the hem.

2375
01:58:34,626 --> 01:58:39,957
Then she remembered: she saw again their
first meeting, the swollen river,

2376
01:58:39,957 --> 01:58:45,216
the overset stage, the unknown horseman
who carried her to the bank on his

2377
01:58:45,216 --> 01:58:51,459
saddle and went away unthanked⁠—her
whole first adventure on that first day

2378
01:58:51,459 --> 01:58:55,939
of her coming to this new country⁠—and
now she knew how her long-forgotten

2379
01:58:55,939 --> 01:58:57,730
handkerchief had gone that day.

2380
01:58:57,730 --> 01:59:01,490
She refolded it gently and put it back in
his bundle, for there was

2381
01:59:01,490 --> 01:59:03,128
enough bandage without it.

2382
01:59:03,128 --> 01:59:06,640
She said not a word to him,
and he placed a wrong meaning upon the

2383
01:59:06,640 --> 01:59:09,924
look which she gave him as she returned
to bind his shoulder.

2384
01:59:09,924 --> 01:59:15,967
“It don’t hurt so much,”
he assured her (though extreme pain was

2385
01:59:15,967 --> 01:59:18,967
clearing his head for the moment,
and he had been able to hold

2386
01:59:18,967 --> 01:59:20,368
the cliff from turning).

2387
01:59:20,368 --> 01:59:22,427
“Yu’ must not squander your pity.”

2388
01:59:22,427 --> 01:59:25,271
“Do not squander your strength,” said she.

2389
01:59:25,271 --> 01:59:28,528
“Oh, I could put up a
pretty good fight now!”

2390
01:59:28,528 --> 01:59:33,168
But he tottered in showing her how strong
he was, and she told him that,

2391
01:59:33,168 --> 01:59:35,883
after all, he was a child still.

2392
01:59:35,883 --> 01:59:40,645
“Yes,” he slowly said,
looking after her as she went to bring

2393
01:59:40,645 --> 01:59:45,208
his horse, “the same child that wanted
to touch the moon, I guess.”

2394
01:59:45,208 --> 01:59:51,194
And during the slow climb down into the
saddle from a rock to which she helped

2395
01:59:51,194 --> 01:59:57,722
him he said, “You have got to be the man
all through this mess.”

2396
01:59:57,722 --> 02:00:02,607
She saw his teeth clinched and his
drooping muscles compelled by will;

2397
02:00:02,607 --> 02:00:08,462
and as he rode and she walked to lend
him support, leading her horse by a

2398
02:00:08,462 --> 02:00:13,242
backward-stretched left hand,
she counted off the distance to him

2399
02:00:13,242 --> 02:00:19,025
continually⁠—the increasing gain,
the lessening road, the landmarks

2400
02:00:19,025 --> 02:00:24,366
nearing and dropping behind;
here was the tree with the wasp-nest

2401
02:00:24,366 --> 02:00:28,003
gone; now the burned cabin was passed;
now the cottonwoods at the

2402
02:00:28,003 --> 02:00:29,597
ford were in sight.

2403
02:00:29,597 --> 02:00:34,429
He was silent, and held to the saddle-
horn, leaning more and more against his

2404
02:00:34,429 --> 02:00:39,210
two hands clasped over it;
and just after they had made the

2405
02:00:39,210 --> 02:00:44,017
crossing he fell, without a sound
slipping to the grass,

2406
02:00:44,017 --> 02:00:46,008
and his descent broken by her.

2407
02:00:46,008 --> 02:00:50,057
But it started the blood a little,
and she dared not leave him to seek

2408
02:00:50,057 --> 02:00:50,507
help.

2409
02:00:50,507 --> 02:00:55,820
She gave him the last of the flask and
all the water he craved.

2410
02:00:55,820 --> 02:00:58,335
Revived, he managed to smile.

2411
02:00:58,335 --> -1:59:59,000
“Yu’ see, I ain’t worth keeping.

2412
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2413
02:01:00,636 --> 02:01:02,896
“It’s only a mile,” said she.

2414
02:01:02,896 --> 02:01:07,834
So she found a log, a fallen trunk,
and he crawled to that,

2415
02:01:07,834 --> 02:01:12,037
and from there crawled to his saddle,
and she marched on with him,

2416
02:01:12,037 --> 02:01:14,815
talking, bidding him
note the steps accomplished.

2417
02:01:14,815 --> 02:01:19,205
For the next half-mile they went thus,
the silent man clinched on the horse,

2418
02:01:19,205 --> 02:01:23,739
and by his side the girl walking and
cheering him forward,

2419
02:01:23,739 --> 02:01:25,940
when suddenly he began to speak:⁠—

2420
02:01:25,940 --> -1:59:59,000
“I will say goodbye to you now, ma’am.

2421
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2422
02:01:26,930 --> 02:01:28,353
She did not understand,
at first, the significance of this.

2423
02:01:28,353 --> 02:01:31,618
“He is getting away,”
pursued the Virginian.

2424
02:01:31,618 --> 02:01:34,216
“I must ask you to excuse me, ma’am.”

2425
02:01:34,216 --> 02:01:38,727
It was a long while since her lord had
addressed her as “ma’am.”

2426
02:01:38,727 --> 02:01:43,068
As she looked at him in growing
apprehension, he turned Monte and would

2427
02:01:43,068 --> 02:01:45,388
have ridden away, but
she caught the bridle.

2428
02:01:45,388 --> 02:01:50,611
“You must take me home,”
said she, with ready inspiration.

2429
02:01:50,611 --> 02:01:53,171
“I am afraid of the Indians.”

2430
02:01:53,171 --> 02:01:55,777
“Why, you⁠—why, they’ve all gone.

2431
02:01:55,777 --> 02:01:57,150
There he goes.

2432
02:01:57,150 --> 02:01:59,213
Ma’am⁠—that hawss⁠—”

2433
02:01:59,213 --> 02:02:04,100
“No,” said she, holding firmly his rein
and quickening her step.

2434
02:02:04,100 --> 02:02:07,928
“A gentleman does not invite a lady to go
out riding and leave her.”

2435
02:02:07,928 --> 02:02:10,764
His eyes lost their purpose.

2436
02:02:10,764 --> 02:02:12,462
“I’ll cert’nly take you home.

2437
02:02:12,462 --> 02:02:16,846
That sorrel has gone in there by the
wallow, and Judge Henry will

2438
02:02:16,846 --> 02:02:17,591
understand.”

2439
02:02:17,591 --> 02:02:23,318
With his eyes watching imaginary objects,
he rode and rambled and it was now the

2440
02:02:23,318 --> 02:02:28,271
girl who was silent,
except to keep his mind from its half-

2441
02:02:28,271 --> 02:02:31,035
fixed idea of the sorrel.

2442
02:02:31,035 --> 02:02:37,139
As he grew more fluent she hastened still
more, listening to head off that notion

2443
02:02:37,139 --> 02:02:43,652
of return, skilfully inventing questions
to engage him, so that when she brought

2444
02:02:43,652 --> 02:02:49,169
him to her gate she held him in a manner
subjected, answering faithfully the

2445
02:02:49,169 --> 02:02:55,088
shrewd unrealities which she devised,
whatever makeshifts she could summon to

2446
02:02:55,088 --> 02:03:00,430
her mind; and next she had got him
inside her dwelling and set him down

2447
02:03:00,430 --> 02:03:06,542
docile, but now completely wandering;
and then⁠—no help was at hand, even

2448
02:03:06,542 --> 02:03:07,159
here.

2449
02:03:07,159 --> 02:03:11,867
She had made sure of aid from next door,
and there she hastened,

2450
02:03:11,867 --> 02:03:16,992
to find the Taylor’s cabin locked and
silent; and this meant that parents and

2451
02:03:16,992 --> 02:03:21,241
children were gone to drive;
nor might she be luckier at her next

2452
02:03:21,241 --> 02:03:26,595
nearest neighbors’, should she travel
the intervening mile to fetch them.

2453
02:03:26,595 --> 02:03:30,694
With a mind jostled once more into
uncertainty, she returned to her room,

2454
02:03:30,694 --> 02:03:32,584
and saw a change in him already.

2455
02:03:32,584 --> 02:03:37,553
Illness had stridden upon him;
his face was not as she had left it,

2456
02:03:37,553 --> 02:03:43,759
and the whole body, the splendid supple
horseman, showed sickness in every line

2457
02:03:43,759 --> 02:03:54,700
and limb, its spurs and pistol and bold
leather chaps a mockery of trappings.

2458
02:03:54,700 --> 02:03:58,977
She looked at him, and decision came back
to her, clear and steady.

2459
02:03:58,977 --> 02:04:02,338
She supported him over to her bed and
laid him on it.

2460
02:04:02,338 --> 02:04:09,361
His head sank flat, and his loose,
nerveless arms stayed as she left them.

2461
02:04:09,361 --> 02:04:12,401
Then among her packing-boxes and beneath
the little miniature,

2462
02:04:12,401 --> 02:04:17,231
blue and flaxen and gold upon its lonely
wall, she undressed him.

2463
02:04:17,231 --> 02:04:21,471
He was cold, and she covered him to the
face, and arranged the pillow,

2464
02:04:21,471 --> 02:04:25,845
and got from its box her scarlet and
black Navajo blanket and

2465
02:04:25,845 --> 02:04:27,099
spread it over him.

2466
02:04:27,099 --> 02:04:31,688
There was no more that she could do,
and she sat down by him to wait.

2467
02:04:31,688 --> 02:04:37,622
Among the many and many things that came
into her mind was a word he said to her

2468
02:04:37,622 --> 02:04:39,731
lightly a long while ago.

2469
02:04:39,731 --> 02:04:44,462
“Cowpunchers do not live long enough to
get old,” he had told her.

2470
02:04:44,462 --> 02:04:48,989
And now she looked at the head upon the
pillow, grave and strong,

2471
02:04:48,989 --> 02:04:52,355
but still the head of
splendid, unworn youth.

2472
02:04:52,355 --> 02:04:57,564
At the distant jingle of the wagon in the
lane she was out, and had met

2473
02:04:57,564 --> 02:04:59,760
her returning neighbors midway.

2474
02:04:59,760 --> 02:05:03,544
They heard her with amazement,
and came in haste to the bedside;

2475
02:05:03,544 --> 02:05:07,387
then Taylor departed to spread news of
the Indians and bring the doctor,

2476
02:05:07,387 --> 02:05:08,968
twenty-five miles away.

2477
02:05:08,968 --> 02:05:14,248
The two women friends stood alone again,
as they had stood in the morning when

2478
02:05:14,248 --> 02:05:15,969
anger had been between them.

2479
02:05:15,969 --> 02:05:18,940
“Kiss me, deary,” said Mrs. Taylor.

2480
02:05:18,940 --> -1:59:59,000
“Now I will look after him⁠—and you’ll
need some looking after yourself.

2481
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2482
02:05:23,068 --> 02:05:31,242
But on returning from her cabin with what
store she possessed of lint and

2483
02:05:31,242 --> 02:05:36,145
stimulants, she encountered a
rebel, independent as ever.

2484
02:05:36,145 --> 02:05:41,023
Molly would hear no talk about saving her
strength, would not be in any room but

2485
02:05:41,023 --> 02:05:45,275
this one until the doctor should arrive;
then perhaps it would be time

2486
02:05:45,275 --> 02:05:46,831
to think about resting.

2487
02:05:46,831 --> 02:05:51,675
So together the dame and the girl rinsed
the man’s wound and wrapped him in clean

2488
02:05:51,675 --> 02:05:57,982
things, and did all the little that they
knew⁠—which was, in truth,

2489
02:05:57,982 --> 02:05:59,386
the very thing needed.

