02:19:39,818 --> 02:19:40,675
voice.

2708
02:19:40,675 --> 02:19:41,680
“Yes.

2709
02:19:41,680 --> 02:19:45,769
They have given me awdehs not to talk,”
said the Southerner, smiling.

2710
02:19:45,769 --> 02:19:47,452
“Oh, yes.

2711
02:19:47,452 --> -1:59:59,000
Please do not talk⁠—not today

2712
-1:59:59,000 --> -1:59:59,000
.

2713
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2714
02:19:52,974 --> 02:19:54,235
“No.

2715
02:19:54,235 --> 02:20:03,314
Only this”⁠—he looked at her,
and saw her seem to shrink⁠—“thank you

2716
02:20:03,314 --> 02:20:06,279
for what you have done,” he said simply.

2717
02:20:06,279 --> 02:20:10,969
She took tenderly the hand he stretched
to her; and upon these terms they set

2718
02:20:10,969 --> 02:20:12,886
to work at cribbage.

2719
02:20:12,886 --> 02:20:17,711
She won, and won again,
and the third time laid down her cards

2720
02:20:17,711 --> -1:59:59,000
and reproached him with playing
in order to lose.

2721
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
“

2722
02:20:20,747 --> 02:20:26,279
No,” he said, and his eye
wandered to the boxes.

2723
02:20:26,279 --> 02:20:30,040
“But my thoughts get away from me.

2724
02:20:30,040 --> -1:59:59,000
I’ll be strong enough to hold them on the
cyards next time, I reckon.

2725
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2726
02:20:33,679 --> 02:20:37,071
Many tones in his voice she had heard,
but never the tone of

2727
02:20:37,071 --> 02:20:38,975
sadness until today.

2728
02:20:38,975 --> 02:20:41,951
Then they played a little more,
and she put away the board

2729
02:20:41,951 --> 02:20:43,272
for this first time.

2730
02:20:43,272 --> 02:20:45,457
“You are going now?”

2731
02:20:45,457 --> 02:20:46,206
he asked.

2732
02:20:46,206 --> 02:20:50,146
“When I have made this room look
a little less forlorn.

2733
02:20:50,146 --> 02:20:53,446
They haven’t wanted to meddle with
my things, I suppose.”

2734
02:20:53,446 --> 02:20:59,069
And Molly stooped once again among the
chattels destined for Vermont.

2735
02:20:59,069 --> 02:21:03,424
Out they came; again the bearskin was
spread on the floor,

2736
02:21:03,424 --> 02:21:07,244
various possessions and ornaments went
back into their ancient niches,

2737
02:21:07,244 --> 02:21:11,468
the shelves grew comfortable with books,
and, last, some flowers were

2738
02:21:11,468 --> 02:21:12,428
stood on the table.

2739
02:21:12,428 --> 02:21:16,665
“More like old times,”
said the Virginian, but sadly.

2740
02:21:16,665 --> 02:21:20,568
“It’s too bad,” said Molly,
“you had to be brought into

2741
02:21:20,568 --> -1:59:59,000
such a looking place.

2742
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2743
02:21:22,179 --> 02:21:24,763
“And your folks waiting for you,” said he.

2744
02:21:24,763 --> 02:21:28,552
“Oh, I’ll pay my visit later,”
said Molly, putting the

2745
02:21:28,552 --> 02:21:30,032
rug a trifle straighter.

2746
02:21:30,032 --> 02:21:32,428
“May I ask one thing?”

2747
02:21:32,428 --> 02:21:36,191
pleaded the Virginian,
and at the gentleness of his voice her

2748
02:21:36,191 --> 02:21:40,801
face grew rosy, and she fixed her eyes
on him with a sort of dread.

2749
02:21:40,801 --> 02:21:43,624
“Anything that I can answer,” said she.

2750
02:21:43,624 --> 02:21:45,137
“Oh, yes.

2751
02:21:45,137 --> 02:21:49,309
Did I tell yu’ to quit me,
and did yu’ load up my gun and stay?

2752
02:21:49,309 --> 02:21:50,937
Was that a real business?

2753
02:21:50,937 --> 02:21:52,814
I have been mixed up in my haid.”

2754
02:21:52,814 --> 02:21:54,712
“That was real,” said Molly.

2755
02:21:54,712 --> 02:21:56,373
“What else was there to do?”

2756
02:21:56,373 --> 02:21:58,407
“Just nothing⁠—for such as you!”

2757
02:21:58,407 --> 02:21:59,173
he exclaimed.

2758
02:21:59,173 --> 02:22:03,453
“My haid has been mighty crazy;
and that little grandmother of yours

2759
02:22:03,453 --> 02:22:08,253
yondeh, she⁠—but I can’t just quite
catch ahold of these things”⁠—he passed

2760
02:22:08,253 --> 02:22:13,817
a hand over his forehead⁠—“so many⁠—or
else one right along⁠—

2761
02:22:13,817 --> 02:22:16,425
well, it’s all foolishness!”

2762
02:22:16,425 --> 02:22:20,220
he concluded, with something almost
savage in his tone.

2763
02:22:20,220 --> 02:22:24,380
And after she had gone from the cabin he
lay very still, looking at the

2764
02:22:24,380 --> 02:22:25,651
miniature on the wall.

2765
02:22:25,651 --> 02:22:29,580
He was in another sort of mood the next
time, cribbage not interesting

2766
02:22:29,580 --> 02:22:31,031
him in the least.

2767
02:22:31,031 --> 02:22:34,831
“Your folks will be wondering
about you,” said he.

2768
02:22:34,831 --> 02:22:39,134
“I don’t think they will mind which month
I go to them,” said Molly.

2769
02:22:39,134 --> -1:59:59,000
“Especially when they know the reason

2770
-1:59:59,000 --> -1:59:59,000
.

2771
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2772
02:22:41,390 --> 02:22:44,152
“Don’t let me keep you, ma’am,” said he.

2773
02:22:44,152 --> 02:22:49,092
Molly stared at him; but he pursued,
with the same edge lurking in his slow

2774
02:22:49,092 --> 02:22:51,728
words: “Though I’ll never forget.

2775
02:22:51,728 --> 02:22:55,063
How could I forget any of all you
have done⁠—and been?

2776
02:22:55,063 --> 02:23:00,155
If there had been none of this,
why, I had enough to remember!

2777
02:23:00,155 --> 02:23:01,890
But please don’t stay, ma’am.

2778
02:23:01,890 --> 02:23:06,067
We’ll say I had a claim when yu’ found me
pretty well dead, but I’m gettin’ well,

2779
02:23:06,067 --> 02:23:07,905
yu’ see⁠—right smart, too!”

2780
02:23:07,905 --> 02:23:13,714
“I can’t understand, indeed I can’t,”
said Molly, “why you’re talking so!”

2781
02:23:13,714 --> 02:23:17,890
He seemed to have certain moods when he
would address her as “ma’am,”

2782
02:23:17,890 --> 02:23:20,658
and this she did not like,
but could not prevent.

2783
02:23:20,658 --> 02:23:23,651
“Oh, a sick man is funny.

2784
02:23:23,651 --> 02:23:25,255
And yu’ know I’m grateful to you.”

2785
02:23:25,255 --> 02:23:28,293
“Please say no more about that,
or I shall go this afternoon.

2786
02:23:28,293 --> 02:23:29,674
I don’t want to go.

2787
02:23:29,674 --> 02:23:30,762
I am not ready.

2788
02:23:30,762 --> 02:23:32,972
I think I had better read something now.”

2789
02:23:32,972 --> 02:23:34,175
“Why, yes.

2790
02:23:34,175 --> 02:23:36,643
That’s cert’nly a good notion.

2791
02:23:36,643 --> 02:23:40,375
Why, this is the best show you’ll ever
get to give me education.

2792
02:23:40,375 --> 02:23:43,055
Won’t yu’ please try that
Emma book now, ma’am?

2793
02:23:43,055 --> 02:23:45,335
Listening to you will be different.”

2794
02:23:45,335 --> 02:23:49,800
This was said with softness and humility.

2795
02:23:49,800 --> 02:23:56,040
Uncertain⁠—as his gravity often left
her⁠—precisely what he meant by what he

2796
02:23:56,040 --> 02:24:01,155
said, Molly proceeded with Emma,
slackly at first, but soon with the

2797
02:24:01,155 --> 02:24:04,352
enthusiasm that Miss
Austen invariably gave her.

2798
02:24:04,352 --> 02:24:09,386
She held the volume and read away at it,
commenting briefly, and then,

2799
02:24:09,386 --> 02:24:13,203
finishing a chapter of the sprightly
classic, found her pupil

2800
02:24:13,203 --> 02:24:14,737
slumbering peacefully.

2801
02:24:14,737 --> 02:24:16,845
There was no uncertainty about that.

2802
02:24:16,845 --> 02:24:21,044
“You couldn’t be doing a healthier thing
for him, deary,” said Mrs. Taylor.

2803
02:24:21,044 --> 02:24:24,764
“If it gets to make him
wakeful, try something harder.”

2804
02:24:24,764 --> 02:24:29,185
This was the lady’s scarcely
sympathetic view.

2805
02:24:29,185 --> 02:24:33,665
But it turned out to be not obscurity in
which Miss Austen sinned.

2806
02:24:33,665 --> 02:24:37,388
When Molly next appeared at the
Virginian’s threshold,

2807
02:24:37,388 --> 02:24:40,141
he said plaintively,
“I reckon I am a dunce.”

2808
02:24:40,141 --> 02:24:41,724
And he sued for pardon.

2809
02:24:41,724 --> 02:24:44,838
“When I waked up,” he said,
“I was ashamed of myself for

2810
02:24:44,838 --> 02:24:46,085
a plumb half-hour.”

2811
02:24:46,085 --> 02:24:48,869
Nor could she doubt this day that he
meant what he said.

2812
02:24:48,869 --> 02:24:53,749
His mood was again serene and gentle,
and without referring to his singular

2813
02:24:53,749 --> 02:24:58,496
words that had distressed her,
he made her feel his contrition,

2814
02:24:58,496 --> 02:24:59,889
even in his silence.

2815
02:24:59,889 --> 02:25:02,329
“I am right glad you have come,” he said.

2816
02:25:02,329 --> 02:25:06,853
And as he saw her going to the bookshelf,
he continued, with diffidence:

2817
02:25:06,853 --> 02:25:14,372
“As regyards that Emma book,
yu’ see⁠—yu’ see, the doin’s and sayin’s

2818
02:25:14,372 --> 02:25:16,012
of folks like them are above me.

2819
02:25:16,012 --> 02:25:21,134
But I think” (he spoke most diffidently),
“if yu’ could read me something that was

2820
02:25:21,134 --> 02:25:25,054
about something, I⁠—I’d be
liable to keep awake.”

2821
02:25:25,054 --> 02:25:27,435
And he smiled with a certain shyness.

2822
02:25:27,435 --> 02:25:29,317
“Something about something?”

2823
02:25:29,317 --> 02:25:31,276
queried Molly, at a loss.

2824
02:25:31,276 --> 02:25:32,747
“Why, yes.

2825
02:25:32,747 --> 02:25:34,038
Shakespeare.

2826
02:25:34,038 --> 02:25:35,427
Henry the Fourth.

2827
02:25:35,427 --> 02:25:42,740
The British king is fighting,
and there is his son the prince.

2828
02:25:42,740 --> 02:25:46,574
He cert’nly must have been a jim-dandy
boy if that is all true.

2829
02:25:46,574 --> 02:25:50,149
Only he would go around town with
a mighty triflin’ gang.

2830
02:25:50,149 --> 02:25:53,902
They sported and they held up citizens.

2831
02:25:53,902 --> 02:25:58,946
And his father hated his travelling
with trash like them.

2832
02:25:58,946 --> 02:26:03,372
It was right natural⁠—the boy
and the old man!

2833
02:26:03,372 --> 02:26:06,679
But the boy showed himself a man too.

2834
02:26:06,679 --> 02:26:10,795
He killed a big fighter on the other side
who was another jim-dandy⁠—and he was

2835
02:26:10,795 --> 02:26:12,595
sorry for having it to do.”

2836
02:26:12,595 --> 02:26:14,795
The Virginian warmed to his recital.

2837
02:26:14,795 --> 02:26:17,865
“I understand most all of that.

2838
02:26:17,865 --> 02:26:20,830
There was a fat man kept
everybody laughing.

2839
02:26:20,830 --> 02:26:24,819
He was awful natural too;
except yu’ don’t commonly

2840
02:26:24,819 --> 02:26:26,476
meet ’em so fat.

2841
02:26:26,476 --> 02:26:29,764
But the prince⁠—that play
is bedrock, ma’am!

2842
02:26:29,764 --> 02:26:31,430
Have you got something like that?”

2843
02:26:31,430 --> 02:26:34,870
“Yes, I think so,” she replied.

2844
02:26:34,870 --> 02:26:37,013
“I believe I see what
you would appreciate.”

2845
02:26:37,013 --> 02:26:41,045
She took her Browning,
her idol, her imagined affinity.

2846
02:26:41,045 --> 02:26:45,178
For the pale decadence of New England had
somewhat watered her good old

2847
02:26:45,178 --> 02:26:48,457
Revolutionary blood too,
and she was inclined to think under

2848
02:26:48,457 --> 02:26:52,783
glass and to live underdone⁠—when there
were no Indians to shoot!

2849
02:26:52,783 --> 02:26:56,199
She would have joyed to venture
Paracelsus on him, and some lengthy

2850
02:26:56,199 --> 02:27:01,606
rhymed discourses; and she fondly turned
leaves and leaves of

2851
02:27:01,606 --> 02:27:03,335
her pet doggerel analytics.

2852
02:27:03,335 --> 02:27:08,369
Pippa Passes and others she had to skip,
from discreet motives⁠—pages which he

2853
02:27:08,369 --> 02:27:12,120
would have doubtless stayed awake at;
but she chose a poem at length.

2854
02:27:12,120 --> 02:27:16,174
This was better than Emma, he pronounced.

2855
02:27:16,174 --> 02:27:17,113
And short.

2856
02:27:17,113 --> 02:27:18,930
The horse was a good horse.

2857
02:27:18,930 --> 02:27:22,455
He thought a man whose horse must not
play out on him would watch the ground

2858
02:27:22,455 --> 02:27:25,975
he was galloping over for holes,
and not be likely to see what color the

2859
02:27:25,975 --> 02:27:28,318
rims of his animal’s eye-sockets were.

2860
02:27:28,318 --> 02:27:32,985
You could not see them if you sat as you
ought to for such a hard ride.

2861
02:27:32,985 --> 02:27:36,678
Of the next piece that she read him
he thought still better.

2862
02:27:36,678 --> 02:27:38,896
“And it is short,” said he.

2863
02:27:38,896 --> 02:27:40,759
“But the last part drops.”

2864
02:27:40,759 --> 02:27:43,361
Molly instantly exacted particulars.

2865
02:27:43,361 --> 02:27:46,601
“The soldier should not have told the
general he was killed,”

2866
02:27:46,601 --> 02:27:47,921
stated the cowpuncher.

2867
02:27:47,921 --> 02:27:50,921
“What should he have told him,
I’d like to know?”

2868
02:27:50,921 --> 02:27:51,981
said Molly.

2869
02:27:51,981 --> 02:27:54,021
“Why, just nothing.

2870
02:27:54,021 --> 02:27:58,903
If the soldier could ride out of the
battle all shot up, and tell his general

2871
02:27:58,903 --> 02:28:02,011
about their takin’ the town⁠—that was
being gritty, yu’ see.

2872
02:28:02,011 --> 02:28:04,903
But that truck at the finish⁠—will yu’
please say it again?”

2873
02:28:04,903 --> 02:28:06,701
So Molly read:⁠—

2874
02:28:06,701 --> 02:28:09,364
“ ‘You’re wounded!

2875
02:28:09,364 --> 02:28:14,298
‘Nay,’ the soldier’s prideTouched to the
quick, he said,‘I’m killed, sire!’

2876
02:28:14,298 --> -1:59:59,000
And, his chief beside,
Smiling the boy fell dead.

2877
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2878
02:28:18,533 --> 02:28:22,483
“ ‘Nay, I’m killed, sire,’
” drawled the Virginian,

2879
02:28:22,483 --> 02:28:33,263
amiably; for (symptom of convalescence)
his freakish irony was revived in him.

2880
02:28:33,263 --> 02:28:39,222
“Now a man who was man enough to act like
he did, yu’ see, would fall

2881
02:28:39,222 --> 02:28:40,916
dead without mentioning it.”

2882
02:28:40,916 --> 02:28:46,590
None of Molly’s sweet girl friends had
ever thus challenged Mr. Browning.

2883
02:28:46,590 --> 02:28:50,807
They had been wont to cluster over him
with a joyous awe that deepened

2884
02:28:50,807 --> 02:28:53,397
proportionally with their
misunderstanding.

2885
02:28:53,397 --> 02:28:57,488
Molly paused to consider this novelty of
view about the soldier.

2886
02:28:57,488 --> 02:29:01,648
“He was a Frenchman, you know,”
she said, under inspiration.

2887
02:29:01,648 --> 02:29:04,701
“A Frenchman,” murmured
the grave cowpuncher.

2888
02:29:04,701 --> 02:29:08,648
“I never knowed a Frenchman,
but I reckon they might perform

2889
02:29:08,648 --> -1:59:59,000
that class of foolishness.

2890
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2891
02:29:10,992 --> 02:29:13,080
“But why was it foolish?”

2892
02:29:13,080 --> 02:29:13,871
she cried.

2893
02:29:13,871 --> 02:29:16,048
“His soldier’s pride⁠—don’t you see?”

2894
02:29:16,048 --> 02:29:16,677
“No.”

2895
02:29:16,677 --> 02:29:19,812
Molly now burst into a
luxury of discussion.

2896
02:29:19,812 --> 02:29:23,847
She leaned toward her cowpuncher with
bright eyes searching his;

2897
02:29:23,847 --> 02:29:30,112
with elbow on knee and hand propping
chin, her lap became a slant,

2898
02:29:30,112 --> 02:29:34,720
and from it Browning the poet slid and
toppled, and lay unrescued.

2899
02:29:34,720 --> 02:29:40,724
For the slow cowpuncher unfolded his
notions of masculine courage and modesty

2900
02:29:40,724 --> 02:29:45,056
(though he did not deal in such high-
sounding names), and Molly forgot

2901
02:29:45,056 --> 02:29:49,293
everything to listen to him,
as he forgot himself and his inveterate

2902
02:29:49,293 --> 02:29:55,010
shyness and grew talkative to her.

2903
02:29:55,010 --> 02:29:58,604
“I would never have supposed that!”

2904
02:29:58,604 --> 02:30:02,610
she would exclaim as she heard him;
or, presently again,

2905
02:30:02,610 --> 02:30:05,130
“I never had such an idea!”

2906
02:30:05,130 --> 02:30:10,633
And her mind opened with delight to these
new things which came from the man’s

2907
02:30:10,633 --> 02:30:13,827
mind so simple and direct.

2908
02:30:13,827 --> 02:30:18,645
To Browning they did come back,
but the Virginian, though interested,

2909
02:30:18,645 --> 02:30:20,712
conceived a dislike for him.

2910
02:30:20,712 --> 02:30:24,168
“He is a smarty,” said he, once or twice.

2911
02:30:24,168 --> 02:30:26,609
“Now here is something,” said Molly.

2912
02:30:26,609 --> 02:30:29,364
“I have never known what to think.”

2913
02:30:29,364 --> 02:30:31,709
“Oh, Heavens!”

2914
02:30:31,709 --> 02:30:33,597
murmured the sick man, smiling.

2915
02:30:33,597 --> 02:30:34,749
“Is it short?”

2916
02:30:34,749 --> 02:30:36,881
“Very short.

2917
02:30:36,881 --> 02:30:38,163
Now please attend.”

2918
02:30:38,163 --> 02:30:42,498
And she read him twelve lines about a
lover who rowed to a beach in the dusk,

2919
02:30:42,498 --> 02:30:46,212
crossed a field, tapped at a
pane, and was admitted.

2920
02:30:46,212 --> 02:30:49,020
“That is the best yet,”
said the Virginian.

2921
02:30:49,020 --> 02:30:51,383
“There’s only one thing yu’
can think about that.”

2922
02:30:51,383 --> 02:30:53,611
“But wait,” said the girl, swiftly.

2923
02:30:53,611 --> 02:30:55,160
“Here is how they parted:⁠—

2924
02:30:55,160 --> 02:30:59,063
“Round the cape of a sudden came the sea,
And the sun looked over the mountain’s

2925
02:30:59,063 --> 02:31:02,783
rim⁠—And straight was a path of gold for
him,And the need of a world

2926
02:31:02,783 --> 02:31:03,863
of men for me.”

2927
02:31:03,863 --> 02:31:07,532
“That is very, very true,”
murmured the Virginian,

2928
02:31:07,532 --> 02:31:10,463
dropping his eyes from
the girl’s intent ones.

2929
02:31:10,463 --> 02:31:11,700
“Had they quarrelled?”

2930
02:31:11,700 --> 02:31:12,843
she inquired.

2931
02:31:12,843 --> 02:31:13,508
“Oh, no!”

2932
02:31:13,508 --> 02:31:13,999
“But⁠—”

2933
02:31:13,999 --> 02:31:15,399
“I reckon he loved her very much.”

2934
02:31:15,399 --> 02:31:17,161
“Then you’re sure they hadn’t quarrelled?”

2935
02:31:17,161 --> 02:31:18,306
“Dead sure, ma’am.

2936
02:31:18,306 --> 02:31:21,846
He would come back afteh he had played
some more of the game.”

2937
02:31:21,846 --> 02:31:22,699
“The game?”

2938
02:31:22,699 --> 02:31:24,311
“Life, ma’am.

2939
02:31:24,311 --> 02:31:26,780
Whatever he was a-doin’ in
the world of men.

2940
02:31:26,780 --> -1:59:59,000
That’s a bedrock piece, ma’am!

2941
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2942
02:31:28,820 --> 02:31:33,080
“Well, I don’t see why you think it’s so
much better than some of the others.”

2943
02:31:33,080 --> 02:31:36,684
“I could sca’cely explain,”
answered the man.

2944
02:31:36,684 --> 02:31:39,102
“But that writer does know something.”

2945
02:31:39,102 --> 02:31:42,663
“I am glad they hadn’t
quarrelled,” said Molly, thoughtfully.

2946
02:31:42,663 --> 02:31:46,306
And she began to like
having her opinions refuted.

2947
02:31:46,306 --> 02:31:52,180
His bandages, becoming a little irksome,
had to be shifted, and this turned their

2948
02:31:52,180 --> 02:31:56,060
discourse from literature to Wyoming;
and Molly inquired, had he

2949
02:31:56,060 --> 02:31:57,539
ever been shot before?

2950
02:31:57,539 --> 02:31:59,747
Only once, he told her.

2951
02:31:59,747 --> 02:32:04,880
“I have been lucky in having
few fusses,” said he.

2952
02:32:04,880 --> 02:32:09,276
“I hate them.

2953
02:32:09,276 --> 02:32:11,916
If a man has to be killed⁠—”

2954
02:32:11,916 --> 02:32:13,885
“You never⁠—” broke in Molly.

2955
02:32:13,885 --> 02:32:17,065
She had started back a little.

2956
02:32:17,065 --> 02:32:21,397
“Well,” she added hastily,
“don’t tell me if⁠—”

2957
02:32:21,397 --> 02:32:25,461
“I shouldn’t wonder if I got one of those
Indians,” he said quietly.

2958
02:32:25,461 --> 02:32:28,685
“But I wasn’t waitin’ to see!

2959
02:32:28,685 --> 02:32:32,131
But I came mighty near doing for a
white man that day.

2960
02:32:32,131 --> -1:59:59,000
He had been hurtin’ a hawss.

2961
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2962
02:32:34,785 --> 02:32:35,594
“Hurting?”

2963
02:32:35,594 --> 02:32:37,368
said Molly.

2964
02:32:37,368 --> 02:32:38,469
“Injurin.’

2965
02:32:38,469 --> 02:32:42,510
I will not tell yu’ about that.

2966
02:32:42,510 --> 02:32:44,809
It would hurt yu’ to hear such things.

2967
02:32:44,809 --> 02:32:47,582
But hawsses⁠—don’t they depend on us?

2968
02:32:47,582 --> -1:59:59,000
Ain’t they somethin’ like children

2969
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
?

2970
02:32:49,891 --> 02:32:53,064
I did not lay up the man very bad.

2971
02:32:53,064 --> 02:32:55,510
He was able to travel ’most right away.

2972
02:32:55,510 --> 02:32:57,655
Why, you’d have wanted
to kill him yourself!”

2973
02:32:57,655 --> 02:33:01,494
So the Virginian talked,
nor knew what he was doing to the girl.

2974
02:33:01,494 --> 02:33:05,774
Nor was she aware of what she was
receiving from him as he unwittingly

2975
02:33:05,774 --> 02:33:09,677
spoke himself out to her in these
Browning meetings they had each day.

2976
02:33:09,677 --> 02:33:11,882
But Mrs. Taylor grew pleased.

2977
02:33:11,882 --> 02:33:16,284
The kindly dame would sometimes cross the
road to see if she were needed,

2978
02:33:16,284 --> 02:33:19,978
and steal away again after a
peep at the window.

2979
02:33:19,978 --> 02:33:24,760
There, inside, among the restored home
treasures, sat the two:

2980
02:33:24,760 --> 02:33:30,139
the rosy alert girl,
sweet as she talked or read to him;

2981
02:33:30,139 --> 02:33:38,933
and he, the grave, half-weak giant among
his wraps, watching her.

2982
02:33:38,933 --> 02:33:44,003
Of her delayed home visit he never again
spoke, either to her or to Mrs. Taylor;

2983
02:33:44,003 --> 02:33:47,794
and Molly veered aside from any trend of
talk she foresaw was

2984
02:33:47,794 --> 02:33:49,514
leading toward that subject.

2985
02:33:49,514 --> 02:33:53,859
But in those hours when no visitors came,
and he was by himself in the quiet,

2986
02:33:53,859 --> 02:33:57,845
he would lie often sombrely
contemplating the girl’s room,

2987
02:33:57,845 --> 02:34:01,376
her little dainty knickknacks,
her home photographs,

2988
02:34:01,376 --> 02:34:06,572
all the delicate manifestations of what
she came from and what she was.

2989
02:34:06,572 --> 02:34:11,475
Strength was flowing back into him each
day, and Judge Henry’s latest messenger

2990
02:34:11,475 --> 02:34:15,667
had brought him clothes and mail from
Sunk Creek and many inquiries of

2991
02:34:15,667 --> 02:34:19,678
kindness, and returned taking the news
of the cowpuncher’s improvement,

2992
02:34:19,678 --> 02:34:24,619
and how soon he would be
permitted the fresh air.

2993
02:34:24,619 --> 02:34:30,899
Hence Molly found him waiting in a
flannel shirt of highly becoming shade,

2994
02:34:30,899 --> 02:34:35,500
and with a silk handkerchief knotted
round his throat; and he told her it was

2995
02:34:35,500 --> 02:34:37,569
good to feel respectable again.

2996
02:34:37,569 --> 02:34:41,651
She had come to read to him for the
allotted time; and she threw around his

2997
02:34:41,651 --> 02:34:48,213
shoulders the scarlet and black Navajo
blanket, striped with its

2998
02:34:48,213 --> 02:34:50,702
splendid zigzags of barbarity.

2999
02:34:50,702 --> 02:34:57,056
Thus he half sat, half leaned,
languid but at ease.

3000
02:34:57,056 --> 02:35:00,676
In his lap lay one of the letters brought
over by the messenger:

3001
02:35:00,676 --> 02:35:04,848
and though she was midway in a book that
engaged his full attention⁠—David

3002
02:35:04,848 --> 02:35:08,859
Copperfield⁠—his silence and absent look
this morning stopped her,

3003
02:35:08,859 --> 02:35:11,231
and she accused him of not attending.

3004
02:35:11,231 --> 02:35:14,648
“No,” he admitted; “I am
thinking of something else.”

3005
02:35:14,648 --> 02:35:17,248
She looked at him with that
apprehension which he knew.

3006
02:35:17,248 --> 02:35:19,728
“It had to come,” said he.

3007
02:35:19,728 --> 02:35:25,823
“And today I see my thoughts straighter
than I’ve been up to managing since⁠—

3008
02:35:25,823 --> 02:35:27,580
since my haid got clear.

3009
02:35:27,580 --> 02:35:31,940
And now I must say these thoughts⁠—if I
can, if I can!”

3010
02:35:31,940 --> 02:35:32,842
He stopped.

3011
02:35:32,842 --> 02:35:36,312
His eyes were intent upon her;
one hand was gripping the

3012
02:35:36,312 --> 02:35:37,632
arm of his chair.

3013
02:35:37,632 --> 02:35:40,254
“You promised⁠—” trembled Molly.

3014
02:35:40,254 --> 02:35:45,527
“I promised you should love
me,” he sternly interrupted.

3015
02:35:45,527 --> 02:35:47,905
“Promised that to myself.

3016
02:35:47,905 --> 02:35:50,057
I have broken that word.”

3017
02:35:50,057 --> 02:35:54,187
She shut David Copperfield
mechanically, and grew white.

3018
02:35:54,187 --> 02:35:59,709
“Your letter has come to me hyeh,”
he continued, gentle again.

3019
02:35:59,709 --> 02:36:01,726
“My⁠—” She had forgotten it.

3020
02:36:01,726 --> 02:36:05,830
“The letter you wrote to tell me goodbye.

3021
02:36:05,830 --> 02:36:09,960
You wrote it a little while ago⁠—not a
month yet, but it’s away and away

3022
02:36:09,960 --> -1:59:59,000
long gone for me.

3023
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

3024
02:36:11,828 --> 02:36:15,172
“I have never let you know⁠—” began Molly.

3025
02:36:15,172 --> 02:36:19,989
“The doctor,” he interrupted once more,
but very gently now,

3026
02:36:19,989 --> 02:36:23,002
“he gave awdehs I must be kept quiet.

3027
02:36:23,002 --> 02:36:25,516
I reckon yu’ thought tellin’ me might⁠—”

3028
02:36:25,516 --> 02:36:26,708
“Forgive me!”

3029
02:36:26,708 --> 02:36:27,858
cried the girl.

3030
02:36:27,858 --> 02:36:30,338
“Indeed I ought to have told you sooner!

3031
02:36:30,338 --> 02:36:32,093
Indeed I had no excuse!”

3032
02:36:32,093 --> 02:36:37,421
“Why, should yu’ tell me
if yu’ preferred not?

3033
02:36:37,421 --> 02:36:39,343
You had written.

3034
02:36:39,343 --> 02:36:44,505
And you speak” (he lifted the letter) “of
never being able to repay kindness;

3035
02:36:44,505 --> 02:36:46,699
but you have turned the tables.

3036
02:36:46,699 --> 02:36:49,508
I can never repay you by anything!

3037
02:36:49,508 --> 02:36:50,999
by anything!

3038
02:36:50,999 --> 02:36:55,183
So I had figured I would just jog back to
Sunk Creek and let you get away,

3039
02:36:55,183 --> 02:36:57,267
if you did not want to say
that kind of goodbye.

3040
02:36:57,267 --> 02:36:59,560
For I saw the boxes.

3041
02:36:59,560 --> 02:36:59,966
Mrs.

3042
02:36:59,966 --> 02:37:03,468
Taylor is too nice a woman to know the
trick of lyin’, and she

3043
02:37:03,468 --> 02:37:04,833
could not deceive me.

3044
02:37:04,833 --> 02:37:09,430
I have knowed yu’ were going away for
good ever since I saw those boxes.

3045
02:37:09,430 --> 02:37:14,357
But now hyeh comes your letter,
and it seems no way but I must speak.

3046
02:37:14,357 --> 02:37:16,850
I have thought a deal, lyin’ in this room.

3047
02:37:16,850 --> 02:37:20,523
And⁠—today⁠—I can say what I have thought.

3048
02:37:20,523 --> 02:37:21,977
I could not make you happy.”

3049
02:37:21,977 --> 02:37:23,822
He stopped, but she did not answer.

3050
02:37:23,822 --> 02:37:27,860
His voice had grown softer than
whispering, but yet was not a whisper.

3051
02:37:27,860 --> 02:37:33,629
From its quiet syllables she turned away,
blinded with sudden tears.

3052
02:37:33,629 --> 02:37:38,449
“Once, I thought love must surely
be enough,” he continued.

3053
02:37:38,449 --> 02:37:45,038
“And I thought if I could make you love
me, you could learn me to be less⁠—

3054
02:37:45,038 --> 02:37:48,574
less⁠—more your kind.

3055
02:37:48,574 --> 02:37:52,078
And I think I could give you a pretty
good sort of love.

3056
02:37:52,078 --> 02:37:58,501
But that don’t help the little mean pesky
things of day by day that make roughness

3057
02:37:58,501 --> 02:38:02,532
or smoothness for folks tied
together so awful close.

3058
02:38:02,532 --> 02:38:02,997
Mrs.

3059
02:38:02,997 --> 02:38:06,570
Taylor hyeh⁠—she don’t know anything
better than Taylor does.

3060
02:38:06,570 --> 02:38:09,325
She don’t want anything he can’t give her.

3061
02:38:09,325 --> 02:38:12,522
Her friends will do for him
and his for her.

3062
02:38:12,522 --> 02:38:15,958
And when I dreamed of you in my home⁠—”
he closed his eyes and

3063
02:38:15,958 --> 02:38:17,065
drew a long breath.

3064
02:38:17,065 --> 02:38:20,263
At last he looked at her again.

3065
02:38:20,263 --> 02:38:22,911
“This is no country for a lady.

3066
02:38:22,911 --> 02:38:26,342
Will yu’ forget and forgive the
bothering I have done?”

3067
02:38:26,342 --> 02:38:27,240
“Oh!”

3068
02:38:27,240 --> 02:38:28,183
cried Molly.

3069
02:38:28,183 --> 02:38:28,752
“Oh!”

3070
02:38:28,752 --> 02:38:31,082
And she put her hands to her eyes.

3071
02:38:31,082 --> 02:38:34,364
She had risen and stood
with her face covered.

3072
02:38:34,364 --> 02:38:37,325
“I surely had to tell you this
all out, didn’t I?”

3073
02:38:37,325 --> 02:38:40,648
said the cowpuncher, faintly,
in his chair.

3074
02:38:40,648 --> 02:38:41,215
“Oh!”

3075
02:38:41,215 --> 02:38:42,583
said Molly again.

3076
02:38:42,583 --> 02:38:46,142
“I have put it clear how
it is,” he pursued.

3077
02:38:46,142 --> 02:38:50,862
“I ought to have seen from the start I
was not the sort to keep you happy.”

3078
02:38:50,862 --> 02:38:56,133
“But,” said Molly⁠—“but I⁠—you ought⁠—
please try to keep me happy!”

3079
02:38:56,133 --> 02:38:59,716
And sinking by his chair,
she hid her face on his knees.

3080
02:38:59,716 --> 02:39:04,840
Speechless, he bent down and folded her
round, putting his hands on the hair

3081
02:39:04,840 --> 02:39:06,865
that had been always his delight.

3082
02:39:06,865 --> 02:39:08,126
Presently he whispered:⁠—

3083
02:39:08,126 --> 02:39:10,839
“You have beat me; how can I fight this?”

3084
02:39:10,839 --> 02:39:12,067
She answered nothing.

3085
02:39:12,067 --> 02:39:18,969
The Navajo’s scarlet and black
folds fell over both.

3086
02:39:18,969 --> 02:39:25,429
Not with words, not even with meeting
eyes, did the two plight their troth in

3087
02:39:25,429 --> 02:39:26,942
this first new hour.

3088
02:39:26,942 --> 02:39:33,339
So they remained long,
the fair head nesting in the great arms,

3089
02:39:33,339 --> 02:39:37,610
and the black head laid against it,
while over the silent room presided the

3090
02:39:37,610 --> 02:39:41,596
little Grandmother Stark in her frame,
rosy, blue, and flaxen,

3091
02:39:41,596 --> 02:39:44,700
not quite familiar, not quite smiling.

3092
02:39:44,700 --> 02:39:45,452
CHAPTER XXVIII

3093
02:39:45,452 --> 02:39:46,239
No Dream to Wake from

3094
02:39:46,239 --> 02:39:52,069
For a long while after she had left him,
he lay still, stretched in his chair.

3095
02:39:52,069 --> 02:39:57,178
His eyes were fixed steadily upon the
open window and the sunshine outside.

3096
02:39:57,178 --> 02:40:01,648
There he watched the movement of the
leaves upon the green cottonwoods.

3097
02:40:01,648 --> 02:40:04,644
What had she said to him when she went?

3098
02:40:04,644 --> 02:40:07,889
She had said, “Now I know how
unhappy I have been.”

3099
02:40:07,889 --> 02:40:13,581
These sweet words he repeated to himself
over and over, fearing in some way that

3100
02:40:13,581 --> 02:40:14,591
he might lose them.

3101
02:40:14,591 --> 02:40:19,631
They almost slipped from him at times;
but with a jump of his mind he caught

3102
02:40:19,631 --> 02:40:24,825
them again and held them⁠—and then⁠—“I’m
not all strong yet,” he murmured.

3103
02:40:24,825 --> 02:40:26,637
“I must have been very sick.”

3104
02:40:26,637 --> 02:40:30,197
And, weak from his bullet wound and
fever, he closed his

3105
02:40:30,197 --> 02:40:32,155
eyes without knowing it.

3106
02:40:32,155 --> 02:40:37,450
There were the cottonwoods again,
waving, waving; and he felt the cool,

3107
02:40:37,450 --> 02:40:39,304
pleasant air from the window.

3108
02:40:39,304 --> 02:40:44,213
He saw the light draught stir the ashes
in the great stone fireplace.

3109
02:40:44,213 --> 02:40:47,984
“I have been asleep,” he said.

3110
02:40:47,984 --> 02:40:50,271
“But she was cert’nly here herself.

3111
02:40:50,271 --> 02:40:51,535
Oh, yes.

3112
02:40:51,535 --> 02:40:52,495
Surely.

3113
02:40:52,495 --> 02:40:55,689
She always has to go away every day
because the doctor says⁠—

3114
02:40:55,689 --> 02:40:57,458
why, she was readin’!”

3115
02:40:57,458 --> 02:40:59,259
he broke off, aloud.

3116
02:40:59,259 --> 02:41:00,640
“David Copperfield.”

3117
02:41:00,640 --> 02:41:02,361
There it was on the floor.

3118
02:41:02,361 --> 02:41:03,054
“Aha!

3119
02:41:03,054 --> 02:41:04,875
nailed you anyway!”

3120
02:41:04,875 --> 02:41:05,614
he said.

3121
02:41:05,614 --> 02:41:08,967
“But how scared I am of
myself!⁠—You’re a fool.

3122
02:41:08,967 --> 02:41:10,175
Of course it’s so.

3123
02:41:10,175 --> 02:41:13,321
No fever business could make
yu’ feel like this.”

3124
02:41:13,321 --> 02:41:18,390
His eye dwelt awhile on the fireplace,
next on the deer horns,

3125
02:41:18,390 --> 02:41:25,060
and next it travelled toward the shelf
where her books were;

3126
02:41:25,060 --> 02:41:29,130
but it stopped before reaching them.

3127
02:41:29,130 --> 02:41:33,194
“Better say off the names before
I look,” said he.

3128
02:41:33,194 --> 02:41:35,452
“I’ve had a heap o’ misreading visions.

3129
02:41:35,452 --> 02:41:40,202
And⁠—and supposin’⁠—if this was just my
sickness fooling me some more⁠—

3130
02:41:40,202 --> 02:41:41,402
I’d want to die.

3131
02:41:41,402 --> 02:41:42,523
I would die!

3132
02:41:42,523 --> 02:41:43,813
Now we’ll see.

3133
02:41:43,813 --> 02:41:47,972
If Copperfield is on the floor” (he
looked stealthily to be sure that it

3134
02:41:47,972 --> 02:41:50,933
was), “then she was readin’ to me when
everything happened,

3135
02:41:50,933 --> 02:41:55,087
and then there should be a hole in the
book row, top, left.

3136
02:41:55,087 --> 02:41:59,682
Top, left,” he repeated,
and warily brought his

3137
02:41:59,682 --> 02:42:01,072
glance to the place.

3138
02:42:01,072 --> 02:42:01,754
“Proved!”

3139
02:42:01,754 --> 02:42:02,426
he cried.

3140
02:42:02,426 --> 02:42:03,359
“It’s all so!”

3141
02:42:03,359 --> 02:42:06,543
He now noticed the miniature
of Grandmother Stark.

3142
02:42:06,543 --> 02:42:10,457
“You are awful like her,” he whispered.

3143
02:42:10,457 --> 02:42:12,701
“You’re cert’nly awful like her.

3144
02:42:12,701 --> 02:42:14,665
May I kiss you too, ma’am?”

3145
02:42:14,665 --> 02:42:17,417
Then, tottering, he rose
from his sick-chair.

3146
02:42:17,417 --> 02:42:22,126
The Navajo blanket fell from his
shoulders, and gradually,

3147
02:42:22,126 --> 02:42:24,922
experimentally, he stood upright.

3148
02:42:24,922 --> 02:42:28,574
Helping himself with his hand slowly
along the wall of the room,

3149
02:42:28,574 --> 02:42:32,274
and round to the opposite wall with many
a pause, he reached the picture,

3150
02:42:32,274 --> 02:42:38,328
and very gently touched the forehead of
the ancestral dame with his lips.

3151
02:42:38,328 --> 02:42:42,489
“I promise to make your little
girl happy,” he whispered.

3152
02:42:42,489 --> 02:42:49,618
He almost fell in stooping to the
portrait, but caught himself and stood

3153
02:42:49,618 --> 02:42:53,089
carefully quiet, trembling,
and speaking to himself.

3154
02:42:53,089 --> 02:42:54,496
“Where is your strength?”

3155
02:42:54,496 --> 02:42:55,478
he demanded.

3156
02:42:55,478 --> 02:42:58,468
“I reckon it is joy that
has unsteadied your laigs.”

3157
02:42:58,468 --> 02:42:59,416
The door opened.

3158
02:42:59,416 --> 02:43:01,959
It was she, come back with his dinner.

3159
02:43:01,959 --> 02:43:03,683
“My Heavens!”

3160
02:43:03,683 --> 02:43:08,074
she said; and setting the tray down,
she rushed to him.

3161
02:43:08,074 --> 02:43:11,156
She helped him back to his chair,
and covered him again.

3162
02:43:11,156 --> 02:43:13,916
He had suffered no hurt,
but she clung to him;

3163
02:43:13,916 --> 02:43:18,990
and presently he moved and let himself
kiss her with fuller passion.

3164
02:43:18,990 --> 02:43:20,953
“I will be good,” he whispered.

3165
02:43:20,953 --> 02:43:23,458
“You must,” she said.

3166
02:43:23,458 --> 02:43:24,975
“You looked so pale!”

3167
02:43:24,975 --> 02:43:27,507
“You are speakin’ low
like me,” he answered.

3168
02:43:27,507 --> 02:43:30,273
“But we have no dream we can wake from.”

3169
02:43:30,273 --> 02:43:34,777
Had she surrendered on this day to her
cowpuncher, her wild man?

3170
02:43:34,777 --> 02:43:37,432
Was she forever wholly his?

3171
02:43:37,432 --> 02:43:42,748
Had the Virginian’s fire so melted her
heart that no rift in it remained?

3172
02:43:42,748 --> 02:43:45,596
So she would have thought if any thought
had come to her.

3173
02:43:45,596 --> 02:43:49,821
But in his arms today,
thought was lost in something

3174
02:43:49,821 --> 02:43:50,821
more divine.

3175
02:43:50,821 --> 02:43:52,181
CHAPTER XXIX

3176
02:43:52,181 --> 02:43:53,331
Word to Bennington

3177
02:43:53,331 --> 02:43:57,972
They kept their secret for a while,
or at least they had that special joy of

3178
02:43:57,972 --> 02:44:02,718
believing that no one in all the world
but themselves knew this that

3179
02:44:02,718 --> 02:44:03,670
had happened to them.

3180
02:44:03,670 --> 02:44:08,679
But I think that there was one person who
knew how to keep a secret even better

3181
02:44:08,679 --> 02:44:10,434
than these two lovers.

3182
02:44:10,434 --> 02:44:10,840
Mrs.

3183
02:44:10,840 --> 02:44:13,960
Taylor made no remarks to anyone whatever.

3184
02:44:13,960 --> 02:44:19,061
Nobody on Bear Creek,
however, was so extraordinarily

3185
02:44:19,061 --> 02:44:20,740
cheerful and serene.

3186
02:44:20,740 --> 02:44:26,334
That peculiar severity which she had
manifested in the days when Molly was

3187
02:44:26,334 --> 02:44:31,572
packing her possessions,
had now altogether changed.

3188
02:44:31,572 --> 02:44:34,972
In these days she was endlessly kind and
indulgent to her “deary.”

3189
02:44:34,972 --> 02:44:38,453
Although, as a housekeeper,
Mrs. Taylor believed in punctuality at

3190
02:44:38,453 --> 02:44:42,997
meals, and visited her offspring with
discipline when they were late without

3191
02:44:42,997 --> 02:44:46,757
good and sufficient excuse,
Molly was now exempt from the

3192
02:44:46,757 --> 02:44:49,222
faintest hint of reprimand.

3193
02:44:49,222 --> 02:44:54,085
“And it’s not because you’re not her
mother,” said George Taylor, bitterly.

3194
02:44:54,085 --> 02:44:55,515
“She used to get it, too.

3195
02:44:55,515 --> 02:44:57,396
And we’re the only ones that get it.

3196
02:44:57,396 --> 02:45:00,703
There she comes, just as we’re
about ready to quit!

3197
02:45:00,703 --> 02:45:02,788
Aren’t you going to say nothing to her?”

3198
02:45:02,788 --> 02:45:06,921
“George,” said his mother,
“when you’ve saved a man’s life it’ll be

3199
02:45:06,921 --> 02:45:08,267
time for you to talk.”

3200
02:45:08,267 --> 02:45:12,788
So Molly would come in to her meals with
much irregularity; and her remarks about

3201
02:45:12,788 --> 02:45:18,265
the imperfections of her clock
met with no rejoinder.

3202
02:45:18,265 --> 02:45:24,929
And yet one can scarcely be so severe as
had been Mrs. Taylor,

3203
02:45:24,929 --> 02:45:29,689
and become wholly as mild as milk.

3204
02:45:29,689 --> 02:45:34,355
There was one recurrent event that could
invariably awaken hostile

3205
02:45:34,355 --> 02:45:36,187
symptoms in the dame.

3206
02:45:36,187 --> 02:45:40,214
Whenever she saw a letter arrive with the
Bennington postmark upon it,

3207
02:45:40,214 --> 02:45:42,247
she shook her fist at that letter.

3208
02:45:42,247 --> 02:45:44,201
“What’s family pride?”

3209
02:45:44,201 --> 02:45:45,997
she would say to herself.

3210
02:45:45,997 --> 02:45:49,679
“Taylor could be a Son of the Revolution
if he’d a mind to.

3211
02:45:49,679 --> -1:59:59,000
I wonder if she has told her folks yet.

3212
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

3213
02:45:52,349 --> 02:45:57,401
And when letters directed to Bennington
would go out, Mrs. Taylor would inspect

3214
02:45:57,401 --> 02:46:03,994
every one as if its envelope ought to
grow transparent beneath her eyes,

3215
02:46:03,994 --> 02:46:08,685
and yield up to her its great secret,
if it had one.

3216
02:46:08,685 --> 02:46:17,099
But in truth these letters had no great
secret to yield up, until one day⁠—yes;

3217
02:46:17,099 --> 02:46:22,806
one day Mrs. Taylor would have burst,
were bursting a thing

3218
02:46:22,806 --> 02:46:24,714
that people often did.

3219
02:46:24,714 --> 02:46:28,439
Three letters were the cause of this
emotion on Mrs. Taylor’s part;

3220
02:46:28,439 --> 02:46:34,624
one addressed to Bennington,
one to Dunbarton, and the third⁠—here

3221
02:46:34,624 --> 02:46:38,839
was the great excitement⁠—to Bennington,
but not in the little

3222
02:46:38,839 --> 02:46:40,724
schoolmarm’s delicate writing.

3223
02:46:40,724 --> 02:46:46,627
A man’s hand had traced those plain,
steady vowels and consonants.

3224
02:46:46,627 --> 02:46:47,762
“It’s come!”

3225
02:46:47,762 --> 02:46:51,162
exclaimed Mrs. Taylor, at this sight.

3226
02:46:51,162 --> 02:46:54,467
“He has written to her mother himself.”

3227
02:46:54,467 --> 02:47:00,303
That is what the Virginian had done,
and here is how it had come about.

3228
02:47:00,303 --> 02:47:04,024
The sick man’s convalescence was achieved.

3229
02:47:04,024 --> 02:47:07,787
The weeks had brought back to him,
not his whole strength yet⁠—that could

3230
02:47:07,787 --> 02:47:12,187
come only by many miles of open air on
the back of Monte; but he was strong

3231
02:47:12,187 --> 02:47:15,128
enough now to get strength.

3232
02:47:15,128 --> 02:47:19,394
When a patient reaches this stage,
he is out of the woods.

3233
02:47:19,394 --> 02:47:22,332
He had gone for a little
walk with his nurse.

3234
02:47:22,332 --> 02:47:26,353
They had taken (under the doctor’s
recommendation) several such little

3235
02:47:26,353 --> 02:47:30,654
walks, beginning with a five-minute one,
and at last today accomplishing

3236
02:47:30,654 --> 02:47:31,527
three miles.

3237
02:47:31,527 --> 02:47:34,544
“No, it has not been too far,” said he.

3238
02:47:34,544 --> 02:47:37,974
“I am afraid I could walk twice as far.”

3239
02:47:37,974 --> 02:47:39,116
“Afraid?”

3240
02:47:39,116 --> 02:47:40,167
“Yes.

3241
02:47:40,167 --> 02:47:42,745
Because it means I can go to work again.

3242
02:47:42,745 --> 02:47:44,893
This thing we have had together is over.”

3243
02:47:44,893 --> 02:47:46,731
For reply, she leaned against him.

3244
02:47:46,731 --> 02:47:47,768
“Look at you!”

3245
02:47:47,768 --> 02:47:48,541
he said.

3246
02:47:48,541 --> 02:47:53,570
“Only a little while ago you had to help
me stand on my laigs.

3247
02:47:53,570 --> 02:47:57,309
And now⁠—” For a while there
was silence between them.

3248
02:47:57,309 --> 02:48:01,584
“I have never had a right down sickness
before,” he presently went on.

3249
02:48:01,584 --> 02:48:03,199
“Not to remember, that is.

3250
02:48:03,199 --> 02:48:08,863
If any person had told me I could enjoy
such a thing⁠—” He said no more,

3251
02:48:08,863 --> 02:48:12,825
for she reached up, and no
more speech was possible.

3252
02:48:12,825 --> 02:48:14,033
“How long has it been?”

3253
02:48:14,033 --> 02:48:15,198
he next asked her.

3254
02:48:15,198 --> 02:48:16,457
She told him.

3255
02:48:16,457 --> 02:48:20,105
“Well, if it could be forever⁠—no.

3256
02:48:20,105 --> 02:48:23,526
Not forever with no more than this.

3257
02:48:23,526 --> 02:48:25,415
I reckon I’d be sick again!

3258
02:48:25,415 --> 02:48:29,800
But if it could be forever with just you
and me, and no one else to bother with.

3259
02:48:29,800 --> 02:48:32,703
But any longer would not be doing
right by your mother.

3260
02:48:32,703 --> 02:48:35,305
She would have a right to
think ill of me.”

3261
02:48:35,305 --> 02:48:35,823
“Oh!”

3262
02:48:35,823 --> 02:48:36,543
said the girl.

3263
02:48:36,543 --> -1:59:59,000
“Let us keep it.”

3264
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
“

3265
02:48:37,567 --> 02:48:39,074
Not after I am gone.

3266
02:48:39,074 --> 02:48:41,144
Your mother must be told.”

3267
02:48:41,144 --> 02:48:44,647
“It seems so⁠—can’t we⁠—oh,
why need anybody know?”

3268
02:48:44,647 --> 02:48:47,632
“Your mother ain’t ‘anybody.’

3269
02:48:47,632 --> 02:48:48,416
She is your mother.

3270
02:48:48,416 --> 02:48:51,556
I feel mighty responsible to her for
what I have done.”

3271
02:48:51,556 --> 02:48:52,732
“But I did it!”

3272
02:48:52,732 --> 02:48:53,746
“Do you think so?

3273
02:48:53,746 --> 02:48:56,570
Your mother will not think so.

3274
02:48:56,570 --> 02:48:58,856
I am going to write to her today.”

3275
02:48:58,856 --> 02:48:59,490
“You!

3276
02:48:59,490 --> 02:49:01,550
Write to my mother!

3277
02:49:01,550 --> 02:49:05,278
Oh, then everything will be so different!

3278
02:49:05,278 --> 02:49:09,845
They will all⁠—” Molly stopped before the
rising visions of Bennington.

3279
02:49:09,845 --> 02:49:14,286
Upon the fairytale that she had been
living with her cowboy lover broke the

3280
02:49:14,286 --> 02:49:18,528
voices of the world.

3281
02:49:19,309 --> 02:49:21,777
She could hear them from afar.

3282
02:49:21,777 --> 02:49:26,374
She could see the eyes of Bennington
watching this man at her side.

3283
02:49:26,374 --> 02:49:31,205
She could imagine the ears of Bennington
listening for slips in his English.

3284
02:49:31,205 --> 02:49:35,016
There loomed upon her the round of visits
which they would have to make.

3285
02:49:35,016 --> 02:49:38,457
The ringing of the doorbells,
the waiting in drawing-rooms for the

3286
02:49:38,457 --> 02:49:42,445
mistress to descend and utter her
prepared congratulations,

3287
02:49:42,445 --> 02:49:46,332
while her secret eye devoured the
Virginian’s appearance,

3288
02:49:46,332 --> 02:49:48,479
and his manner of standing and sitting.

3289
02:49:48,479 --> 02:49:51,692
He would be wearing gloves,
instead of fringed gauntlets of

3290
02:49:51,692 --> 02:49:52,632
buckskin.

3291
02:49:52,632 --> 02:49:58,316
In a smooth black coat and waistcoat,
how could they perceive the man he was?

3292
02:49:58,316 --> 02:50:01,937
During those short formal interviews,
what would they ever find out of the

3293
02:50:01,937 --> 02:50:03,445
things that she knew about him?

3294
02:50:03,445 --> 02:50:06,066
The things for which she was proud of him?

3295
02:50:06,066 --> 02:50:11,682
He would speak shortly and simply;
they would say, “Oh, yes!”

3296
02:50:11,682 --> 02:50:15,802
and “How different you must find this
from Wyoming!”⁠—and then,

3297
02:50:15,802 --> 02:50:21,143
after the door was shut behind his
departing back they would say⁠—He would

3298
02:50:21,143 --> 02:50:24,876
be totally underrated,
not in the least understood.

3299
02:50:24,876 --> 02:50:26,921
Why should he be subjected to this?

3300
02:50:26,921 --> 02:50:28,316
He should never be!

3301
02:50:28,316 --> 02:50:33,901
Now in all these half-formed,
hurried, distressing thoughts which

3302
02:50:33,901 --> 02:50:38,964
streamed through the girl’s mind,
she altogether forgot one truth.

3303
02:50:38,964 --> 02:50:44,053
True it was that the voice of the world
would speak as she imagined.

3304
02:50:44,053 --> 02:50:48,495
True it was that in the eyes of her
family and acquaintance this lover of

3305
02:50:48,495 --> 02:50:53,838
her choice would be examined even more
like a specimen than are other lovers

3306
02:50:53,838 --> 02:50:57,611
upon these occasions:
and all accepted lovers have to face

3307
02:50:57,611 --> 02:51:02,826
this ordeal of being treated like
specimens by the other family.

3308
02:51:02,826 --> 02:51:03,700
But dear me!

3309
02:51:03,700 --> 02:51:06,823
most of us manage to stand it, don’t we?

3310
02:51:06,823 --> 02:51:11,346
It isn’t, perhaps, the most delicious
experience that we can recall in

3311
02:51:11,346 --> 02:51:12,951
connection with our engagement.

3312
02:51:12,951 --> 02:51:14,861
But it didn’t prove fatal.

3313
02:51:14,861 --> 02:51:16,268
We got through it somehow.

3314
02:51:16,268 --> 02:51:19,736
We dined with Aunt Jane,
and wined with Uncle Joseph,

3315
02:51:19,736 --> 02:51:24,312
and perhaps had two fingers given to us
by old Cousin Horatio,

3316
02:51:24,312 --> 02:51:28,391
whose enormous fortune was of the
greatest importance to everybody.

3317
02:51:28,391 --> 02:51:32,258
And perhaps fragments of the other
family’s estimate of us subsequently

3318
02:51:32,258 --> 02:51:34,278
reached our own ears.

3319
02:51:34,278 --> 02:51:38,278
But if a chosen lover cannot stand being
treated as a specimen by the other

3320
02:51:38,278 --> 02:51:42,849
family, he’s a very weak vessel,
and not worth any good girl’s love.

3321
02:51:42,849 --> 02:51:45,149
That’s all I can say for him.

3322
02:51:45,149 --> 02:51:49,521
Now the Virginian was scarcely what even
his enemy would term a weak vessel;

3323
02:51:49,521 --> 02:51:53,149
and Molly’s jealousy of the impression
which he might make upon

3324
02:51:53,149 --> 02:51:56,002
Bennington was vastly superfluous.

3325
02:51:56,002 --> 02:51:59,630
She should have known that he would
indeed care to make a good impression;

3326
02:51:59,630 --> 02:52:04,566
but that such anxiety on his part would
be wholly for her sake,

3327
02:52:04,566 --> 02:52:08,377
that in the eyes of her friends she
might stand justified in taking him

3328
02:52:08,377 --> 02:52:09,657
for her wedded husband.

3329
02:52:09,657 --> 02:52:14,902
So far as he was concerned apart from
her, Aunt Jane and Uncle Joseph might

3330
02:52:14,902 --> 02:52:18,792
say anything they pleased,
or think anything they pleased.

3331
02:52:18,792 --> 02:52:22,136
His character was open for investigation.

3332
02:52:22,136 --> 02:52:25,459
Judge Henry would vouch for him.

3333
02:52:25,459 --> 02:52:29,831
This is what he would have said to his
sweetheart had she but revealed

3334
02:52:29,831 --> 02:52:31,813
to him her perturbations.

3335
02:52:31,813 --> 02:52:35,302
But she did not reveal them;
and they were not of the order that he

3336
02:52:35,302 --> 02:52:38,005
with his nature was likely to divine.

3337
02:52:38,005 --> 02:52:41,483
I do not know what good would have come
from her speaking out to him,

3338
02:52:41,483 --> 02:52:45,336
unless that perfect understanding
between lovers which indeed

3339
02:52:45,336 --> 02:52:46,602
is a good thing.

3340
02:52:46,602 --> 02:52:52,180
But I do not believe that he could have
reassured her; and I am certain that she

3341
02:52:52,180 --> 02:52:54,734
could not have prevented his
writing to her mother.

3342
02:52:54,734 --> 02:52:59,459
“Well, then,” she sighed at last,
“if you think so, I will tell her.”

3343
02:52:59,459 --> 02:53:06,793
That sigh of hers, be it well understood,
was not only because of those far-off

3344
02:53:06,793 --> 02:53:10,915
voices which the world would in
consequence of her news

3345
02:53:10,915 --> 02:53:12,235
be lifting presently.

3346
02:53:12,235 --> 02:53:16,814
It came also from bidding farewell to the
fairytale which she must leave now;

3347
02:53:16,814 --> 02:53:22,445
that land in which she and he had been
living close together alone,

3348
02:53:22,445 --> 02:53:25,827
unhindered, unmindful of all things.

3349
02:53:25,827 --> 02:53:29,901
“Yes, you will tell her,” said her lover.

3350
02:53:29,901 --> 02:53:31,358
“And I must tell her too.”

3351
02:53:31,358 --> 02:53:32,272
“Both of us?”

3352
02:53:32,272 --> 02:53:33,454
questioned the girl.

3353
02:53:33,454 --> 02:53:35,481
What would he say to her mother?

3354
02:53:35,481 --> 02:53:39,927
How would her mother like such a letter
as he would write to her?

3355
02:53:39,927 --> 02:53:42,268
Suppose he should misspell a word?

3356
02:53:42,268 --> 02:53:47,741
Would not sentences from him at this
time⁠—written sentences⁠—be a further

3357
02:53:47,741 --> -1:59:59,000
bar to his welcome acceptance
at Bennington

3358
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
?

3359
02:53:51,557 --> 02:53:54,308
“Why don’t you send messages by me?”

3360
02:53:54,308 --> 02:53:55,048
she asked him.

3361
02:53:55,048 --> 02:53:55,909
He shook his head.

3362
02:53:55,909 --> 02:53:59,083
“She is not going to like
it, anyway,” he answered.

3363
02:53:59,083 --> 02:54:01,218
“I must speak to her direct.

3364
02:54:01,218 --> 02:54:03,327
It would be like shirking.”

3365
02:54:03,327 --> 02:54:08,423
Molly saw how true his instinct was here;
and a little flame shot upward from the

3366
02:54:08,423 --> 02:54:11,053
glow of her love and pride in him.

3367
02:54:11,053 --> 02:54:15,360
Oh, if they could all only know that he
was like this when you understood him!

3368
02:54:15,360 --> 02:54:19,052
She did not dare say out to him what her
fear was about this letter of

3369
02:54:19,052 --> 02:54:20,862
his to her mother.

3370
02:54:20,862 --> 02:54:25,366
She did not dare because⁠—well,
because she lacked a little faith.

3371
02:54:25,366 --> 02:54:26,813
That is it, I am afraid.

3372
02:54:26,813 --> 02:54:30,708
And for that sin she was
her own punishment.

3373
02:54:30,708 --> 02:54:37,067
For in this day, and in many days to
come, the pure joy of her love was vexed

3374
02:54:37,067 --> 02:54:42,743
and clouded, all through a little lack
of faith; while for him,

3375
02:54:42,743 --> 02:54:46,025
perfect in his faith,
his joy was like crystal.

3376
02:54:46,025 --> 02:54:49,094
“Tell me what you’re going
to write,” she said.

3377
02:54:49,094 --> 02:54:50,855
He smiled at her.

3378
02:54:50,855 --> 02:54:52,175
“No.”

3379
02:54:52,175 --> 02:54:56,322
“Aren’t you going to let me see
it when it’s done?”

3380
02:54:56,322 --> 02:54:56,898
“No.”

3381
02:54:56,898 --> 02:54:59,353
Then a freakish look came into his eyes.

3382
02:54:59,353 --> 02:55:01,522
“I’ll let yu’ see anything I
write to other women.”

3383
02:55:01,522 --> 02:55:03,717
And he gave her one of his long kisses.

3384
02:55:03,717 --> 02:55:08,419
“Let’s get through with it together,”
he suggested, when they were once more

3385
02:55:08,419 --> 02:55:12,480
in his sickroom, that room which she
had given to him.

3386
02:55:12,480 --> 02:55:15,725
“You’ll sit one side o’ the table,
and I’ll sit the other,

3387
02:55:15,725 --> 02:55:19,026
and we’ll go ahaid; and pretty soon
it will be done.”

3388
02:55:19,026 --> 02:55:20,620
“O dear!”

3389
02:55:20,620 --> 02:55:21,422
she said.

3390
02:55:21,422 --> 02:55:23,820
“Yes, I suppose that is the best way.”

3391
02:55:23,820 --> 02:55:26,730
And so, accordingly, they
took their places.

3392
02:55:26,730 --> 02:55:28,694
The inkstand stood between them.

3393
02:55:28,694 --> 02:55:33,750
Beside each of them she distributed paper
enough, almost, for a

3394
02:55:33,750 --> 02:55:35,059
presidential message.

3395
02:55:35,059 --> 02:55:37,743
And pens and pencils were in plenty.

3396
02:55:37,743 --> 02:55:42,845
Was this not the headquarters of
the Bear Creek schoolmarm?

3397
02:55:42,845 --> 02:55:45,704
“Why, aren’t you going to do
it in pencil first?”

3398
02:55:45,704 --> 02:55:49,181
she exclaimed, looking up
from her vacant sheet.

3399
02:55:49,181 --> 02:55:52,211
His pen was moving slowly, but steadily.

3400
02:55:52,211 --> 02:55:56,995
“No, I don’t reckon I need to,”
he answered, with his nose

3401
02:55:56,995 --> 02:55:58,242
close to the paper.

3402
02:55:58,242 --> 02:56:00,455
“Oh, damnation, there’s a blot!”

3403
02:56:00,455 --> 02:56:05,107
He tore his spoiled beginning in small
bits, and threw them into the fireplace.

3404
02:56:05,107 --> 02:56:09,251
“You’ve got it too full,”
he commented; and taking the inkstand,

3405
02:56:09,251 --> 02:56:11,079
he tipped a little from it
out of the window.

3406
02:56:11,079 --> 02:56:15,073
She sat lost among her false starts.

3407
02:56:15,073 --> 02:56:18,210
Had she heard him swear,
she would not have minded.

3408
02:56:18,210 --> 02:56:20,435
She rather liked it when he swore.

3409
02:56:20,435 --> 02:56:25,606
He possessed that quality in his
profanity of not offending by it.

3410
02:56:25,606 --> 02:56:30,832
It is quite wonderful how much worse the
same word will sound in one man’s

3411
02:56:30,832 --> 02:56:33,216
lips than in another’s.

3412
02:56:33,216 --> 02:56:35,220
But she did not hear him.

3413
02:56:35,220 --> 02:56:38,921
Her mind was among a litter
of broken sentences.

3414
02:56:38,921 --> 02:56:42,626
Each thought which she began ran out into
the empty air, or came

3415
02:56:42,626 --> 02:56:44,226
against some stone wall.

3416
02:56:44,226 --> 02:56:49,066
So there she sat, her eyes now upon that
inexorable blank sheet that lay before

3417
02:56:49,066 --> 02:56:53,951
her, waiting, and now turned with vacant
hopelessness upon the sundry

3418
02:56:53,951 --> 02:56:55,913
objects in the room.

3419
02:56:55,913 --> 02:57:01,529
And while she thus sat accomplishing
nothing, opposite to her the black head

3420
02:57:01,529 --> 02:57:06,028
bent down, and the steady pen moved
from phrase to phrase.

3421
02:57:06,028 --> 02:57:10,322
She became aware of his gazing at
her, flushed and solemn.

3422
02:57:10,322 --> 02:57:14,362
That strange color of the seawater,
which she could never name,

3423
02:57:14,362 --> 02:57:16,002
was lustrous in his eyes.

3424
02:57:16,002 --> 02:57:17,762
He was folding his letter.

3425
02:57:17,762 --> 02:57:19,320
“You have finished?”

3426
02:57:19,320 --> 02:57:20,073
she said.

3427
02:57:20,073 --> 02:57:20,970
“Yes.”

3428
02:57:20,970 --> 02:57:22,995
His voice was very quiet.

3429
02:57:22,995 --> 02:57:24,890
“I feel like an honester man.”

3430
02:57:24,890 --> 02:57:30,159
“Perhaps I can do something tonight at
Mrs. Taylor’s,” she said,

3431
02:57:30,159 --> 02:57:31,079
looking at her paper.

3432
02:57:31,079 --> 02:57:34,342
On it were a few words crossed out.

3433
02:57:34,342 --> 02:57:36,822
This was all she had to show.

3434
02:57:36,822 --> 02:57:41,386
At this set task in letter-writing,
the cowpuncher had greatly

3435
02:57:41,386 --> 02:57:42,851
excelled the schoolmarm!

3436
02:57:42,851 --> 02:57:47,146
But that night, while he lay quite fast
asleep in his bed, she was keeping vigil

3437
02:57:47,146 --> 02:57:49,306
in her room at Mrs. Taylor’s.

3438
02:57:49,306 --> 02:57:53,146
Accordingly, the next day,
those three letters departed for the

3439
02:57:53,146 --> 02:57:58,210
mail, and Mrs. Taylor consequently made
her exclamation, “It’s come!”

3440
02:57:58,210 --> 02:58:03,229
On the day before the Virginian returned
to take up his work at Judge Henry’s

3441
02:58:03,229 --> 02:58:08,991
ranch, he and Molly announced their
news.

3442
02:58:08,991 --> 02:58:15,291
What Molly said to Mrs. Taylor and what
Mrs. Taylor said to her,

3443
02:58:15,291 --> 02:58:18,612
is of no interest to us,
though it was of much to them.

3444
02:58:18,612 --> 02:58:23,735
But Mr. McLean happened to make a call
quite early in the morning to inquire

3445
02:58:23,735 --> 02:58:25,074
for his friend’s health.

3446
02:58:25,074 --> 02:58:29,215
“Lin,” began the Virginian,
“there is no harm in your knowing an

3447
02:58:29,215 --> 02:58:31,855
hour or so before the rest, I am⁠—”

3448
02:58:31,855 --> 02:58:32,865
“Lord!”

3449
02:58:32,865 --> 02:58:34,724
said Mr. McLean, indulgently.

3450
02:58:34,724 --> 02:58:39,246
“Everybody has knowed that since the day
she found yu’ at the spring.”

3451
02:58:39,246 --> 02:58:42,924
“It was not so, then,”
said the Virginian, crossly.

3452
02:58:42,924 --> 02:58:43,652
“Lord!

3453
02:58:43,652 --> 02:58:45,630
Everybody has knowed it right along.”

3454
02:58:45,630 --> 02:58:46,212
“Hmp!”

3455
02:58:46,212 --> 02:58:47,411
said the Virginian.

3456
02:58:47,411 --> 02:58:51,703
“I didn’t know this country was
that rank with gossips.”

3457
02:58:51,703 --> 02:58:52,193
Mr.

3458
02:58:52,193 --> 02:58:54,764
McLean laughed mirthfully at the lover.

3459
02:58:54,764 --> 02:58:57,490
“Well,” he said, “Mrs.

3460
02:58:57,490 --> 02:58:59,167
McLean will be glad.

3461
02:58:59,167 --> 02:59:02,767
She told me to give yu’ her
congratulations quite a while ago.

3462
02:59:02,767 --> 02:59:06,807
I was to have ’em ready just as soon as
ever yu’ asked for ’em yourself.”

3463
02:59:06,807 --> 02:59:11,891
Lin had been made a happy man some twelve
months previous to this.

3464
02:59:11,891 --> 02:59:16,971
And now, by way of an exchange of news,
he added: “We’re expectin’ a little

3465
02:59:16,971 --> 02:59:19,058
McLean down on Box Elder.

3466
02:59:19,058 --> 02:59:22,097
That’s what you’ll be expectin’ some of
these days, I hope.”

3467
02:59:22,097 --> 02:59:25,361
“Yes,” murmured the Virginian,
“I hope so too.”

3468
02:59:25,361 --> 02:59:29,584
“And I don’t guess,” said Lin,
“that you and I will do much shufflin’

3469
02:59:29,584 --> -1:59:59,000
of other folks’ children any more.

3470
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

3471
02:59:31,424 --> 02:59:35,624
Whereupon he and the Virginian shook
hands silently, and understood

3472
02:59:35,624 --> 02:59:37,694
each other very well.

3473
02:59:37,694 --> 02:59:42,030
On the day that the Virginian parted with
Molly, beside the weight of farewell

3474
02:59:42,030 --> 02:59:46,918
which lay heavy on his heart,
his thoughts were also grave with news.

3475
02:59:46,918 --> 02:59:51,844
The cattle thieves had
grown more audacious.

3476
02:59:51,844 --> 02:59:55,685
Horses and cattle both were being missed,
and each man began almost

3477
02:59:55,685 --> 02:59:56,927
to doubt his neighbor.

3478
02:59:56,927 --> 03:00:01,545
“Steps will have to be taken soon by
somebody, I reckon,” said the lover.

3479
03:00:01,545 --> 03:00:03,011
“By you?”

3480
03:00:03,011 --> 03:00:04,128
she asked quickly.

3481
03:00:04,128 --> 03:00:06,248
“Most likely I’ll get mixed up with it.”

3482
03:00:06,248 --> 03:00:07,932
“What will you have to do?”

3483
03:00:07,932 --> 03:00:08,928
“Can’t say.

3484
03:00:08,928 --> -1:59:59,000
I’ll tell yu’ when I come back.

3485
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

3486
03:00:11,499 --> 03:00:14,659
So did he part from her,
leaving her more kisses

3487
03:00:14,659 --> 03:00:16,319
than words to remember.

3488
03:00:16,319 --> 03:00:20,578
And what was doing at Bennington,
meanwhile, and at Dunbarton?

3489
03:00:20,578 --> 03:00:25,011
Those three letters which by their mere
outside had so moved Mrs. Taylor,

3490
03:00:25,011 --> 03:00:28,664
produced by their contents
much painful disturbance.

3491
03:00:28,664 --> 03:00:33,229
It will be remembered that Molly wrote to
her mother, and to her great-aunt.

3492
03:00:33,229 --> 03:00:36,926
That announcement to her
mother was undertaken first.

3493
03:00:36,926 --> 03:00:42,345
Its composition occupied three hours and
a half, and it filled eleven pages,

3494
03:00:42,345 --> 03:00:44,463
not counting a postscript
upon the twelfth.

3495
03:00:44,463 --> 03:00:47,965
The letter to the great-aunt
took only ten minutes.

3496
03:00:47,965 --> 03:00:52,361
I cannot pretend to explain why this one
was so greatly superior to the other;

3497
03:00:52,361 --> 03:00:54,137
but such is the remarkable fact.

3498
03:00:54,137 --> 03:00:56,945
Its beginning, to be sure,
did give the old lady a start;

3499
03:00:56,945 --> 03:00:59,916
she had dismissed the
cowboy from her probabilities.

3500
03:00:59,916 --> 03:01:00,985
“Tut, tut, tut!”

3501
03:01:00,985 --> 03:01:03,381
she exclaimed out loud in her bedroom.

3502
03:01:03,381 --> 03:01:05,549
“She has thrown herself
away on that fellow!”

3503
03:01:05,549 --> 03:01:12,210
But some sentences at the end made her
pause and sit still for a long while.

3504
03:01:12,210 --> 03:01:19,075
The severity upon her face
changed to tenderness, gradually.

3505
03:01:19,075 --> 03:01:21,793
“Ah, me,” she sighed.

3506
03:01:21,793 --> 03:01:24,166
“If marriage were as simple as love!”

3507
03:01:24,166 --> 03:01:27,610
Then she went slowly downstairs,
and out into her garden,

3508
03:01:27,610 --> 03:01:29,955
where she walked long
between the box borders.

3509
03:01:29,955 --> 03:01:34,035
“But if she has found a great love,”
said the old lady at length.

3510
03:01:34,035 --> 03:01:37,235
And she returned to her bedroom,
and opened an old desk,

3511
03:01:37,235 --> 03:01:39,174
and read some old letters.

3512
03:01:39,174 --> 03:01:43,609
There came to her the next morning
a communication from Bennington.

3513
03:01:43,609 --> 03:01:46,887
This had been penned frantically
by poor Mrs. Wood.

3514
03:01:46,887 --> 03:01:50,007
As soon as she had been able to gather
her senses after the shock of her

3515
03:01:50,007 --> 03:01:53,971
daughter’s eleven pages and the
postscript, the mother had poured out

3516
03:01:53,971 --> 03:01:56,929
eight pages herself to the eldest
member of the family.

3517
03:01:56,929 --> 03:02:00,855
There had been, indeed,
much excuse for the poor lady.

3518
03:02:00,855 --> 03:02:06,874
To begin with, Molly had constructed her
whole opening page with the express and

3519
03:02:06,874 --> 03:02:09,692
merciful intention of
preparing her mother.

3520
03:02:09,692 --> 03:02:12,590
Consequently, it made no sense whatever.

3521
03:02:12,590 --> 03:02:16,635
Its effect was the usual effect of
remarks designed to break a thing

3522
03:02:16,635 --> 03:02:17,298
gently.

3523
03:02:17,298 --> 03:02:22,752
It merely made Mrs. Wood’s head swim,
and filled her with a sickening dread.

3524
03:02:22,752 --> 03:02:27,283
“Oh, mercy, Sarah,” she
had cried, “come here.

3525
03:02:27,283 --> 03:02:28,402
What does this mean?”

3526
03:02:28,402 --> 03:02:32,639
And then, fortified by her elder
daughter, she had turned over that first

3527
03:02:32,639 --> 03:02:35,699
page and found what it meant on the
top of the second.

3528
03:02:35,699 --> 03:02:38,883
“A savage with knives and pistols!”

3529
03:02:38,883 --> 03:02:39,733
she wailed.

3530
03:02:39,733 --> 03:02:43,537
“Well, mother, I always told you so,”
said her daughter Sarah.

3531
03:02:43,537 --> 03:02:44,907
“What is a foreman?”

3532
03:02:44,907 --> 03:02:46,089
exclaimed the mother.

3533
03:02:46,089 --> 03:02:47,670
“And who is Judge Henry?”

3534
03:02:47,670 --> 03:02:51,040
“She has taken a sort of
upper servant,” said Sarah.

3535
03:02:51,040 --> 03:02:54,943
“If it is allowed to go as far as a
wedding, I doubt if I can bring

3536
03:02:54,943 --> 03:02:56,867
myself to be present.”

3537
03:02:56,867 --> 03:03:01,544
(This threat she proceeded to make to
Molly, with results that shall be set

3538
03:03:01,544 --> -1:59:59,000
forth in their proper place.

3539
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
)

3540
03:03:03,681 --> 03:03:07,725
“The man appears to have written to me
himself,” said Mrs. Wood.

3541
03:03:07,725 --> 03:03:10,334
“He knows no better,” said Sarah.

3542
03:03:10,334 --> 03:03:11,296
“Bosh!”

3543
03:03:11,296 --> 03:03:13,295
said Sarah’s husband later.

3544
03:03:13,295 --> 03:03:15,501
“It was a very manly thing to do.”

3545
03:03:15,501 --> 03:03:20,167
Thus did consternation rage in
the house at Bennington.

3546
03:03:20,167 --> 03:03:24,287
Molly might have spared herself the many
assurances that she gave concerning the

3547
03:03:24,287 --> 03:03:28,207
universal esteem in which her cowpuncher
was held, and the fair

3548
03:03:28,207 --> 03:03:30,199
prospects which were his.

3549
03:03:30,199 --> 03:03:36,795
So, in the first throes of her despair,
Mrs. Wood wrote those eight not maturely

3550
03:03:36,795 --> 03:03:39,441
considered pages to the great-aunt.

3551
03:03:39,441 --> 03:03:40,770
“Tut, tut, tut!”

3552
03:03:40,770 --> 03:03:42,560
said the great-aunt as she read them.

3553
03:03:42,560 --> 03:03:46,289
Her face was much more severe today.

3554
03:03:46,289 --> 03:03:51,129
“You’d suppose,” she said,
“that the girl had been kidnapped!

3555
03:03:51,129 --> 03:03:54,800
Why, she has kept him
waiting three years!”

3556
03:03:54,800 --> 03:03:57,455
And then she read more,
but soon put the letter

3557
03:03:57,455 --> 03:03:58,532
down with laughter.

3558
03:03:58,532 --> 03:04:02,695
For Mrs. Wood had repeated in writing
that early outburst of hers about a

3559
03:04:02,695 --> 03:04:05,899
savage with knives and pistols.

3560
03:04:05,899 --> 03:04:06,636
“Law!”

3561
03:04:06,636 --> 03:04:07,869
said the great-aunt.

3562
03:04:07,869 --> 03:04:10,465
“Law, what a fool Lizzie is!”

3563
03:04:10,465 --> 03:04:14,780
So she sat down and wrote to Mrs. Wood a
wholesome reply about putting a little

3564
03:04:14,780 --> 03:04:18,780
more trust in her own flesh and blood,
and reminding her among other things

3565
03:04:18,780 --> 03:04:24,082
that General Stark had himself been wont
to carry knives and pistols owing to the

3566
03:04:24,082 --> 03:04:27,642
necessities of his career,
but that he had occasionally taken them

3567
03:04:27,642 --> 03:04:30,546
off, as did probably this
young man in Wyoming.

3568
03:04:30,546 --> 03:04:34,762
“You had better send me the letter he has
written you,” she concluded.

3569
03:04:34,762 --> 03:04:38,122
“I shall know much better what to think
after I have seen that.”

3570
03:04:38,122 --> 03:04:42,223
It is not probable that Mrs. Wood got
much comfort from this communication;

3571
03:04:42,223 --> 03:04:46,510
and her daughter Sarah was
actually enraged by it.

3572
03:04:46,510 --> 03:04:52,763
“She grows more perverse as she nears
her dotage,” said Sarah.

3573
03:04:52,763 --> 03:04:57,107
But the Virginian’s letter was sent to
Dunbarton, where the old lady sat

3574
03:04:57,107 --> 03:05:00,813
herself down to read
it with much attention.

3575
03:05:00,813 --> 03:05:05,121
Here is what the Virginian had said to
the unknown mother of his sweetheart.

3576
03:05:05,121 --> 03:05:05,545
Mrs.

3577
03:05:05,545 --> 03:05:07,145
John Stark Wood,

3578
03:05:07,145 --> 03:05:09,603
Bennington, Vermont.

3579
03:05:09,603 --> 03:05:10,215
Madam:

3580
03:05:10,215 --> 03:05:14,099
If your daughter Miss Wood has ever told
you about her saving a man’s life here

3581
03:05:14,099 --> 03:05:19,256
when some Indians had shot him that is
the man who writes to you now.

3582
03:05:19,256 --> 03:05:22,970
I don’t think she can have told you right
about that affair for she is the only

3583
03:05:22,970 --> 03:05:25,411
one in this country who thinks it
was a little thing.

3584
03:05:25,411 --> 03:05:28,136
So I must tell you it, the main points.

3585
03:05:28,136 --> 03:05:31,509
Such an action would have been thought
highly of in a Western girl,

3586
03:05:31,509 --> 03:05:36,155
but with Miss Wood’s raising nobody had
a right to expect it.

3587
03:05:36,155 --> 03:05:37,086
“Indeed!”

3588
03:05:37,086 --> 03:05:38,853
snorted the great-aunt.

3589
03:05:38,853 --> 03:05:42,810
“Well, he would be right,
if I had not had a good deal more to do

3590
03:05:42,810 --> 03:05:45,260
with her ‘raising’ than ever Lizzie
had.”

3591
03:05:45,260 --> 03:05:46,971
And she went on with the letter.

3592
03:05:46,971 --> 03:05:50,893
I was starting in to die
when she found me.

3593
03:05:50,893 --> 03:05:54,473
I did not know anything then,
and she pulled me back from where I was

3594
03:05:54,473 --> 03:05:56,372
half in the next world.

3595
03:05:56,372 --> 03:06:00,976
She did not know but what Indians would
get her too but I could not

3596
03:06:00,976 --> 03:06:02,494
make her leave me.

3597
03:06:02,494 --> 03:06:07,128
I am a heavy man one hundred and seventy-
three stripped when in full health.

3598
03:06:07,128 --> 03:06:11,795
She lifted me herself from the ground me
helping scarce any for there was not

3599
03:06:11,795 --> 03:06:13,514
much help in me that day.

3600
03:06:13,514 --> 03:06:17,669
She washed my wound and brought me to
with her own whiskey.

3601
03:06:17,669 --> 03:06:21,309
Before she could get me home I was out of
my head but she kept me on my horse

3602
03:06:21,309 --> 03:06:26,252
somehow and talked wisely to me so I
minded her and did not go clean crazy

3603
03:06:26,252 --> 03:06:28,160
till she had got me safe to bed.

3604
03:06:28,160 --> 03:06:32,563
The doctor says I would have died all the
same if she had not nursed me

3605
03:06:32,563 --> 03:06:33,723
the way she did.

3606
03:06:33,723 --> 03:06:37,474
It made me love her more which I did
not know I could.

3607
03:06:37,474 --> 03:06:41,975
But there is no end, for this writing it
down makes me love her more

3608
03:06:41,975 --> 03:06:43,055
as I write it.

3609
03:06:43,055 --> 03:06:48,577
And now Mrs. Wood I am sorry this will be
bad news for you to hear.

3610
03:06:48,577 --> 03:06:52,535
I know you would never choose such a man
as I am for her for I have got no

3611
03:06:52,535 --> 03:06:55,824
education and must write
humble against my birth.

3612
03:06:55,824 --> 03:07:00,896
I wish I could make the news easier but
truth is the best.

3613
03:07:00,896 --> 03:07:02,936
I am of old stock in Virginia.

3614
03:07:02,936 --> 03:07:13,601
English and one Scotch Irish grandmother
my father’s father brought from

3615
03:07:13,601 --> 03:07:15,472
Kentucky.

3616
03:07:15,472 --> 03:07:21,778
We have always stayed at the same place
farmers and hunters not bettering our

3617
03:07:21,778 --> 03:07:23,759
lot and very plain.

3618
03:07:23,759 --> 03:07:28,380
We have fought when we got the chance,
under Old Hickory and in Mexico and my

3619
03:07:28,380 --> 03:07:32,716
father and two brothers were killed in
the Valley sixty-four.

3620
03:07:32,716 --> 03:07:38,595
Always with us one son has been apt to
run away and I was the one this time.

3621
03:07:38,595 --> 03:07:41,800
I had too much older brothering
to suit me.

3622
03:07:41,800 --> 03:07:47,078
But now I am doing well being in full
sight of prosperity and not too old and

3623
03:07:47,078 --> 03:07:53,171
very strong my health having stood the
sundries it has been put through.

3624
03:07:53,171 --> 03:07:56,376
She shall teach school no more
when she is mine.

3625
03:07:56,376 --> 03:08:01,210
I wish I could make this news easier
for you Mrs. Wood.

3626
03:08:01,210 --> 03:08:04,443
I do not like promises I
have heard so many.

3627
03:08:04,443 --> 03:08:08,582
I will tell any man of your family
anything he likes to ask one,

3628
03:08:08,582 --> 03:08:11,477
and Judge Henry would tell
you about my reputation.

3629
03:08:11,477 --> 03:08:17,300
I have seen plenty rough things but can
say I have never killed for pleasure or

3630
03:08:17,300 --> 03:08:23,003
profit and am not one of that
kind, always preferring peace.

3631
03:08:23,003 --> 03:08:27,083
I have had to live in places where they
had courts and lawyers so called but an

3632
03:08:27,083 --> 03:08:31,819
honest man was all the law you could
find in five hundred miles.

3633
03:08:31,819 --> 03:08:35,878
I have not told her about those things
not because I am ashamed of them but

3634
03:08:35,878 --> 03:08:39,605
there are so many things too dark for a
girl like her to hear about.

3635
03:08:39,605 --> 03:08:43,956
I had better tell you the way I know
I love Miss Wood.

3636
03:08:43,956 --> 03:08:47,884
I am not a boy now, and women are no
new thing to me.

3637
03:08:47,884 --> 03:08:53,543
A man like me who has travelled meets
many of them as he goes and passes on

3638
03:08:53,543 --> 03:08:55,935
but I stopped when I came to Miss Wood.

3639
03:08:55,935 --> 03:08:59,660
That is three years but I
have not gone on.

3640
03:08:59,660 --> 03:09:01,361
What right has such as he?

3641
03:09:01,361 --> 03:09:02,458
you will say.

3642
03:09:02,458 --> 03:09:06,740
So did I say it after she
had saved my life.

3643
03:09:06,740 --> 03:09:10,632
It was hard to get to that point and keep
there with her around me all day.

3644
03:09:10,632 --> 03:09:15,020
But I said to myself you have bothered
her for three years with your love and

3645
03:09:15,020 --> 03:09:19,893
if you let your love bother her you
don’t love her like you should and you

3646
03:09:19,893 --> 03:09:23,237
must quit for her sake who
has saved your life.

3647
03:09:23,237 --> 03:09:27,455
I did not know what I was going to do
with my life after that but I supposed I

3648
03:09:27,455 --> 03:09:32,286
could go somewhere and work hard and so
Mrs. Wood I told her I would give her

3649
03:09:32,286 --> 03:09:32,703
up.

3650
03:09:32,703 --> 03:09:34,726
But she said no.

3651
03:09:34,726 --> 03:09:39,206
It is going to be hard for her to get
used to a man like me⁠—

3652
03:09:39,206 --> 03:09:43,799
But at this point in the Virginian’s
letter, the old great-aunt

3653
03:09:43,799 --> 03:09:44,963
could read no more.

3654
03:09:44,963 --> 03:09:49,589
She rose, and went over to that desk
where lay those faded letters of her

3655
03:09:49,589 --> 03:09:50,165
own.

3656
03:09:50,165 --> 03:09:55,309
She laid her head down upon the package,
and as her tears flowed quietly upon it,

3657
03:09:55,309 --> 03:09:57,788
“O dear,” she whispered, “O dear!

3658
03:09:57,788 --> 03:10:00,478
And this is what I lost!”

3659
03:10:00,478 --> 03:10:04,517
To her girl upon Bear Creek she
wrote the next day.

3660
03:10:04,517 --> 03:10:07,986
And this word from Dunbarton was like
balm among the harsh

3661
03:10:07,986 --> 03:10:11,380
stings Molly was receiving.

3662
03:10:11,380 --> 03:10:19,070
The voices of the world reached her in
gathering numbers, and not one of them

3663
03:10:19,070 --> 03:10:21,990
save that great-aunt’s was sweet.

3664
03:10:21,990 --> 03:10:25,149
Her days were full of hurts;
and there was no one by to

3665
03:10:25,149 --> 03:10:26,421
kiss the hurts away.

3666
03:10:26,421 --> 03:10:30,423
Nor did she even hear from her
lover any more now.

3667
03:10:30,423 --> 03:10:34,764
She only knew he had gone into lonely
regions upon his errand.

3668
03:10:34,764 --> 03:10:36,872
That errand took him far:⁠—

3669
03:10:36,872 --> 03:10:44,244
Across the Basin, among the secret places
of Owl Creek, past the Washakie Needles,

3670
03:10:44,244 --> 03:10:49,779
over the Divide to Gros Ventre,
and so through a final barrier of peaks

3671
03:10:49,779 --> 03:10:52,766
into the borders of East Idaho.

3672
03:10:52,766 --> 03:10:57,402
There, by reason of his bidding me,
I met him, and came to share in a

3673
03:10:57,402 --> 03:10:59,432
part of his errand.

3674
03:10:59,432 --> 03:11:02,286
It was with no guide that
I travelled to him.

3675
03:11:02,286 --> 03:11:06,552
He had named a little station on the
railroad, and from thence he had charted

3676
03:11:06,552 --> 03:11:09,005
my route by means of landmarks.

3677
03:11:09,005 --> 03:11:12,474
Did I believe in omens,
the black storm that I set out in upon

3678
03:11:12,474 --> 03:11:14,994
my horse would seem like one today.

3679
03:11:14,994 --> 03:11:21,139
But I had been living in cities and
smoke; and Idaho, even with rain,

3680
03:11:21,139 --> 03:11:22,843
was delightful to me.

3681
03:11:22,843 --> 03:11:24,228
